{"title_page": "Old Court House Recreation Ground", "text_new": "[[File:Old Court House Recreation Ground 04.JPG|thumbnail|Old Court House Recreation Ground]]\n'''Old Court House Recreation Ground''' is a public park in [[High Barnet]] in the [[London Borough of Barnet]]. It is one of the borough's ''Premier Parks'' and received a [[Green Flag Award]] for 2009\u20132010.<ref name = \"Barnet\">[http://www.barnet.gov.uk/index/environment-planning/parks-and-open-spaces/premier-parks/old-court-house-park.htm London Borough of Barnet, Old Court House]</ref>\n\nThe park has six free tennis courts, a bowling green with a pavilion, a children's playground, a caf\u00e9 and a car park (off Manor Close). It has formal gardens, grassed areas, rockeries, and a tree trail. Some of the trees are from California, such as a [[Monterey pine]] and a [[Picea breweriana|Brewer's weeping spruce]], planted in the nineteenth century.<ref>Noticeboards in the park</ref>\n\n==Conservation areas==\n\nA refurbishment plan carried out since 2007 included the introduction of three conservation areas. The Orchard Conservation Area was formerly an orchard and some fruit trees survive. Old varieties of fruit trees have also been planted and some parts, which were formerly mown short, are now managed for a variety of flowers and herbs. The Bungalow Conservation Area was formerly the park keeper's lodge. It has now been cleared and is managed for nature conservation studies by local schools. A former tennis court has been dug up and left to develop its own wildlife as the Old Disused Tennis Court Conservation Area.<ref>Noticeboards in the park</ref>\n\n==History==\n\nThe park is named after a county court adjacent to the site which was held until the First World War.<ref name = \"Barnet\"/> In the nineteenth century, the land was owned by the Rumball family and leased as pasture, a brewery and stables. In 1912 the brewery site was purchased by [[Barnet Urban District|Barnet Urban District Council]], and in 1923 the council purchased the Old Court House estate. The park was opened in 1926.<ref name = \"LGO\">[http://www.londongardensonline.org.uk/gardens-online-record.asp?ID=BAR059 London Gardens Online, Old Court House Recreation Ground]</ref>\n\n==Access==\n\nThe park is open from 8 a.m. until dusk.<ref name = \"LGO\"/> There is access from Wood Street, Manor Close, Mays Lane and Orchard Road.\n\n==Gallery==\n\n<gallery perrow = \"6\">\nFile:Old Court House flowerbeds.jpg|Formal flowerbeds\nFile:Old Court House pond.jpg|Pond\nFile:Old Court House rockery.jpg|Rockery\nFile:Old Court House path.jpg|Path\nFile:Old Court House playground.jpg|Playground\nFile:Old Court House paths.jpg|Junction\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n\n* [[Barnet parks and open spaces]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|Old Court House Recreation Ground}}\n* [http://www.londongardensonline.org.uk/gardens-online-record.asp?ID=BAR059 London Gardens Online, Old Court House Recreation Ground]\n* [http://www.kidsfunlondon.co.uk/kids-london/park/old-court-house.html Kids Fun London, Old Court House]\n* [http://www.barnet.gov.uk/index/environment-planning/parks-and-open-spaces/premier-parks/old-court-house-park.htm London Borough of Barnet, Old Court House]\n\n{{coord|51.6517|-0.2028|type:landmark_region:GB|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Parks and open spaces in the London Borough of Barnet]]\n[[Category:Chipping Barnet]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Old Court House Recreation Ground 04.JPG|thumbnail|Old Court House Recreation Ground]]\n'''Old Court House Recreation Ground''' is a public park in [[High Barnet]] in the [[London Borough of Barnet]]. It is one of the borough's ''Premier Parks'' and received a [[Green Flag Award]] for 2009-2010.<ref name = \"Barnet\">[http://www.barnet.gov.uk/index/environment-planning/parks-and-open-spaces/premier-parks/old-court-house-park.htm London Borough of Barnet, Old Court House]</ref>\n\nThe park has six free tennis courts, a bowling green with a pavilion, a children's playground, a caf\u00e9 and a car park (off Manor Close). It has formal gardens, grassed areas, rockeries, and a tree trail. Some of the trees are from California, such as a [[Monterey pine]] and a [[Picea breweriana|Brewer's weeping spruce]], planted in the nineteenth century.<ref>Noticeboards in the park</ref>\n\n==Conservation areas==\n\nA refurbishment plan carried out since 2007 included the introduction of three conservation areas. The Orchard Conservation Area was formerly an orchard and some fruit trees survive. Old varieties of fruit trees have also been planted and some parts, which were formerly mown short, are now managed for a variety of flowers and herbs. The Bungalow Conservation Area was formerly the park keeper's lodge. It has now been cleared and is managed for nature conservation studies by local schools. A former tennis court has been dug up and left to develop its own wildlife as the Old Disused Tennis Court Conservation Area.<ref>Noticeboards in the park</ref>\n\n==History==\n\nThe park is named after a county court adjacent to the site which was held until the First World War.<ref name = \"Barnet\"/> In the nineteenth century, the land was owned by the Rumball family and leased as pasture, a brewery and stables. In 1912 the brewery site was purchased by [[Barnet Urban District|Barnet Urban District Council]], and in 1923 the council purchased the Old Court House estate. The park was opened in 1926.<ref name = \"LGO\">[http://www.londongardensonline.org.uk/gardens-online-record.asp?ID=BAR059 London Gardens Online, Old Court House Recreation Ground]</ref>\n\n==Access==\n\nThe park is open from 8 a.m. until dusk.<ref name = \"LGO\"/> There is access from Wood Street, Manor Close, Mays Lane and Orchard Road.\n\n==Gallery==\n\n<gallery perrow = \"6\">\nFile:Old Court House flowerbeds.jpg|Formal flowerbeds\nFile:Old Court House pond.jpg|Pond\nFile:Old Court House rockery.jpg|Rockery\nFile:Old Court House path.jpg|Path\nFile:Old Court House playground.jpg|Playground\nFile:Old Court House paths.jpg|Junction\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n\n* [[Barnet parks and open spaces]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|Old Court House Recreation Ground}}\n* [http://www.londongardensonline.org.uk/gardens-online-record.asp?ID=BAR059 London Gardens Online, Old Court House Recreation Ground]\n* [http://www.kidsfunlondon.co.uk/kids-london/park/old-court-house.html Kids Fun London, Old Court House]\n* [http://www.barnet.gov.uk/index/environment-planning/parks-and-open-spaces/premier-parks/old-court-house-park.htm London Borough of Barnet, Old Court House]\n\n{{coord|51.6517|-0.2028|type:landmark_region:GB|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Parks and open spaces in the London Borough of Barnet]]\n[[Category:Chipping Barnet]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 2009-2010 \u2192 2009\u20132010", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Old_Court_House_Recreation_Ground"}
{"title_page": "Michael Peterson (criminal)", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2018}}\n{{Infobox NOVELIST <!-- Please see discussion on talk page pertaining to the usage of this template. Removal of template with no explanation or discussion will most likely result in your edit being reverted. -->\n |name               = Michael Peterson\n |birth_name         = Michael Iver Peterson\n |birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1943|10|23}}\n |birth_place        = [[Nashville, Tennessee]], U.S.\n |occupation         = {{hlist|Marine Corps officer|novelist}}\n |spouse             = {{plainlist|\n* {{marriage|Patricia Sue Peterson|1965|1987|reason=divorced}}\n* {{marriage|Kathleen Peterson|1997|2001|reason=died}}}}\n |children           = 5\n |conviction         = [[Murder]], later reduced to voluntary [[manslaughter]]\n |conviction_penalty = [[Life imprisonment|Life imprisonment without parole]], later reduced to 86&nbsp;months imprisonment (actual [[time served]] was 98.5&nbsp;months)\n}}\n\n'''Michael Iver Peterson''' (born October 23, 1943) is an American [[novelist]] who was convicted in 2003 of [[murder]]ing his second wife, Kathleen Peterson, on December&nbsp;9, 2001. After eight years, Peterson was granted a new trial after the judge ruled a critical prosecution witness gave misleading testimony.<ref name=\"ABC121511\">{{cite news|title= Novelist Michael Peterson, Convicted of Wife's Murder, Is Released From Prison and Will Get New Trial|publisher= [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]|year= 2011|accessdate= December 17, 2011|url= http://abcnews.go.com/blogs/headlines/2011/12/novelist-michael-peterson-convicted-of-wifes-murder-is-released-from-prison-and-will-get-new-trial/|url-status= live|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20111216082633/http://abcnews.go.com/blogs/headlines/2011/12/novelist-michael-peterson-convicted-of-wifes-murder-is-released-from-prison-and-will-get-new-trial/|archivedate= December 16, 2011|df= mdy-all}}</ref> This second trial had been scheduled to begin on May&nbsp;8, 2017.<ref name=\"abc11.com\">{{cite web |url=http://abc11.com/news/judge-rules-peterson-will-stand-trial-in-murder-case/1605864/ |title=Judge rules Michael Peterson will stand trial in murder case |date=November 14, 2016 |accessdate=December 4, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161115135917/http://abc11.com/news/judge-rules-peterson-will-stand-trial-in-murder-case/1605864/ |archivedate=November 15, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn February&nbsp;24, 2017, Peterson submitted an [[Alford plea]] to the reduced charge of [[manslaughter]]. He was sentenced to [[time served|time already served]] and freed. Peterson's case is the subject of the documentary miniseries ''[[The Staircase]]'', which started filming soon after his arrest in 2001 and followed events until his eventual [[Alford plea]] in 2017. In 2019, he released his own account of his life since his wife Kathleen's death in an independently published memoir, ''Behind the Staircase''.<ref name=\"Ch Observer\">{{cite web |last1=Cain |first1=Brooke |title=Hollywood just can\u2019t seem to get enough of the Michael Peterson \u2018Staircase\u2019 story  |url=https://www.charlotteobserver.com/entertainment/tv/article212767324.html |website=www.charlotteobserver.com |publisher=The Charlotte Observer |accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Personal and professional life==\nMichael \"Mike\" Peterson was born near [[Nashville, Tennessee]], the son of Eugen Iver Peterson and Eleanor Peterson ({{nee|Bartolino}}). He graduated from [[Duke University]] with a [[bachelor's degree]] in [[political science]]. While there, he was president of [[Sigma Nu]] fraternity and was<!--source supports this much--> editor of [[The Chronicle (Duke University)|''The Chronicle'']], the daily student newspaper, from 1964\u20131965.<ref name=\"papers\" /> He attended classes at the law school of the [[University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill]].\n\nAfter graduating, Peterson took a civilian job with the [[United States Department of Defense|U.S. Department of Defense]], where he was assigned to research arguments supporting increased military involvement in [[Vietnam]]. That year he also married Patricia Sue<!--Maiden name? Peterson is her married name -->, who taught at an elementary school on the [[Rhein-Main Air Base]] in Gr\u00e4fenhausen, [[West Germany]]. They had two children, Clayton and Todd.\n\nIn 1968, Peterson enlisted in the [[United States Marine Corps]] and served in [[Vietnam War|Vietnam]]. In 1971, he received an honorable discharge with the rank of captain after a car accident left him with a permanent disability. Years later, during [[1999 Durham mayoral election|a mayoral campaign]], Peterson claimed he had won a [[Silver Star]], a [[Bronze Star Medal|Bronze Star]] With Valor, and two [[Purple Heart]]s. He had all the medals, but said he did not have the documentation for them. He claimed he had received one Purple Heart after being hit by shrapnel when another soldier stepped on a land mine, and the other when he was shot. Peterson later admitted his war injury was not the result of the shrapnel wound in Vietnam, but was the result of a vehicle accident in Japan, where he was stationed after the war as a military policeman.<ref name=\"Dline\" /> The ''[[News & Observer]]'' said records did not contain any mention of the two Purple Heart medals that Peterson said he had received. However, military files verified that he received a Silver Star and the Bronze Star Medal with Valor.<ref>Kane, Dan.  [https://www.newsobserver.com/news/local/counties/durham-county/article213595444.html \"Durham mayoral candidate Michael Peterson fabricated war injury, admits falsehood\"], ''[[The News & Observer]]'' website, 18 September 1999. Updated 21 June 2018. Retrieved 1 March 2019.</ref>\n\nMichael and Patricia lived in Germany for some time. There they befriended Elizabeth and George Ratliff and their two children, Margaret and Martha. After George's death, the Peterson and Ratliff families became very close. When Elizabeth Ratliff died in 1985, Michael became the guardian of her two children. After Michael and Patricia divorced in 1987, Clayton and Todd lived with Patricia, and Margaret and Martha stayed with Michael, who then moved to [[Durham, North Carolina]]. Clayton and Todd later also joined their father.\n\nPeterson wrote three novels based \"around his experiences during the Vietnamese conflict\"<ref name=\"papers\" />\u2014''The Immortal Dragon'', ''A Time of War'', and ''A Bitter Peace''.<!--see TALK--> He co-wrote the biographical ''Charlie Two Shoes and the Marines of Love Company'' with journalist David Perlmutt, and co-wrote ''Operation Broken Reed'' with Lt. Col. Arthur L. Boyd. He also worked as a newspaper columnist for the ''[[The Herald-Sun (Durham, North Carolina)|Durham Herald-Sun]]'', where his columns became known for their criticism of police and Durham County District Attorney James Hardin Jr. Hardin was the prosecutor of Peterson for the murder of his second wife, Kathleen.\n\nIn 1989, Michael moved in with Kathleen Atwater, a successful [[Nortel]] business executive. They married in 1997, and Kathleen's daughter Caitlin joined the extended family that now consisted of Clayton, Todd, Martha, and Margaret.<ref name=\"Court TV 1\">{{cite news|title= Wife's staircase death at center of novelist's murder trial|publisher= [[truTV|Court TV]]|year= 2001|accessdate= March 11, 2009|url= http://www.courttv.com/trials/novelist/background_ctv.html|url-status= dead|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090307224345/http://www.courttv.com/trials/novelist/background_ctv.html|archivedate= March 7, 2009|df= mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Murder trial==\n\n===Kathleen's death===\nOn December 9, 2001, Peterson called an emergency line to report that he had just found Kathleen unconscious in their [[Forest Hills Historic District (Durham, North Carolina)|Forest Hills]] mansion and suspected she had fallen down \"15, 20, I don't know\" stairs. He later claimed that he had been outside by the pool and had come in at 2:40&nbsp;am to find Kathleen at the foot of the stairs. He said she must have fallen down the stairs after consuming alcohol and [[Valium]].\n\nToxicology results showed that his wife's [[blood alcohol content]] was 0.07 percent (70&nbsp;mg/100mL). The [[autopsy]] report concluded that the 48-year-old woman sustained a matrix of severe injuries, including a fracture of the [[Thyroid cartilage|thyroid neck cartilage]] and seven lacerations to the top and back of her head, consistent with blows from a blunt object, and had died from blood loss 90 minutes to two hours after sustaining the injuries.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.autopsyfiles.org/reports/Other/peterson,%20kathleen_report.pdf|title=Kathleen Peterson Autopsy Report}}</ref> Kathleen's daughter, Caitlin, and Kathleen's sister, Candace Zamperini, both initially proclaimed Michael's innocence and publicly supported him alongside his children, but Zamperini reconsidered after learning of Peterson's [[bisexuality]], as did Caitlin after reading her mother's autopsy report. Both subsequently broke off from the rest of the family.\n\nAlthough forensic expert [[Henry Lee (forensic scientist)|Henry Lee]], hired by the defense, testified that the [[Bloodstain pattern analysis|blood-spatter evidence]] was consistent with an accidental fall down the stairs, police investigators concluded that the injuries were inconsistent with such an accident. As Michael Peterson was the only person at the residence at the time of Kathleen's death, he was the prime suspect and was soon charged with her murder. He pleaded not guilty.\n\nThe medical examiner, Deborah Radisch, concluded that Kathleen had died from lacerations of the scalp caused by a homicidal assault. According to Radisch, the total of seven lacerations to the top and back of Kathleen's head were the result of repeated blows with a light, yet rigid, weapon. The defense disputed this theory. According to their analysis, Kathleen's skull had not been fractured by the blows, nor was she brain damaged, which was inconsistent with injuries sustained in a beating death.\n\nThe trial drew increasing media attention as details of Michael's private life emerged. Durham County District Attorney James Hardin, Jr. and the prosecutors (among them former District Attorney [[Mike Nifong]]) attacked Peterson's credibility, focusing on his alleged misreporting of his military service and what they described as a \"gay life\" he led and kept secret. The prosecution contended that the Petersons' marriage was far from happy, suggesting that Kathleen had discovered Michael's alleged secret \"gay life\" and wanted to end their marriage. It was the main motive that the prosecution offered at trial for Kathleen's alleged murder (the other being a $1.5 million life insurance policy). According to Assistant District Attorney Freda Black, Kathleen\n\n<blockquote>would have been infuriated by learning that her husband, who she truly loved, was bi-sexual and having an extramarital relationship\u2014not with another woman\u2014but a man, which would have been humiliating and embarrassing to her. We believe that once she learned this information that an argument ensued and a homicide occurred.</blockquote>\n\nThe defense argued that Kathleen accepted Michael's bisexuality and that the marriage was very happy, a position supported by Michael and Kathleen's children and other friends and associates.<ref name=\"Court TV 1\" />\n\nThe prosecution said that the murder was most likely committed with a custom-made [[fireplace poker]] called a blow poke. It had been a gift to the Petersons from Kathleen's sister but was missing from the house at the time of the murder investigation. Late in the trial the defense team produced the missing blow poke, which they said had been overlooked in the garage by police investigators. Forensic tests revealed that it had been untouched and unmoved for too long to have been used in the murder.{{citation needed|date=June 2018}} <!-- doesn't Rudolf claim detectives moved and photographed the blowpoke? --> A juror contacted after the trial noted that the jury dismissed the idea of the blow poke as the murder weapon.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.courttv.com/trials/novelist/guilty_ctv.html |title=Novelist convicted of first-degree murder in wife's staircase death |publisher=Courttv.com |accessdate=December 2, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090406033031/http://www.courttv.com/trials/novelist/guilty_ctv.html |archivedate=April 6, 2009  }}</ref>\n\n===Suspicion surrounding Elizabeth Ratliff's death===\nElizabeth Ratliff, the friend of the Petersons who died in Germany in 1985, had also been found dead at the foot of her staircase with injuries to the head. Her death had been investigated by both the German police and U.S. military police. An autopsy at the time of her death concluded she died from an [[Cerebrovascular accident|intra-cerebral haemorrhage]] secondary to the blood coagulation disorder [[Von Willebrand's disease]], based on blood in her cerebrospinal fluid and reports that she had been suffering severe, persistent headaches in the weeks leading up to her death. The coroner determined that the hemorrhage resulted in immediate death followed by Ratliff falling down the stairs after collapsing. The Petersons had dinner with Ratliff and her daughters, and Peterson had stayed and helped Ratliff put the children to bed before going home. The children's nanny, Barbara, discovered the body when she arrived the next morning. Peterson was the last known person to see her alive.\n\nBefore Peterson's trial, the Durham court ordered the exhumation of Ratliff's [[embalm]]ed body, buried in Texas, for a second autopsy in April 2003.<ref name=\"Herald28803\">Herald-Journal \u2013 August 28, 2003 [https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=_2FhAAAAIBAJ&sjid=Y9AEAAAAIBAJ&pg=6609%2C5088116 Prosecutors Try to Link Two Deaths] Retrieved February 2015</ref>  Arrangements were made for the Durham medical examiner/[[pathologist]] who had initially performed Kathleen Peterson's autopsy, to perform this reevaluation, over the objections of defense counsel who argued that the autopsy should be performed by Texas medical examiners. The body was then transported from Texas to Durham. The Durham M.E. found sufficient evidence drawn from the results of the second autopsy, along with new witness statements describing the scene,<ref name=\"Herald28803\" /> to overturn the earlier findings and list Ratliff's cause of death as \"homicide\".\n\nThe prosecution declined to accuse Peterson of Ratliff's death, but introduced the death into the trial as an incident giving Peterson the idea of how to \"fake\" Kathleen's accident. Despite police reports that there was very little blood at the scene of Ratliff's death, the nanny, who was the first to discover Ratliff's body in 1985, took the stand at Peterson's trial and testified that there was a large amount of blood at the scene. Another witness testified to spending much of the day cleaning blood stains off the wall.\n\nThe admissibility of the Ratliff evidence in court was one of the grounds for the subsequent appeal against his conviction, lodged by Peterson's lawyers in 2005.\n\nIn October 2002, acting as [[Administrator (law)|administrator]] of Kathleen's [[Estate (law)|estate]], Caitlin filed a [[wrongful death claim]] against Michael. In June 2006, he voluntarily filed for [[bankruptcy]]. Two weeks later, Caitlin filed an objection to the bankruptcy. On February 1, 2007, Caitlin and Michael settled the wrongful death claim for $25 million, pending acceptance by the courts involved; finalization of the settlement by the court was announced on February 1, 2008. In the settlement, Michael did not admit that he murdered Kathleen.{{cn|date=February 2020}}\n\n===Verdict===\nOn October 10, 2003, after one of the longest trials in North Carolina history, a [[Durham County, North Carolina|Durham County]] jury found Michael Peterson guilty of the murder of Kathleen Peterson,<ref>The Dispatch \u2013 October 9, 2003 [https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=1PIbAAAAIBAJ&sjid=DVMEAAAAIBAJ&pg=5792%2C3458204 Novelist Peterson Convicted] Retrieved February 2015</ref> and he was sentenced to life in prison without the possibility of parole.<ref>The Item \u2013 October 10, 2003 [https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=_J0iAAAAIBAJ&sjid=M68FAAAAIBAJ&pg=1245%2C1428450 Novelist Convicted of Beating Wife to Death] Retrieved February 2015</ref> Denial of parole requires premeditation. Despite the jury accepting the murder was a \"spur-of-the-moment\" crime, they also found it was premeditated. As one juror explained it, premeditated meant not only planning hours or days ahead, but could also mean planning in the seconds before committing a spur-of-the-moment crime.\n\nPeterson was housed at the Nash Correctional Institution near [[Rocky Mount, North Carolina|Rocky Mount]] until he was released on December 16, 2011.\n\n===Appeal===\nPeterson's appeal was filed by his defense counsel, Thomas Maher, now serving as his court-appointed attorney, and was argued before the [[North Carolina Court of Appeals]] on April 18, 2006. On September 19, 2006, the Court of Appeals rejected Peterson's arguments that he did not get a fair trial because of repeated judicial mistakes.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.vanceholmes.com/court/peterson_appeal2.html |title=Defendant\u2013Appellants Brief |publisher=Vanceholmes.com |accessdate=December 2, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120316100125/http://www.vanceholmes.com/court/peterson_appeal2.html |archivedate=March 16, 2012  }}</ref> The Appeals' ruling said the evidence was fairly admitted. The judges did find defects in a search warrant, but said they had no ill effect on the defense.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.aoc.state.nc.us/www/public/sc/opinions/2007/547-06-1.htm |title=State v. Peterson |publisher=Aoc.state.nc.us |accessdate=December 2, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203035409/http://www.aoc.state.nc.us/www/public/sc/opinions/2007/547-06-1.htm |archivedate=December 3, 2013  }}</ref><ref>The Times-News \u2013 September 20, 2006 [https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=wms0AAAAIBAJ&sjid=BSYEAAAAIBAJ&pg=3379%2C4839920 Appeals Court won't overturn decision] Retrieved February 2015</ref> Because the Court of Appeals' ruling was not unanimous, under North Carolina law, Peterson had right to appeal to the [[North Carolina Supreme Court]], which accepted the case. Oral argument was heard on September 10, 2007. On November 9, 2007, the Court announced that it affirmed the decision of the Court of Appeals. Absent a reconsideration of the ruling or the raising of a [[United States federal courts|federal]] issue, Peterson had exhausted his appeal of the verdict.\n\nOn November 12, 2008, J. Burkhardt Beale and Jason Anthony, [[Richmond, Virginia]] attorneys, who were now representing Peterson, filed a [[Motion (legal)#Motion for new trial|motion for a new trial]] in Durham County court on three grounds: that the prosecution withheld [[exculpatory evidence]] about a blow poke, that the prosecution used an [[expert witness]] whose qualifications were disputed, and that one juror based his judgment on racial factors. On March 10, 2009, Peterson's motion was denied by the Durham County Superior Court.\n\n===Owl theory===\n{{refimprove section|date=March 2020}}\n{{Original research|section|date=March 2020}} \nIn late 2009, a new theory of Kathleen Peterson's death was raised: that she had been attacked by an [[owl]] outside, fallen after rushing inside, and been knocked unconscious after hitting her head on the first tread of the stairs. The owl theory was raised by Durham attorney T. Lawrence Pollard, a neighbor of the Petersons who was not involved in the case but had been following the public details. He approached the police suggesting an owl might have been responsible after reading the [[North Carolina State Bureau of Investigation]] evidence list and finding a \"feather\" listed. Peterson's attorneys had determined that the SBI crime lab report listed a microscopic owl feather and a wooden sliver from a tree limb entangled in a clump of hair that had been pulled out by the roots found clutched in Kathleen's left hand.<ref>[http://owltheory.blog.lemonde.fr/2008/09/05/feathers-flying-in-michael-peterson-case-by-bernie-reeves/ Feathers flying in Michael Peterson case] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110426055501/http://owltheory.blog.lemonde.fr/2008/09/05/feathers-flying-in-michael-peterson-case-by-bernie-reeves/ |date=April 26, 2011 }} [[le Monde]] September 5, 2008</ref><ref name=\"Owl\">[http://www.newsobserver.com/2010/08/19/636421/three-experts-affidavits-support.html Three affidavits support Peterson's murderous owl theory] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101210095810/http://www.newsobserver.com/2010/08/19/636421/three-experts-affidavits-support.html |date=December 10, 2010 }} Durham County News Observer August 19, 2010</ref> A re-examination of the hair in September 2008 had found two more microscopic owl feathers.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://thisiscriminal.com/episode-one-animal-instincts-1-31-2014-2/ |title=Episode 1: Animal Instincts (1.31.2014) |accessdate=January 8, 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150110024809/http://thisiscriminal.com/episode-one-animal-instincts-1-31-2014-2/ |archivedate=January 10, 2015  }}</ref>\n\nAlthough Pollard did not speak of the theory to anyone else,{{citation needed|date=March 2020}} ''The'' ''Durham Herald-Sun'' published an article ridiculing him, and discrediting his theory.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}} Other media picked it up, propagating the ''Herald-Sun'' story, which was later criticized as inaccurate.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\nAdvocates of this theory{{who?|date=March 2020}} assert that other evidence supports it, namely: the scalp wounds were tri-lobed and paired, consistent with marks left by talons,{{citation needed|date=March 2020}} the feathers are similar to those on owl feet,{{citation needed|date=March 2020}} cedar needles were found on her hands and body indicating Kathleen had fallen over outside shortly before entering the house, that her blood had spattered up the staircase rather than down, that her footprints in her own blood indicated that she was already bleeding before she reached the foot of the stairs, and that two drops of her blood were found outside the house on the front walkway along with a finger smear on the front door consistent with her pushing the door shut. Advocates also note that owl attacks on people are common in the area,{{citation needed|date=March 2020}} with one victim{{who?|date=March 2020}} stating that the impact was similar to being hit in the head with a baseball bat.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\nAccording to Pollard, had a jury been presented with this evidence it would have \"materially affected their deliberation and therefore would have materially affected their ultimate verdict\". Prosecutors have ridiculed the claim, and Deborah Radisch, who conducted Kathleen Peterson's autopsy, says it is unlikely that an owl or any other bird could have made wounds as deep as those on her scalp. However, Radisch's opinion was challenged by other experts in three separate affidavits filed in 2010.   Alan van Norman wrote: \"The multiple wounds present suggest to me that an owl and Ms. Peterson somehow became entangled. Perhaps the owl got tangled in her hair or perhaps she grabbed the owl's foot.\"<ref name=\"Owl2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thedurhamnews.com/2010/08/25/203219/three-experts-back-owl-theory.html |title=Three experts back owl theory |accessdate=June 10, 2011 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100831081004/http://www.thedurhamnews.com/2010/08/25/203219/three-experts-back-owl-theory.html |archivedate=August 31, 2010 }} Stanley B. Chambers, Jr. ''The Durham News'' (thedurhamnews.com). August 25, 2010.</ref>\n\nPatrick T. Redig, a professor of [[veterinary medicine]] at the [[University of Minnesota]] wrote: \"In my professional opinion, the hypothesized attack to the face and back of the head resulting in the various punctures and lacerations visible in the autopsy photographs is entirely within the behavioral repertoire of large owls.\"<ref name=\"Owl2\" />\n\nKate P. Davis, executive director of Raptors of the Rockies, a western Montana education and wildlife rehabilitation project, wrote:\nThe lacerations on Mrs. Peterson's scalp look very much like those made by a [[bird of prey|raptor]]'s talons, especially if she had forcibly torn the bird from the back of her head. That would explain the feathers found in her hand and the many hairs pulled out by the root, broken or cut. The size and configuration of the lacerations could certainly indicate the feet of a [[barred owl]].<ref name=\"Owl2\" /> Davis further noted that owls can kill species much larger than themselves and that it is not uncommon for them to attack people.<ref name=\"Owl2\" />\n\nDespite interest in this theory among some outside advocates, no motion for a new trial was filed on this point in 2009.<ref>[http://www.wral.com/news/local/story/5726608/ Attorney wants owl theory reconsidered in Peterson murder case] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100316085507/http://www.wral.com/news/local/story/5726608/ |date=March 16, 2010 }} [[WRAL-TV]] August 11, 2009</ref><ref>[http://owltheory.blog.lemonde.fr/2008/09/04/evidence-points-to-owl-in-peterson-case/ Evidence points to owl in Peterson case] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110129014541/http://owltheory.blog.lemonde.fr/2008/09/04/evidence-points-to-owl-in-peterson-case/ |date=January 29, 2011 }} ''[[Le Monde]]'' September 4, 2008</ref>\n\nOn March 2, 2017 (following his Alford plea), Mr. Peterson's attorney filed a motion to allow him to pay for a bird expert at the [[Smithsonian Institution]] to examine feather fragments found in Kathleen Peterson's hair to determine if she was attacked by a raptor.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wwwcache.wral.com/asset/news/local/2017/03/13/16582208/20170313112617080.pdf|title=North Carolina vs Michael Peterson - Motion for order allowing transport of microslide to expert for inspection and testing|access-date=August 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Retrial hearing===\nIn August 2010, following a series of newspaper articles critical of the investigative tactics of State Bureau of Investigation agents, Attorney General [[Roy Cooper]] led an investigation, which resulted in the suspension of SBI analyst Duane Deaver, one of the principal witnesses against Peterson, after the report found his work among the worst done on scores of flawed criminal cases. T. Lawrence Pollard subsequently filed affidavits<ref>Neurosurgeon and owl expert   Alan van Norman,   Patrick T. Redig, a professor of veterinary medicine at the University of Minnesota, and Kate P. Davis, the director of Raptors of the Rockies, signed affidavits claiming that the evidence and injuries are consistent with an attack by an owl, possibly a [[barred owl]].</ref> to support a motion that Superior Court Judge Orlando Hudson order the state Medical Examiner's Office to turn over all documentation related to Kathleen Peterson's autopsy to Peterson's attorneys. However, Judge Hudson barred Pollard from filing further motions on behalf of Peterson because Pollard did not represent him. A new motion was filed in August 2010 by David Rudolf, one of Peterson's original attorneys who acted [[pro bono]] in proceedings challenging the SBI testimony.<ref name=\"Owl\" /><ref>[http://abclocal.go.com/wtvd/story?section=news/local&id=7619462 Michael Peterson impacted by SBI report?] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110628224744/http://abclocal.go.com/wtvd/story?section=news%2Flocal&id=7619462 |date=June 28, 2011 }} [[ABC News]] August 20, 2010</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=James |first=Jesse |url=http://www.newsobserver.com/2010/08/27/651015/attorney-forbidden-from-filing.html |title=DURHAM: Attorney forbidden from filing Michael Peterson motions &#124; Crime |publisher=NewsObserver.com |date=August 27, 2010 |accessdate=December 2, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131207105441/http://www.newsobserver.com/2010/08/27/651015/attorney-forbidden-from-filing.html |archivedate=December 7, 2013  }}</ref>\n\nDeaver was fired from the SBI in January 2011, after an independent audit of the agency found he had falsely represented evidence in 34 cases, including withholding negative results in the case of Greg Taylor, a North Carolina man who spent 17 years in prison on a murder conviction based on Deaver's testimony.<ref>Troubled SBI agent Duane Deaver fired. {{cite web |url=http://www.newsobserver.com/2011/01/10/911881/troubled-sbi-agent-duane-deaver.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=December 16, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110817013820/http://www.newsobserver.com/2011/01/10/911881/troubled-sbi-agent-duane-deaver.html |archivedate=August 17, 2011  }}</ref> A bloodstain-analysis team that Deaver had trained was suspended and disbanded. In the 2003 Peterson trial, Deaver testified that he had been mentored by SBI bloodstain specialist David Spittle, had worked 500 bloodstain cases, written 200 reports, and testified in 60 cases. During the retrial hearing, SBI Assistant Director Eric Hooks testified that Deaver had written only 47 reports. SBI agent David Spittle testified that he could not recall mentoring Deaver who, since completing a two-day training course in the 1980s, had testified in only four cases, the Peterson case being the third. The SBI cited the bloodstain analysis given in the fourth case as the reason for firing Deaver.<ref>[http://www.newsobserver.com/2011/12/07/1694717/sbi-says-deaver-exaggerated-expertise.html SBI says Deaver exaggerated expertise] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120110133848/http://www.newsobserver.com/2011/12/07/1694717/sbi-says-deaver-exaggerated-expertise.html |date=January 10, 2012 }} [[The News & Observer]] December 08, 2011</ref>\n\nOn December 16, 2011, Peterson was released from the Durham County jail on $300,000 bail and placed under house arrest with a tracking anklet. His release on bond followed a judicial order for a new trial after Judge Hudson found that SBI blood analyst Duane Deaver had given \"materially misleading\" and \"deliberately false\" testimony about bloodstain evidence, and had exaggerated his training, experience, and expertise.<ref>[http://www.newsobserver.com/2012/08/10/2260545/judge-says-peterson-must-keep.html Judge says Peterson must keep wearing ankle bracelet] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120812024815/http://www.newsobserver.com/2012/08/10/2260545/judge-says-peterson-must-keep.html |date=August 12, 2012 }} News Observer August 10, 2012</ref><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20120214125030/http://www.news-record.com/content/2011/12/16/article/durham_novelist_peterson_walks_out_of_jail_awaits_new_murder_trial Durham novelist Peterson walks out of jail; awaits new murder trial. ]</ref><ref>[https://archive.today/20120904052941/http://www.newsobserver.com/2011/12/09/1699177/defense-dissects-deavers-methods.html?tab=gallery&gallery=/2011/12/07/1696640/michael-peterson-hearing-continues.html&gid_index=3 Peterson defense dissects Deaver's methods] [[The News & Observer]] December 9, 2011</ref> Former North Carolina Attorney General [[Rufus L. Edmisten|Rufus Edmisten]] said that any evidence gathered after Deaver arrived at the scene might be deemed inadmissible in a new trial.<ref>[http://www2.nbc17.com/news/durham-county/2011/dec/16/former-nc-ag-says-it-will-be-harder-state-convict--ar-1723556/ Former NC AG says it will be harder for the State to convict Peterson in retrial] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120114154436/http://www2.nbc17.com/news/durham-county/2011/dec/16/former-nc-ag-says-it-will-be-harder-state-convict--ar-1723556/ |date=January 14, 2012 }} [[NBC]] December 17, 2011</ref>\n\nIn July 2014, Peterson's bond restrictions were eased.<ref>{{Cite web|title = DA: Peterson's new trial months away|url = http://www.heraldsun.com/news/localnews/x761901796/DA-Peterson-s-new-trial-months-away|accessdate = May 6, 2015|url-status = dead|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150508085109/http://www.heraldsun.com/news/localnews/x761901796/DA-Peterson-s-new-trial-months-away|archivedate = May 8, 2015|df = mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2014, the court appointed Mike Klinkosum to represent Peterson, replacing David Rudolf, who had been working pro bono on the case since Peterson's conviction was overturned. Rudolf had stated that he could no longer afford to represent Peterson without being paid.<ref>{{Cite news|url =http://www.wral.com/mike-peterson-gets-new-attorney-for-second-murder-trial/14109012/|title =Mike Peterson gets new attorney for second murder trial|url-status =live|archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20141025033605/http://www.wral.com/mike-peterson-gets-new-attorney-for-second-murder-trial/14109012/|archivedate =October 25, 2014|df =mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn November 14, 2016, Peterson's request for the second trial to be dismissed was refused, and a new trial was scheduled to begin on May 8, 2017.<ref name=\"abc11.com\"/> However, a news report on February 7, 2017, indicated that a resolution had been negotiated by Rudolf (once again representing Peterson) and the Durham County DA.\n\n===Alford plea===\nOn February 24, 2017, Peterson entered an [[Alford plea]] (a guilty plea entered because sufficient evidence exists to convict him of the offense, but the defendant asserts innocence) to the voluntary manslaughter of Kathleen Peterson.<ref>{{cite news |last=Sims |first=Julia |last2=Crabtree |first2=Davis |url=http://www.wral.com/mike-peterson-walks-free-after-15-year-murder-case-ends-with-plea-deal/16546848/ |title=Mike Peterson walks free as 15-year murder case ends with plea deal |work=[[WRAL-TV]] |publisher=Capitol Broadcasting Company, Inc. |date=2017-02-24 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170225044044/http://www.wral.com/mike-peterson-walks-free-after-15-year-murder-case-ends-with-plea-deal/16546848/ |archivedate=2017-02-25 |accessdate=2018-07-16 }}</ref> The judge sentenced him to a maximum of 86 months in prison, with credit for time previously served. Because Peterson had already served more time than the sentence (98.5 months), he did not face additional prison time.\n\n==Media==\n\n===Films about the case===\nThe court case generated widespread interest in part because of a televised documentary series variously named ''[[Soup\u00e7ons]]'' (Suspicions), ''Death on the Staircase'', and ''The Staircase'', which detailed Peterson's legal and personal troubles. Eight 45-minute episodes of the documentary were assembled from more than 600 hours of footage. It was directed by French filmmaker [[Jean-Xavier de Lestrade]] and released by Maha Productions in October 2004. The documentary offers an intimate depiction of defense preparations for the trial. It also examines the role and behavior of the popular press as it covered aspects of the case. The filmmakers started their project within weeks of the December 2001 death and Peterson's murder indictment; jury selection took place in May 2003 with the case itself going to trial in July 2003.\n\nFollowing the guilty verdict, de Lestrade interviewed the jurors to find out why they reached this verdict.<ref>The murder weapon was never identified. While his clothes were bloody from cradling his wife, Peterson had insufficient blood spattering on his clothes to support an attack. Media reports explained this by suggesting he probably changed his clothes, but investigators determined very early that he had not.</ref> By and large, the jurors were swayed by the amount of blood Kathleen lost and the number of lacerations, which indicated to them it could not have been an accident. [[Henry Lee (forensic scientist)|Henry Chang-Yu Lee]], however, had testified at the trial that the amount of blood was irrelevant, as the blood spatter indicated most of it was coughed up rather than from the wounds themselves. He also suggested some of the blood could have been diluted with urine. Lee had also duplicated blood spatter from coughing for the jury by drinking [[ketchup]] and spitting it out.<ref name=\"Dline\">[http://www.nbcnews.com/id/15894727 Death at the bottom of the stairs]  NBC Dateline November 25, 2006</ref><ref>[http://www.courttv.com/trials/novelist/091503_ctv.html Court TV News] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090323234230/http://www.courttv.com/trials/novelist/091503_ctv.html |date=March 23, 2009 }} CNN</ref><ref>Forensic neuropathologist Jan Leestma testified Kathleen Peterson had likely sustained four blows to the head, not seven as the medical examiner testified.{{cite web |url=http://www.courttv.com/trials/novelist/090903_ctv.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=March 11, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090204211725/http://www.courttv.com/trials/novelist/090903_ctv.html |archivedate=February 4, 2009  }} The prosecution counted [[Avulsion injury|avulsion]] wounds as multiple injuries and the Medical Examiner also initially counted four wounds following the autopsy.{{cite web |url=http://www.courttv.com/trials/novelist/080603_ctv.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=March 11, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090204211702/http://www.courttv.com/trials/novelist/080603_ctv.html |archivedate=February 4, 2009  }}</ref>\n\nIn November 2012, de Lestrade released a sequel, \"The Staircase 2: The Last Chance\", which premiered at the [[International Documentary Film Festival Amsterdam]].<ref>[http://www.indiewire.com/article/10-docs-to-watch-at-idfa-2012/ 10 Docs to Watch at IDFA 2012] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130209202119/http://www.indiewire.com/article/10-docs-to-watch-at-idfa-2012 |date=February 9, 2013 }}. Indiewire: November 19, 2012</ref><ref>[http://realscreen.com/2012/04/03/exclusive-de-lestrade-making-sequel-to-the-staircase/ Exclusive: de Lestrade making sequel to ''Death on the Staircase''] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130209073745/http://realscreen.com/2012/04/03/exclusive-de-lestrade-making-sequel-to-the-staircase/ |date=February 9, 2013 }} RealScreen: April 3, 2012</ref>\nThe film documents the Peterson family and its legal team's arguments in seeking a retrial, in which they succeed.<ref>[http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/05/14/north-carolina-state-bureau-of-investigation-duane-deaver_n_1516328.html/ North Carolina State Bureau of Investigation Forensics Scandal Grows With New Evidence of Fraud] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130130071357/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/05/14/north-carolina-state-bureau-of-investigation-duane-deaver_n_1516328.html |date=January 30, 2013 }}. Huffington: Post May 14, 2012</ref>\n\n===Television productions about the case===\n* ''[[The Staircase]]'', a French miniseries which got new episodes through [[Netflix]]\n* \"A Novel Idea\" ''[[Forensic Files]]''\n* \"Debut\" ''[[Cold Case]]''\n* \"Written in Blood\" ''[[The New Detectives]]''\n* \"Blood on the Staircase\" ''[[American Justice]]''\n* \"Murder, He Wrote\" ''[[Dominick Dunne]]'s Power, Privilege, and Justice''\n* \"Staircase Killer\" ''[[True Crime with Aphrodite Jones]]''\n* \"Stairway to Hell\" ''[[The Devil You Know (TV series)|The Devil You Know]]''\n* \"Reversal of Fortune\" [[Dateline NBC|''Dateline'' ''NBC'']]\n* \"[[Soup\u00e7ons|Death on the Staircase]]\" ''[[Storyville (TV series)|Storyville]]''\n* \"The Staircase II: The Last Chance\" ''Storyville''\n* \"Down the Back Staircase\" [[Dateline NBC|''Dateline'' ''NBC'']]\n* \u201c[[Trial & Error (TV series)|Trial and Error]]\u201d Season One - Loosely based\n\n===Radio productions about the case===\n* ''[[Criminal (podcast)|Criminal]]'' podcast: [http://thisiscriminal.com/episode-one-animal-instincts-1-31-2014-2/ \"Animal Instincts\"]\n* ''The Generation Why Podcast'': [https://web.archive.org/web/20161220102619/http://thegenerationwhypodcast.com/the-staircase-02-generation-why \"The Staircase\"]\n* [[BBC Radio 5 Live]]: [http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p054dybk/episodes/downloads \"Beyond Reasonable Doubt?\"]\n* ''[[My Favorite Murder]]'' podcast: [https://www.stitcher.com/podcast/independent-content-provider/my-favorite-murder/e/52647310 \"The 100th Episode\"]\n\n==Literary output==\n===Novels written by Peterson===\n* ''The Immortal Dragon'' (New American Library, 1983) \u2013 historical fiction {{LCCN|2009665719}}\n* ''A Time of War'' (Pocket Books, 1990) \u2013 Vietnam War fiction {{LCCN|89049197}}\n* ''A Bitter Peace'' (Pocket Books, 1995) \u2013 Vietnam War fiction {{LCCN|94037559}}\n* ''Charlie Two Shoes and the Marines of Love Company'', Peterson and David Perlmutt (Annapolis, MD: [[USNI#Naval Institute Press|Naval Institute Press]], 1998) \u2013 biography<!-- Tsui, Chi Hsii, 1934- --> {{LCCN|98030090}}\n* ''Operation Broken Reed'', with Lt. Col. Arthur L. Boyd (Da Capo Press, 2007) \u2013 Korean War autobiography\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n<ref name=papers>\n[http://library.duke.edu/rubenstein/findingaids/petersonmichael \"Guide to the Michael Peterson papers, 1961\u20132001 and undated, bulk 1972\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141020000106/http://library.duke.edu/rubenstein/findingaids/petersonmichael/ |date=October 20, 2014 }}. David M. Rubenstein Rare Book & Manuscript Library, Duke University (duke.edu/rubenstein). Retrieved October 19, 2014.</ref>\n}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Worldcat id|lccn-n89667130}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Peterson, Michael}}\n[[Category:20th-century American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American novelists]]\n[[Category:1943 births]]\n[[Category:American columnists]]\n[[Category:American expatriates in Germany]]\n[[Category:American male non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:American male novelists]]\n[[Category:United States Marine Corps personnel of the Vietnam War]]\n[[Category:American people convicted of murder]]\n[[Category:American prisoners sentenced to life imprisonment]]\n[[Category:Bisexual men]]\n[[Category:Bisexual writers]]\n[[Category:Duke University alumni]]\n[[Category:LGBT novelists]]\n[[Category:LGBT writers from the United States]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Novelists from North Carolina]]\n[[Category:Overturned convictions in the United States]]\n[[Category:People convicted of murder by North Carolina]]\n[[Category:People from Nashville, Tennessee]]\n[[Category:People who entered an Alford plea]]\n[[Category:Peterson family]]\n[[Category:Prisoners sentenced to life imprisonment by North Carolina]]\n[[Category:United States Marine Corps officers]]\n[[Category:Writers from Durham, North Carolina]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2018}}\n{{Infobox criminal<!-- Please see discussion on talk page pertaining to the usage of this template. Removal of template with no explanation or discussion will most likely result in your edit being reverted. -->\n |name               = Michael Peterson\n |birth_name         = Michael Iver Peterson\n |birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1943|10|23}}\n |birth_place        = [[Nashville, Tennessee]], U.S.\n |occupation         = {{hlist|Marine Corps officer|novelist}}\n |spouse             = {{plainlist|\n* {{marriage|Patricia Sue Peterson|1965|1987|reason=divorced}}\n* {{marriage|Kathleen Peterson|1997|2001|reason=died}}}}\n |children           = 5\n |conviction         = [[Murder]], later reduced to voluntary [[manslaughter]]\n |conviction_penalty = [[Life imprisonment|Life imprisonment without parole]], later reduced to 86&nbsp;months imprisonment (actual [[time served]] was 98.5&nbsp;months)\n}}\n\n'''Michael Iver Peterson''' (born October 23, 1943) is an American [[novelist]] who was convicted in 2003 of [[murder]]ing his second wife, Kathleen Peterson, on December&nbsp;9, 2001. After eight years, Peterson was granted a new trial after the judge ruled a critical prosecution witness gave misleading testimony.<ref name=\"ABC121511\">{{cite news|title= Novelist Michael Peterson, Convicted of Wife's Murder, Is Released From Prison and Will Get New Trial|publisher= [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]|year= 2011|accessdate= December 17, 2011|url= http://abcnews.go.com/blogs/headlines/2011/12/novelist-michael-peterson-convicted-of-wifes-murder-is-released-from-prison-and-will-get-new-trial/|url-status= live|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20111216082633/http://abcnews.go.com/blogs/headlines/2011/12/novelist-michael-peterson-convicted-of-wifes-murder-is-released-from-prison-and-will-get-new-trial/|archivedate= December 16, 2011|df= mdy-all}}</ref> This second trial had been scheduled to begin on May&nbsp;8, 2017.<ref name=\"abc11.com\">{{cite web |url=http://abc11.com/news/judge-rules-peterson-will-stand-trial-in-murder-case/1605864/ |title=Judge rules Michael Peterson will stand trial in murder case |date=November 14, 2016 |accessdate=December 4, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161115135917/http://abc11.com/news/judge-rules-peterson-will-stand-trial-in-murder-case/1605864/ |archivedate=November 15, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn February&nbsp;24, 2017, Peterson submitted an [[Alford plea]] to the reduced charge of [[manslaughter]]. He was sentenced to [[time served|time already served]] and freed. Peterson's case is the subject of the documentary miniseries ''[[The Staircase]]'', which started filming soon after his arrest in 2001 and followed events until his eventual [[Alford plea]] in 2017. In 2019, he released his own account of his life since his wife Kathleen's death in an independently published memoir, ''Behind the Staircase''.<ref name=\"Ch Observer\">{{cite web |last1=Cain |first1=Brooke |title=Hollywood just can\u2019t seem to get enough of the Michael Peterson \u2018Staircase\u2019 story  |url=https://www.charlotteobserver.com/entertainment/tv/article212767324.html |website=www.charlotteobserver.com |publisher=The Charlotte Observer |accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Personal and professional life==\nMichael \"Mike\" Peterson was born near [[Nashville, Tennessee]], the son of Eugen Iver Peterson and Eleanor Peterson ({{nee|Bartolino}}). He graduated from [[Duke University]] with a [[bachelor's degree]] in [[political science]]. While there, he was president of [[Sigma Nu]] fraternity and was<!--source supports this much--> editor of [[The Chronicle (Duke University)|''The Chronicle'']], the daily student newspaper, from 1964\u20131965.<ref name=\"papers\" /> He attended classes at the law school of the [[University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill]].\n\nAfter graduating, Peterson took a civilian job with the [[United States Department of Defense|U.S. Department of Defense]], where he was assigned to research arguments supporting increased military involvement in [[Vietnam]]. That year he also married Patricia Sue<!--Maiden name? Peterson is her married name -->, who taught at an elementary school on the [[Rhein-Main Air Base]] in Gr\u00e4fenhausen, [[West Germany]]. They had two children, Clayton and Todd.\n\nIn 1968, Peterson enlisted in the [[United States Marine Corps]] and served in [[Vietnam War|Vietnam]]. In 1971, he received an honorable discharge with the rank of captain after a car accident left him with a permanent disability. Years later, during [[1999 Durham mayoral election|a mayoral campaign]], Peterson claimed he had won a [[Silver Star]], a [[Bronze Star Medal|Bronze Star]] With Valor, and two [[Purple Heart]]s. He had all the medals, but said he did not have the documentation for them. He claimed he had received one Purple Heart after being hit by shrapnel when another soldier stepped on a land mine, and the other when he was shot. Peterson later admitted his war injury was not the result of the shrapnel wound in Vietnam, but was the result of a vehicle accident in Japan, where he was stationed after the war as a military policeman.<ref name=\"Dline\" /> The ''[[News & Observer]]'' said records did not contain any mention of the two Purple Heart medals that Peterson said he had received. However, military files verified that he received a Silver Star and the Bronze Star Medal with Valor.<ref>Kane, Dan.  [https://www.newsobserver.com/news/local/counties/durham-county/article213595444.html \"Durham mayoral candidate Michael Peterson fabricated war injury, admits falsehood\"], ''[[The News & Observer]]'' website, 18 September 1999. Updated 21 June 2018. Retrieved 1 March 2019.</ref>\n\nMichael and Patricia lived in Germany for some time. There they befriended Elizabeth and George Ratliff and their two children, Margaret and Martha. After George's death, the Peterson and Ratliff families became very close. When Elizabeth Ratliff died in 1985, Michael became the guardian of her two children. After Michael and Patricia divorced in 1987, Clayton and Todd lived with Patricia, and Margaret and Martha stayed with Michael, who then moved to [[Durham, North Carolina]]. Clayton and Todd later also joined their father.\n\nPeterson wrote three novels based \"around his experiences during the Vietnamese conflict\"<ref name=\"papers\" />\u2014''The Immortal Dragon'', ''A Time of War'', and ''A Bitter Peace''.<!--see TALK--> He co-wrote the biographical ''Charlie Two Shoes and the Marines of Love Company'' with journalist David Perlmutt, and co-wrote ''Operation Broken Reed'' with Lt. Col. Arthur L. Boyd. He also worked as a newspaper columnist for the ''[[The Herald-Sun (Durham, North Carolina)|Durham Herald-Sun]]'', where his columns became known for their criticism of police and Durham County District Attorney James Hardin Jr. Hardin was the prosecutor of Peterson for the murder of his second wife, Kathleen.\n\nIn 1989, Michael moved in with Kathleen Atwater, a successful [[Nortel]] business executive. They married in 1997, and Kathleen's daughter Caitlin joined the extended family that now consisted of Clayton, Todd, Martha, and Margaret.<ref name=\"Court TV 1\">{{cite news|title= Wife's staircase death at center of novelist's murder trial|publisher= [[truTV|Court TV]]|year= 2001|accessdate= March 11, 2009|url= http://www.courttv.com/trials/novelist/background_ctv.html|url-status= dead|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090307224345/http://www.courttv.com/trials/novelist/background_ctv.html|archivedate= March 7, 2009|df= mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Murder trial==\n\n===Kathleen's death===\nOn December 9, 2001, Peterson called an emergency line to report that he had just found Kathleen unconscious in their [[Forest Hills Historic District (Durham, North Carolina)|Forest Hills]] mansion and suspected she had fallen down \"15, 20, I don't know\" stairs. He later claimed that he had been outside by the pool and had come in at 2:40&nbsp;am to find Kathleen at the foot of the stairs. He said she must have fallen down the stairs after consuming alcohol and [[Valium]].\n\nToxicology results showed that his wife's [[blood alcohol content]] was 0.07 percent (70&nbsp;mg/100mL). The [[autopsy]] report concluded that the 48-year-old woman sustained a matrix of severe injuries, including a fracture of the [[Thyroid cartilage|thyroid neck cartilage]] and seven lacerations to the top and back of her head, consistent with blows from a blunt object, and had died from blood loss 90 minutes to two hours after sustaining the injuries.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.autopsyfiles.org/reports/Other/peterson,%20kathleen_report.pdf|title=Kathleen Peterson Autopsy Report}}</ref> Kathleen's daughter, Caitlin, and Kathleen's sister, Candace Zamperini, both initially proclaimed Michael's innocence and publicly supported him alongside his children, but Zamperini reconsidered after learning of Peterson's [[bisexuality]], as did Caitlin after reading her mother's autopsy report. Both subsequently broke off from the rest of the family.\n\nAlthough forensic expert [[Henry Lee (forensic scientist)|Henry Lee]], hired by the defense, testified that the [[Bloodstain pattern analysis|blood-spatter evidence]] was consistent with an accidental fall down the stairs, police investigators concluded that the injuries were inconsistent with such an accident. As Michael Peterson was the only person at the residence at the time of Kathleen's death, he was the prime suspect and was soon charged with her murder. He pleaded not guilty.\n\nThe medical examiner, Deborah Radisch, concluded that Kathleen had died from lacerations of the scalp caused by a homicidal assault. According to Radisch, the total of seven lacerations to the top and back of Kathleen's head were the result of repeated blows with a light, yet rigid, weapon. The defense disputed this theory. According to their analysis, Kathleen's skull had not been fractured by the blows, nor was she brain damaged, which was inconsistent with injuries sustained in a beating death.\n\nThe trial drew increasing media attention as details of Michael's private life emerged. Durham County District Attorney James Hardin, Jr. and the prosecutors (among them former District Attorney [[Mike Nifong]]) attacked Peterson's credibility, focusing on his alleged misreporting of his military service and what they described as a \"gay life\" he led and kept secret. The prosecution contended that the Petersons' marriage was far from happy, suggesting that Kathleen had discovered Michael's alleged secret \"gay life\" and wanted to end their marriage. It was the main motive that the prosecution offered at trial for Kathleen's alleged murder (the other being a $1.5 million life insurance policy). According to Assistant District Attorney Freda Black, Kathleen\n\n<blockquote>would have been infuriated by learning that her husband, who she truly loved, was bi-sexual and having an extramarital relationship\u2014not with another woman\u2014but a man, which would have been humiliating and embarrassing to her. We believe that once she learned this information that an argument ensued and a homicide occurred.</blockquote>\n\nThe defense argued that Kathleen accepted Michael's bisexuality and that the marriage was very happy, a position supported by Michael and Kathleen's children and other friends and associates.<ref name=\"Court TV 1\" />\n\nThe prosecution said that the murder was most likely committed with a custom-made [[fireplace poker]] called a blow poke. It had been a gift to the Petersons from Kathleen's sister but was missing from the house at the time of the murder investigation. Late in the trial the defense team produced the missing blow poke, which they said had been overlooked in the garage by police investigators. Forensic tests revealed that it had been untouched and unmoved for too long to have been used in the murder.{{citation needed|date=June 2018}} <!-- doesn't Rudolf claim detectives moved and photographed the blowpoke? --> A juror contacted after the trial noted that the jury dismissed the idea of the blow poke as the murder weapon.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.courttv.com/trials/novelist/guilty_ctv.html |title=Novelist convicted of first-degree murder in wife's staircase death |publisher=Courttv.com |accessdate=December 2, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090406033031/http://www.courttv.com/trials/novelist/guilty_ctv.html |archivedate=April 6, 2009  }}</ref>\n\n===Suspicion surrounding Elizabeth Ratliff's death===\nElizabeth Ratliff, the friend of the Petersons who died in Germany in 1985, had also been found dead at the foot of her staircase with injuries to the head. Her death had been investigated by both the German police and U.S. military police. An autopsy at the time of her death concluded she died from an [[Cerebrovascular accident|intra-cerebral haemorrhage]] secondary to the blood coagulation disorder [[Von Willebrand's disease]], based on blood in her cerebrospinal fluid and reports that she had been suffering severe, persistent headaches in the weeks leading up to her death. The coroner determined that the hemorrhage resulted in immediate death followed by Ratliff falling down the stairs after collapsing. The Petersons had dinner with Ratliff and her daughters, and Peterson had stayed and helped Ratliff put the children to bed before going home. The children's nanny, Barbara, discovered the body when she arrived the next morning. Peterson was the last known person to see her alive.\n\nBefore Peterson's trial, the Durham court ordered the exhumation of Ratliff's [[embalm]]ed body, buried in Texas, for a second autopsy in April 2003.<ref name=\"Herald28803\">Herald-Journal \u2013 August 28, 2003 [https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=_2FhAAAAIBAJ&sjid=Y9AEAAAAIBAJ&pg=6609%2C5088116 Prosecutors Try to Link Two Deaths] Retrieved February 2015</ref>  Arrangements were made for the Durham medical examiner/[[pathologist]] who had initially performed Kathleen Peterson's autopsy, to perform this reevaluation, over the objections of defense counsel who argued that the autopsy should be performed by Texas medical examiners. The body was then transported from Texas to Durham. The Durham M.E. found sufficient evidence drawn from the results of the second autopsy, along with new witness statements describing the scene,<ref name=\"Herald28803\" /> to overturn the earlier findings and list Ratliff's cause of death as \"homicide\".\n\nThe prosecution declined to accuse Peterson of Ratliff's death, but introduced the death into the trial as an incident giving Peterson the idea of how to \"fake\" Kathleen's accident. Despite police reports that there was very little blood at the scene of Ratliff's death, the nanny, who was the first to discover Ratliff's body in 1985, took the stand at Peterson's trial and testified that there was a large amount of blood at the scene. Another witness testified to spending much of the day cleaning blood stains off the wall.\n\nThe admissibility of the Ratliff evidence in court was one of the grounds for the subsequent appeal against his conviction, lodged by Peterson's lawyers in 2005.\n\nIn October 2002, acting as [[Administrator (law)|administrator]] of Kathleen's [[Estate (law)|estate]], Caitlin filed a [[wrongful death claim]] against Michael. In June 2006, he voluntarily filed for [[bankruptcy]]. Two weeks later, Caitlin filed an objection to the bankruptcy. On February 1, 2007, Caitlin and Michael settled the wrongful death claim for $25 million, pending acceptance by the courts involved; finalization of the settlement by the court was announced on February 1, 2008. In the settlement, Michael did not admit that he murdered Kathleen.{{cn|date=February 2020}}\n\n===Verdict===\nOn October 10, 2003, after one of the longest trials in North Carolina history, a [[Durham County, North Carolina|Durham County]] jury found Michael Peterson guilty of the murder of Kathleen Peterson,<ref>The Dispatch \u2013 October 9, 2003 [https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=1PIbAAAAIBAJ&sjid=DVMEAAAAIBAJ&pg=5792%2C3458204 Novelist Peterson Convicted] Retrieved February 2015</ref> and he was sentenced to life in prison without the possibility of parole.<ref>The Item \u2013 October 10, 2003 [https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=_J0iAAAAIBAJ&sjid=M68FAAAAIBAJ&pg=1245%2C1428450 Novelist Convicted of Beating Wife to Death] Retrieved February 2015</ref> Denial of parole requires premeditation. Despite the jury accepting the murder was a \"spur-of-the-moment\" crime, they also found it was premeditated. As one juror explained it, premeditated meant not only planning hours or days ahead, but could also mean planning in the seconds before committing a spur-of-the-moment crime.\n\nPeterson was housed at the Nash Correctional Institution near [[Rocky Mount, North Carolina|Rocky Mount]] until he was released on December 16, 2011.\n\n===Appeal===\nPeterson's appeal was filed by his defense counsel, Thomas Maher, now serving as his court-appointed attorney, and was argued before the [[North Carolina Court of Appeals]] on April 18, 2006. On September 19, 2006, the Court of Appeals rejected Peterson's arguments that he did not get a fair trial because of repeated judicial mistakes.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.vanceholmes.com/court/peterson_appeal2.html |title=Defendant\u2013Appellants Brief |publisher=Vanceholmes.com |accessdate=December 2, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120316100125/http://www.vanceholmes.com/court/peterson_appeal2.html |archivedate=March 16, 2012  }}</ref> The Appeals' ruling said the evidence was fairly admitted. The judges did find defects in a search warrant, but said they had no ill effect on the defense.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.aoc.state.nc.us/www/public/sc/opinions/2007/547-06-1.htm |title=State v. Peterson |publisher=Aoc.state.nc.us |accessdate=December 2, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203035409/http://www.aoc.state.nc.us/www/public/sc/opinions/2007/547-06-1.htm |archivedate=December 3, 2013  }}</ref><ref>The Times-News \u2013 September 20, 2006 [https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=wms0AAAAIBAJ&sjid=BSYEAAAAIBAJ&pg=3379%2C4839920 Appeals Court won't overturn decision] Retrieved February 2015</ref> Because the Court of Appeals' ruling was not unanimous, under North Carolina law, Peterson had right to appeal to the [[North Carolina Supreme Court]], which accepted the case. Oral argument was heard on September 10, 2007. On November 9, 2007, the Court announced that it affirmed the decision of the Court of Appeals. Absent a reconsideration of the ruling or the raising of a [[United States federal courts|federal]] issue, Peterson had exhausted his appeal of the verdict.\n\nOn November 12, 2008, J. Burkhardt Beale and Jason Anthony, [[Richmond, Virginia]] attorneys, who were now representing Peterson, filed a [[Motion (legal)#Motion for new trial|motion for a new trial]] in Durham County court on three grounds: that the prosecution withheld [[exculpatory evidence]] about a blow poke, that the prosecution used an [[expert witness]] whose qualifications were disputed, and that one juror based his judgment on racial factors. On March 10, 2009, Peterson's motion was denied by the Durham County Superior Court.\n\n===Owl theory===\n{{refimprove section|date=March 2020}}\n{{Original research|section|date=March 2020}} \nIn late 2009, a new theory of Kathleen Peterson's death was raised: that she had been attacked by an [[owl]] outside, fallen after rushing inside, and been knocked unconscious after hitting her head on the first tread of the stairs. The owl theory was raised by Durham attorney T. Lawrence Pollard, a neighbor of the Petersons who was not involved in the case but had been following the public details. He approached the police suggesting an owl might have been responsible after reading the [[North Carolina State Bureau of Investigation]] evidence list and finding a \"feather\" listed. Peterson's attorneys had determined that the SBI crime lab report listed a microscopic owl feather and a wooden sliver from a tree limb entangled in a clump of hair that had been pulled out by the roots found clutched in Kathleen's left hand.<ref>[http://owltheory.blog.lemonde.fr/2008/09/05/feathers-flying-in-michael-peterson-case-by-bernie-reeves/ Feathers flying in Michael Peterson case] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110426055501/http://owltheory.blog.lemonde.fr/2008/09/05/feathers-flying-in-michael-peterson-case-by-bernie-reeves/ |date=April 26, 2011 }} [[le Monde]] September 5, 2008</ref><ref name=\"Owl\">[http://www.newsobserver.com/2010/08/19/636421/three-experts-affidavits-support.html Three affidavits support Peterson's murderous owl theory] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101210095810/http://www.newsobserver.com/2010/08/19/636421/three-experts-affidavits-support.html |date=December 10, 2010 }} Durham County News Observer August 19, 2010</ref> A re-examination of the hair in September 2008 had found two more microscopic owl feathers.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://thisiscriminal.com/episode-one-animal-instincts-1-31-2014-2/ |title=Episode 1: Animal Instincts (1.31.2014) |accessdate=January 8, 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150110024809/http://thisiscriminal.com/episode-one-animal-instincts-1-31-2014-2/ |archivedate=January 10, 2015  }}</ref>\n\nAlthough Pollard did not speak of the theory to anyone else,{{citation needed|date=March 2020}} ''The'' ''Durham Herald-Sun'' published an article ridiculing him, and discrediting his theory.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}} Other media picked it up, propagating the ''Herald-Sun'' story, which was later criticized as inaccurate.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\nAdvocates of this theory{{who?|date=March 2020}} assert that other evidence supports it, namely: the scalp wounds were tri-lobed and paired, consistent with marks left by talons,{{citation needed|date=March 2020}} the feathers are similar to those on owl feet,{{citation needed|date=March 2020}} cedar needles were found on her hands and body indicating Kathleen had fallen over outside shortly before entering the house, that her blood had spattered up the staircase rather than down, that her footprints in her own blood indicated that she was already bleeding before she reached the foot of the stairs, and that two drops of her blood were found outside the house on the front walkway along with a finger smear on the front door consistent with her pushing the door shut. Advocates also note that owl attacks on people are common in the area,{{citation needed|date=March 2020}} with one victim{{who?|date=March 2020}} stating that the impact was similar to being hit in the head with a baseball bat.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\nAccording to Pollard, had a jury been presented with this evidence it would have \"materially affected their deliberation and therefore would have materially affected their ultimate verdict\". Prosecutors have ridiculed the claim, and Deborah Radisch, who conducted Kathleen Peterson's autopsy, says it is unlikely that an owl or any other bird could have made wounds as deep as those on her scalp. However, Radisch's opinion was challenged by other experts in three separate affidavits filed in 2010.   Alan van Norman wrote: \"The multiple wounds present suggest to me that an owl and Ms. Peterson somehow became entangled. Perhaps the owl got tangled in her hair or perhaps she grabbed the owl's foot.\"<ref name=\"Owl2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thedurhamnews.com/2010/08/25/203219/three-experts-back-owl-theory.html |title=Three experts back owl theory |accessdate=June 10, 2011 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100831081004/http://www.thedurhamnews.com/2010/08/25/203219/three-experts-back-owl-theory.html |archivedate=August 31, 2010 }} Stanley B. Chambers, Jr. ''The Durham News'' (thedurhamnews.com). August 25, 2010.</ref>\n\nPatrick T. Redig, a professor of [[veterinary medicine]] at the [[University of Minnesota]] wrote: \"In my professional opinion, the hypothesized attack to the face and back of the head resulting in the various punctures and lacerations visible in the autopsy photographs is entirely within the behavioral repertoire of large owls.\"<ref name=\"Owl2\" />\n\nKate P. Davis, executive director of Raptors of the Rockies, a western Montana education and wildlife rehabilitation project, wrote:\nThe lacerations on Mrs. Peterson's scalp look very much like those made by a [[bird of prey|raptor]]'s talons, especially if she had forcibly torn the bird from the back of her head. That would explain the feathers found in her hand and the many hairs pulled out by the root, broken or cut. The size and configuration of the lacerations could certainly indicate the feet of a [[barred owl]].<ref name=\"Owl2\" /> Davis further noted that owls can kill species much larger than themselves and that it is not uncommon for them to attack people.<ref name=\"Owl2\" />\n\nDespite interest in this theory among some outside advocates, no motion for a new trial was filed on this point in 2009.<ref>[http://www.wral.com/news/local/story/5726608/ Attorney wants owl theory reconsidered in Peterson murder case] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100316085507/http://www.wral.com/news/local/story/5726608/ |date=March 16, 2010 }} [[WRAL-TV]] August 11, 2009</ref><ref>[http://owltheory.blog.lemonde.fr/2008/09/04/evidence-points-to-owl-in-peterson-case/ Evidence points to owl in Peterson case] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110129014541/http://owltheory.blog.lemonde.fr/2008/09/04/evidence-points-to-owl-in-peterson-case/ |date=January 29, 2011 }} ''[[Le Monde]]'' September 4, 2008</ref>\n\nOn March 2, 2017 (following his Alford plea), Mr. Peterson's attorney filed a motion to allow him to pay for a bird expert at the [[Smithsonian Institution]] to examine feather fragments found in Kathleen Peterson's hair to determine if she was attacked by a raptor.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wwwcache.wral.com/asset/news/local/2017/03/13/16582208/20170313112617080.pdf|title=North Carolina vs Michael Peterson - Motion for order allowing transport of microslide to expert for inspection and testing|access-date=August 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Retrial hearing===\nIn August 2010, following a series of newspaper articles critical of the investigative tactics of State Bureau of Investigation agents, Attorney General [[Roy Cooper]] led an investigation, which resulted in the suspension of SBI analyst Duane Deaver, one of the principal witnesses against Peterson, after the report found his work among the worst done on scores of flawed criminal cases. T. Lawrence Pollard subsequently filed affidavits<ref>Neurosurgeon and owl expert   Alan van Norman,   Patrick T. Redig, a professor of veterinary medicine at the University of Minnesota, and Kate P. Davis, the director of Raptors of the Rockies, signed affidavits claiming that the evidence and injuries are consistent with an attack by an owl, possibly a [[barred owl]].</ref> to support a motion that Superior Court Judge Orlando Hudson order the state Medical Examiner's Office to turn over all documentation related to Kathleen Peterson's autopsy to Peterson's attorneys. However, Judge Hudson barred Pollard from filing further motions on behalf of Peterson because Pollard did not represent him. A new motion was filed in August 2010 by David Rudolf, one of Peterson's original attorneys who acted [[pro bono]] in proceedings challenging the SBI testimony.<ref name=\"Owl\" /><ref>[http://abclocal.go.com/wtvd/story?section=news/local&id=7619462 Michael Peterson impacted by SBI report?] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110628224744/http://abclocal.go.com/wtvd/story?section=news%2Flocal&id=7619462 |date=June 28, 2011 }} [[ABC News]] August 20, 2010</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=James |first=Jesse |url=http://www.newsobserver.com/2010/08/27/651015/attorney-forbidden-from-filing.html |title=DURHAM: Attorney forbidden from filing Michael Peterson motions &#124; Crime |publisher=NewsObserver.com |date=August 27, 2010 |accessdate=December 2, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131207105441/http://www.newsobserver.com/2010/08/27/651015/attorney-forbidden-from-filing.html |archivedate=December 7, 2013  }}</ref>\n\nDeaver was fired from the SBI in January 2011, after an independent audit of the agency found he had falsely represented evidence in 34 cases, including withholding negative results in the case of Greg Taylor, a North Carolina man who spent 17 years in prison on a murder conviction based on Deaver's testimony.<ref>Troubled SBI agent Duane Deaver fired. {{cite web |url=http://www.newsobserver.com/2011/01/10/911881/troubled-sbi-agent-duane-deaver.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=December 16, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110817013820/http://www.newsobserver.com/2011/01/10/911881/troubled-sbi-agent-duane-deaver.html |archivedate=August 17, 2011  }}</ref> A bloodstain-analysis team that Deaver had trained was suspended and disbanded. In the 2003 Peterson trial, Deaver testified that he had been mentored by SBI bloodstain specialist David Spittle, had worked 500 bloodstain cases, written 200 reports, and testified in 60 cases. During the retrial hearing, SBI Assistant Director Eric Hooks testified that Deaver had written only 47 reports. SBI agent David Spittle testified that he could not recall mentoring Deaver who, since completing a two-day training course in the 1980s, had testified in only four cases, the Peterson case being the third. The SBI cited the bloodstain analysis given in the fourth case as the reason for firing Deaver.<ref>[http://www.newsobserver.com/2011/12/07/1694717/sbi-says-deaver-exaggerated-expertise.html SBI says Deaver exaggerated expertise] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120110133848/http://www.newsobserver.com/2011/12/07/1694717/sbi-says-deaver-exaggerated-expertise.html |date=January 10, 2012 }} [[The News & Observer]] December 08, 2011</ref>\n\nOn December 16, 2011, Peterson was released from the Durham County jail on $300,000 bail and placed under house arrest with a tracking anklet. His release on bond followed a judicial order for a new trial after Judge Hudson found that SBI blood analyst Duane Deaver had given \"materially misleading\" and \"deliberately false\" testimony about bloodstain evidence, and had exaggerated his training, experience, and expertise.<ref>[http://www.newsobserver.com/2012/08/10/2260545/judge-says-peterson-must-keep.html Judge says Peterson must keep wearing ankle bracelet] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120812024815/http://www.newsobserver.com/2012/08/10/2260545/judge-says-peterson-must-keep.html |date=August 12, 2012 }} News Observer August 10, 2012</ref><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20120214125030/http://www.news-record.com/content/2011/12/16/article/durham_novelist_peterson_walks_out_of_jail_awaits_new_murder_trial Durham novelist Peterson walks out of jail; awaits new murder trial. ]</ref><ref>[https://archive.today/20120904052941/http://www.newsobserver.com/2011/12/09/1699177/defense-dissects-deavers-methods.html?tab=gallery&gallery=/2011/12/07/1696640/michael-peterson-hearing-continues.html&gid_index=3 Peterson defense dissects Deaver's methods] [[The News & Observer]] December 9, 2011</ref> Former North Carolina Attorney General [[Rufus L. Edmisten|Rufus Edmisten]] said that any evidence gathered after Deaver arrived at the scene might be deemed inadmissible in a new trial.<ref>[http://www2.nbc17.com/news/durham-county/2011/dec/16/former-nc-ag-says-it-will-be-harder-state-convict--ar-1723556/ Former NC AG says it will be harder for the State to convict Peterson in retrial] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120114154436/http://www2.nbc17.com/news/durham-county/2011/dec/16/former-nc-ag-says-it-will-be-harder-state-convict--ar-1723556/ |date=January 14, 2012 }} [[NBC]] December 17, 2011</ref>\n\nIn July 2014, Peterson's bond restrictions were eased.<ref>{{Cite web|title = DA: Peterson's new trial months away|url = http://www.heraldsun.com/news/localnews/x761901796/DA-Peterson-s-new-trial-months-away|accessdate = May 6, 2015|url-status = dead|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150508085109/http://www.heraldsun.com/news/localnews/x761901796/DA-Peterson-s-new-trial-months-away|archivedate = May 8, 2015|df = mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2014, the court appointed Mike Klinkosum to represent Peterson, replacing David Rudolf, who had been working pro bono on the case since Peterson's conviction was overturned. Rudolf had stated that he could no longer afford to represent Peterson without being paid.<ref>{{Cite news|url =http://www.wral.com/mike-peterson-gets-new-attorney-for-second-murder-trial/14109012/|title =Mike Peterson gets new attorney for second murder trial|url-status =live|archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20141025033605/http://www.wral.com/mike-peterson-gets-new-attorney-for-second-murder-trial/14109012/|archivedate =October 25, 2014|df =mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn November 14, 2016, Peterson's request for the second trial to be dismissed was refused, and a new trial was scheduled to begin on May 8, 2017.<ref name=\"abc11.com\"/> However, a news report on February 7, 2017, indicated that a resolution had been negotiated by Rudolf (once again representing Peterson) and the Durham County DA.\n\n===Alford plea===\nOn February 24, 2017, Peterson entered an [[Alford plea]] (a guilty plea entered because sufficient evidence exists to convict him of the offense, but the defendant asserts innocence) to the voluntary manslaughter of Kathleen Peterson.<ref>{{cite news |last=Sims |first=Julia |last2=Crabtree |first2=Davis |url=http://www.wral.com/mike-peterson-walks-free-after-15-year-murder-case-ends-with-plea-deal/16546848/ |title=Mike Peterson walks free as 15-year murder case ends with plea deal |work=[[WRAL-TV]] |publisher=Capitol Broadcasting Company, Inc. |date=2017-02-24 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170225044044/http://www.wral.com/mike-peterson-walks-free-after-15-year-murder-case-ends-with-plea-deal/16546848/ |archivedate=2017-02-25 |accessdate=2018-07-16 }}</ref> The judge sentenced him to a maximum of 86 months in prison, with credit for time previously served. Because Peterson had already served more time than the sentence (98.5 months), he did not face additional prison time.\n\n==Media==\n\n===Films about the case===\nThe court case generated widespread interest in part because of a televised documentary series variously named ''[[Soup\u00e7ons]]'' (Suspicions), ''Death on the Staircase'', and ''The Staircase'', which detailed Peterson's legal and personal troubles. Eight 45-minute episodes of the documentary were assembled from more than 600 hours of footage. It was directed by French filmmaker [[Jean-Xavier de Lestrade]] and released by Maha Productions in October 2004. The documentary offers an intimate depiction of defense preparations for the trial. It also examines the role and behavior of the popular press as it covered aspects of the case. The filmmakers started their project within weeks of the December 2001 death and Peterson's murder indictment; jury selection took place in May 2003 with the case itself going to trial in July 2003.\n\nFollowing the guilty verdict, de Lestrade interviewed the jurors to find out why they reached this verdict.<ref>The murder weapon was never identified. While his clothes were bloody from cradling his wife, Peterson had insufficient blood spattering on his clothes to support an attack. Media reports explained this by suggesting he probably changed his clothes, but investigators determined very early that he had not.</ref> By and large, the jurors were swayed by the amount of blood Kathleen lost and the number of lacerations, which indicated to them it could not have been an accident. [[Henry Lee (forensic scientist)|Henry Chang-Yu Lee]], however, had testified at the trial that the amount of blood was irrelevant, as the blood spatter indicated most of it was coughed up rather than from the wounds themselves. He also suggested some of the blood could have been diluted with urine. Lee had also duplicated blood spatter from coughing for the jury by drinking [[ketchup]] and spitting it out.<ref name=\"Dline\">[http://www.nbcnews.com/id/15894727 Death at the bottom of the stairs]  NBC Dateline November 25, 2006</ref><ref>[http://www.courttv.com/trials/novelist/091503_ctv.html Court TV News] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090323234230/http://www.courttv.com/trials/novelist/091503_ctv.html |date=March 23, 2009 }} CNN</ref><ref>Forensic neuropathologist Jan Leestma testified Kathleen Peterson had likely sustained four blows to the head, not seven as the medical examiner testified.{{cite web |url=http://www.courttv.com/trials/novelist/090903_ctv.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=March 11, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090204211725/http://www.courttv.com/trials/novelist/090903_ctv.html |archivedate=February 4, 2009  }} The prosecution counted [[Avulsion injury|avulsion]] wounds as multiple injuries and the Medical Examiner also initially counted four wounds following the autopsy.{{cite web |url=http://www.courttv.com/trials/novelist/080603_ctv.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=March 11, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090204211702/http://www.courttv.com/trials/novelist/080603_ctv.html |archivedate=February 4, 2009  }}</ref>\n\nIn November 2012, de Lestrade released a sequel, \"The Staircase 2: The Last Chance\", which premiered at the [[International Documentary Film Festival Amsterdam]].<ref>[http://www.indiewire.com/article/10-docs-to-watch-at-idfa-2012/ 10 Docs to Watch at IDFA 2012] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130209202119/http://www.indiewire.com/article/10-docs-to-watch-at-idfa-2012 |date=February 9, 2013 }}. Indiewire: November 19, 2012</ref><ref>[http://realscreen.com/2012/04/03/exclusive-de-lestrade-making-sequel-to-the-staircase/ Exclusive: de Lestrade making sequel to ''Death on the Staircase''] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130209073745/http://realscreen.com/2012/04/03/exclusive-de-lestrade-making-sequel-to-the-staircase/ |date=February 9, 2013 }} RealScreen: April 3, 2012</ref>\nThe film documents the Peterson family and its legal team's arguments in seeking a retrial, in which they succeed.<ref>[http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/05/14/north-carolina-state-bureau-of-investigation-duane-deaver_n_1516328.html/ North Carolina State Bureau of Investigation Forensics Scandal Grows With New Evidence of Fraud] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130130071357/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/05/14/north-carolina-state-bureau-of-investigation-duane-deaver_n_1516328.html |date=January 30, 2013 }}. Huffington: Post May 14, 2012</ref>\n\n===Television productions about the case===\n* ''[[The Staircase]]'', a French miniseries which got new episodes through [[Netflix]]\n* \"A Novel Idea\" ''[[Forensic Files]]''\n* \"Debut\" ''[[Cold Case]]''\n* \"Written in Blood\" ''[[The New Detectives]]''\n* \"Blood on the Staircase\" ''[[American Justice]]''\n* \"Murder, He Wrote\" ''[[Dominick Dunne]]'s Power, Privilege, and Justice''\n* \"Staircase Killer\" ''[[True Crime with Aphrodite Jones]]''\n* \"Stairway to Hell\" ''[[The Devil You Know (TV series)|The Devil You Know]]''\n* \"Reversal of Fortune\" [[Dateline NBC|''Dateline'' ''NBC'']]\n* \"[[Soup\u00e7ons|Death on the Staircase]]\" ''[[Storyville (TV series)|Storyville]]''\n* \"The Staircase II: The Last Chance\" ''Storyville''\n* \"Down the Back Staircase\" [[Dateline NBC|''Dateline'' ''NBC'']]\n* \u201c[[Trial & Error (TV series)|Trial and Error]]\u201d Season One - Loosely based\n\n===Radio productions about the case===\n* ''[[Criminal (podcast)|Criminal]]'' podcast: [http://thisiscriminal.com/episode-one-animal-instincts-1-31-2014-2/ \"Animal Instincts\"]\n* ''The Generation Why Podcast'': [https://web.archive.org/web/20161220102619/http://thegenerationwhypodcast.com/the-staircase-02-generation-why \"The Staircase\"]\n* [[BBC Radio 5 Live]]: [http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p054dybk/episodes/downloads \"Beyond Reasonable Doubt?\"]\n* ''[[My Favorite Murder]]'' podcast: [https://www.stitcher.com/podcast/independent-content-provider/my-favorite-murder/e/52647310 \"The 100th Episode\"]\n\n==Literary output==\n===Novels written by Peterson===\n* ''The Immortal Dragon'' (New American Library, 1983) \u2013 historical fiction {{LCCN|2009665719}}\n* ''A Time of War'' (Pocket Books, 1990) \u2013 Vietnam War fiction {{LCCN|89049197}}\n* ''A Bitter Peace'' (Pocket Books, 1995) \u2013 Vietnam War fiction {{LCCN|94037559}}\n* ''Charlie Two Shoes and the Marines of Love Company'', Peterson and David Perlmutt (Annapolis, MD: [[USNI#Naval Institute Press|Naval Institute Press]], 1998) \u2013 biography<!-- Tsui, Chi Hsii, 1934- --> {{LCCN|98030090}}\n* ''Operation Broken Reed'', with Lt. Col. Arthur L. Boyd (Da Capo Press, 2007) \u2013 Korean War autobiography\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n<ref name=papers>\n[http://library.duke.edu/rubenstein/findingaids/petersonmichael \"Guide to the Michael Peterson papers, 1961\u20132001 and undated, bulk 1972\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141020000106/http://library.duke.edu/rubenstein/findingaids/petersonmichael/ |date=October 20, 2014 }}. David M. Rubenstein Rare Book & Manuscript Library, Duke University (duke.edu/rubenstein). Retrieved October 19, 2014.</ref>\n}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Worldcat id|lccn-n89667130}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Peterson, Michael}}\n[[Category:20th-century American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American novelists]]\n[[Category:1943 births]]\n[[Category:American columnists]]\n[[Category:American expatriates in Germany]]\n[[Category:American male non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:American male novelists]]\n[[Category:United States Marine Corps personnel of the Vietnam War]]\n[[Category:American people convicted of murder]]\n[[Category:American prisoners sentenced to life imprisonment]]\n[[Category:Bisexual men]]\n[[Category:Bisexual writers]]\n[[Category:Duke University alumni]]\n[[Category:LGBT novelists]]\n[[Category:LGBT writers from the United States]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Novelists from North Carolina]]\n[[Category:Overturned convictions in the United States]]\n[[Category:People convicted of murder by North Carolina]]\n[[Category:People from Nashville, Tennessee]]\n[[Category:People who entered an Alford plea]]\n[[Category:Peterson family]]\n[[Category:Prisoners sentenced to life imprisonment by North Carolina]]\n[[Category:United States Marine Corps officers]]\n[[Category:Writers from Durham, North Carolina]]\n", "name_user": "2605:6000:b840:8600:a8ca:4177:933a:a5fa", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Michael_Peterson_(criminal)"}
{"title_page": "List of nature reserves in the London Borough of Barnet", "text_new": "{{featured list}}\n[[File:Beech Hill Lake.jpg|thumb|Beech Hill Lake in [[Monken Hadley Common]]|350px|alt=Beech Hill Lake in Monken Hadley Common ]]\nThe [[London Borough of Barnet]], on the northern outskirts of London, is mainly residential, but it has large areas of green space and farmland. The spread of suburban development into the countryside was halted by the designation of a statutory [[Metropolitan Green Belt|Green Belt]] around London after the Second World War, and almost one third of Barnet's area of {{convert|8663|ha|acre}} is Green Belt. Without this control, Barnet would be very different today, and this list of nature reserves would be much shorter.<ref>Hewlett, pp. 2, 11\u201313</ref>\n\nMost of Barnet lies over [[London Clay]], which is poor for agriculture, and open land is mainly used for activities such as horse grazing, playing fields, parks and golf courses. Features of the traditional agricultural landscape have survived, such as old hedgerows, ancient trees and areas of herb-rich grassland. Some hay meadows have a large diversity of wild flowers, and the [[London Ecology Unit]] (LEU){{efn|The London Ecology Unit was established to provide advice to London boroughs following the abolition of the [[Greater London Council]] in 1986. In 2000 it was abolished and absorbed into the [[Greater London Authority]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wildlondon.org.uk/activism-for-change|publisher=London Wildlife Trust|title=Activism for Change|accessdate=16 July 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121025102530/http://www.wildlondon.org.uk/activism-for-change|archivedate=25 October 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://legacy.london.gov.uk/mayor/strategies/biodiversity/docs/Building_Green_main_text.pdf|publisher=Mayor of London|title=Building Green: A guide to using plants on roofs, walls and pavements|isbn=1 85261 637 7|year=2004|accessdate=16 July 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120816005511/http://legacy.london.gov.uk/mayor/strategies/biodiversity/docs/Building_Green_main_text.pdf|archivedate=16 August 2012}}</ref>}} described them as one of Barnet's most important ecological assets.<ref>Hewlett, pp. 2\u20133, 6</ref>\n\nBarnet has large areas with designations intended to protect them from \"inappropriate development\", and to \"provide the strongest protection for the preservation of Barnet's green and natural open spaces\". As well as {{convert|2466|ha|acre}} of Green Belt, Barnet has another {{convert|690|ha|acre}} of [[Metropolitan Open Land]], which receive a similar level of protection. [[Watling Chase Community Forest]]{{efn|[[Community forests in England|Community Forests']] objects include revitalising derelict land, providing new leisure facilities, preparing for climate change and increasing biodiversity.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.communityforest.org.uk/aboutenglandsforests.htm|title=About England\u2019s Community Forests|publisher=England\u2019s Community Forests|accessdate=14 November 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151117030515/http://www.communityforest.org.uk/aboutenglandsforests.htm|archivedate=17 November 2015}}</ref>}} covers {{convert|72|sqmi|sqkm}}, extending north and west from Totteridge into south Hertfordshire.<ref>Barnet Unitary Development Plan, Chapter 5, pp. 65\u201367, 83\u201384</ref>\n\nIn 1992 Barnet Council commissioned the LEU to carry out a survey of wildlife habitats in the borough, which looked at green sites covering {{convert|4055|ha|acre}}, 45% of the borough. In 1997 the LEU published ''Nature Conservation in Barnet'', which described 67 [[Site of Nature Conservation Interest|Sites of Importance for Nature Conservation]] (SINCs).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.london.gov.uk/priorities/environment/greening-london/biodiversity/sites-importance-nature-conservation|title=Sites of Importance for Nature Conservation|publisher=[[Mayor of London]]|accessdate=24 February 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130119130405/http://london.gov.uk/priorities/environment/greening-london/biodiversity/sites-importance-nature-conservation|archivedate=19 January 2013}}</ref><ref>Hewlett, pp. 14\u201315</ref> This formed the basis of Barnet's nature conservation policies in its 2006 ''Unitary Development Plan'', designated as \"a material planning consideration\" to be used as \"non-statutory guidance\".<ref>Barnet Unitary Development Plan, Chapter 5, p. 79</ref> The table below lists SINCs described in ''Nature Conservation in Barnet''.<ref name=NCB>Hewlett et al, ''Nature Conservation in Barnet''</ref>{{efn|''Nature Conservation in Barnet'' lists 67 sites, but only 66 are shown in this table because Grahame Park SINC no longer exists. It has been re-modelled and renamed Heybourne Park.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://barnet.moderngov.co.uk/documents/s260/Regeneration%20New%20Dwellings%20Report%20FINAL.pdf|format=pdf|title=Budget and Performance Overview and Scrutiny Committee: Number of New Dwellings Started on Regeneration Schemes \u2013 Performance Update|date=15 March 2012|publisher=London Borough of Barnet|accessdate=15 February 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305003457/http://barnet.moderngov.co.uk/documents/s260/Regeneration%20New%20Dwellings%20Report%20FINAL.pdf|archivedate=5 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaL02&sType=sinc|title=Grahame Park|publisher=Greenspace Information for Greater London|year=2013|accessdate=16 August 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141218191918/http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaL02&sType=sinc|archivedate=18 December 2014}}</ref> The sites were listed on the [[Mayor of London]]'s Wildweb website, which was taken down in December 2010. In spring 2012 it was replaced by a new site hosted by [[Greenspace Information for Greater London]] (GiGL), London's environmental record centre.<ref>{{cite web|first=Boris|last=Johnson|url=http://london.gov.uk/mqt/public/question.do?id=39724|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130917102952/http://london.gov.uk/mqt/public/question.do?id=39724|url-status=dead|archive-date=17 September 2013|title=London Wildweb site|publisher=The London Assembly|date=25 January 2012|accessdate=17 September 2013}}</ref> This new website covers most SINCs, but others are left out, some which are not publicly accessible and others in error. Wildweb included maps of every site, but ''Nature Conservation in Barnet'' only has maps of the most important ones, the 'Sites of Metropolitan Importance'. GiGL has maps for the sites it lists,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/|title=iGiGL the data portal of Greenspace Information for London|publisher=Greenspace Information for Greater London|year=2013|accessdate=14 August 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140114132930/http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/|archivedate=14 January 2014}}</ref> but the only map for the other sites is the map of the whole borough inside the back cover of ''Nature Conservation in Barnet''. The list of SINCs in ''Nature Conservation in Barnet'' has not been updated and is still the basis for GiGL's database.}} SINCs do not have statutory protection, but some sites are also wholly or partly designated as [[Site of Special Scientific Interest|Sites of Special Scientific Interest]]{{efn|There are 36 [[List of Sites of Special Scientific Interest in Greater London|Sites of Special Scientific Interest in Greater London]]. The only one in Barnet is Brent Reservoir.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sssi.naturalengland.org.uk/special/sssi/searchresults.cfm?sssi_name=&frmcounty=1017|publisher=Natural England|title=Sites of Special Scientific Interest, Search results for Greater London|accessdate=24 February 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121024044922/http://www.sssi.naturalengland.org.uk/special/sssi/searchresults.cfm?sssi_name=&frmcounty=1017|archivedate=24 October 2012}}</ref> Darland's Lake was formerly an SSSI but the designation was withdrawn when it was found that the rare [[fritillaries]] on the site had probably been planted.<ref>Hewlett, p. 53</ref>}} or [[local nature reserve]]s,{{efn|[[Natural England]] lists 141 [[local nature reserve]]s in Greater London. Seven of these are in Barnet, but two of these are divided into separate SINCs. Scratchwood and Moat Mount is one LNR but two SINCs, and the same applies to Coppett's Wood and Glebelands. Nine SINCs are thus also LNRs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lnr.naturalengland.org.uk/special/lnr/lnr_results.asp?N=&C=17&Submit=Search |publisher=Natural England |title=Local Nature Reserves, Search Results for Greater London |accessdate=24 February 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927113247/http://www.lnr.naturalengland.org.uk/special/lnr/lnr_results.asp?N=&C=17&Submit=Search |archivedate=27 September 2013 }}</ref>}} which do have statutory protection.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.naturalengland.org.uk/ourwork/conservation/designations/lnr/default.aspx|publisher=Natural England|title=Local Nature Reserves|accessdate=22 September 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130923032955/http://www.naturalengland.org.uk/ourwork/conservation/designations/lnr/default.aspx|archivedate=23 September 2013}}</ref> According to a report of the [[Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs]], 39% of Barnet's SINCs were \"in positive conservation management\" in 2009\u201310. Barnet Council did not supply figures for 2010\u201311, 2011\u201312 or 2012\u201313.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/env10-local-sites-in-positive-conservation-management|title=Nature Conservation: Local Sites in Positive Conservation Management in England, 2008/9 to 2012/13|accessdate=2 February 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140219080420/https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/env10-local-sites-in-positive-conservation-management|archivedate=19 February 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Nature reserves==\n\n===Key===\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n;Access\n* '''P '''  = free public access to all or most of the site\n* '''PP''' = free public access to part of the site\n* '''PL''' = public at limited times\n* '''F '''  = access on public footpaths only\n* '''V '''  = can be viewed from adjacent paths or roads only\n* '''NO''' = no public access\n{{col-2}}\n;Type\n* '''M '''    = Site of Metropolitan Importance \u2013 the best examples of London's habitats, or which contain rare species<ref name=Hewlett27>Hewlett, p. 27</ref>\n* '''B1 '''   = Site of Borough Importance Grade 1 \u2013 of significant value to the borough<ref name=Hewlett27/>\n* '''B2 '''   = Site of Borough Importance, Grade 2 \u2013 as B1, but not as important<ref name=Hewlett27/>\n* '''L '''    = Site of local importance \u2013 of particular value to nearby residents or schools<ref name=Hewlett27/>\n* '''LNR '''  = [[Local nature reserve]] \u2013 of special interest locally for wildlife or geological features<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lnr.naturalengland.org.uk/special/lnr/office.htm|title=Local Nature Reserves|publisher=Natural England|accessdate=7 March 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130525090416/http://www.lnr.naturalengland.org.uk/special/lnr/office.htm|archivedate=25 May 2013}}</ref>\n* '''SSSI''' = [[Site of Special Scientific Interest]] \u2013 the country's best wildlife and geological sites<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.naturalengland.org.uk/ourwork/conservation/designations/sssi/default.aspx|publisher=Natural England|title=Sites of Special Scientific Interest|accessdate=7 March 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130314103950/http://www.naturalengland.org.uk/ourwork/conservation/designations/sssi/default.aspx|archivedate=14 March 2013}}</ref>\n* '''CL'''  = [[Common land|registered common land]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archive.defra.gov.uk/rural/documents/protected/common-land/biosurvey-glondon.pdf |title=The Common Lands of Greater London: A Biological Survey |publisher=[[Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs]] |accessdate=24 February 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20130402151656/http://archive.defra.gov.uk/rural/documents/protected/common-land/biosurvey-glondon.pdf |archivedate=2 April 2013 }}</ref> \u2013 free public access to all of site<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.naturalengland.org.uk/ourwork/access/openaccess/default.aspx|publisher=Natural England|title=Open Access land|accessdate=25 February 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130201131041/http://www.naturalengland.org.uk/ourwork/access/openaccess/default.aspx|archivedate=1 February 2013}}</ref>\n{{col-end}}\n{{kml}}\n\n===Sites===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"width:98%\"\n!scope=\"col\" | Site\n!scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\"| Photograph\n!scope=\"col\" | Hectares{{efn|The figures for area are taken from ''Nature Conservation in Barnet''.}}\n!scope=\"col\" | Location{{efn|The grid references are taken from ''Nature Conservation in Barnet''. Click on the grid reference and then select a map to see the location of the reserve.}}\n!scope=\"col\" | Access\n!scope=\"col\" | Type\n!scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\"| Description\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Arkley Lane and Pastures]]\n|[[File:Arkley Lane.JPG|100px|alt=Arkley Lane in autumn]]|| 52 || [[Arkley]] <br/><small>{{coord|51.655|-0.230   |type:landmark_region:GB|name= Arkley Lane and Pastures   }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 225 965}}</small>|| PP || B2 || The site covers Arkley Lane, a neighbouring woodland and fields on either side. The lane, now a quiet country path, is thought to be an old drovers' road. The hedges have massive gnarled oak trees, lofty ash and mature field maples, while the hedge bottoms have a diverse range of plants. The woodland is probably ancient, and supports a variety of nesting birds.<ref>Hewlett, p. 83</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Arkley South Fields]]\n|[[File:Arkley South Field.JPG|100px|alt=Birds in Arkley South Field]]|| 38 || [[Arkley]] <br/><small>{{coord|  51.641|-0.232 |type:landmark_region:GB|name=  Arkley South Fields  }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 224 951}}</small> || V  || B2 ||This is an extensive area of open grassland crossed by ditches and with mature hedgerows. Its importance lies in its breeding grassland birds, including [[Eurasian skylark|skylarks]] and [[meadow pipit]]s, and it is the main site in the borough for these species. Skylarks have declined in recent years, and they are a priority species in the UK Biodiversity Action Plan.<ref>Hewlett, pp. 84\u201385</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://jncc.defra.gov.uk/page-5163|publisher=Joint Nature Conservation Committee, Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs|title=UK Biodiversity Action Plan priority bird species|accessdate=7 March 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130513164420/http://jncc.defra.gov.uk/page-5163|archivedate=13 May 2013}}\n</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Arrandene Open Space and Featherstone Hill]] \n|[[File:Arrandene Open Space.JPG|alt=Arrandene Open Space|100px]]|| 25 || [[Mill Hill]] <br/><small>{{coord| 51.613|-0.230  |type:landmark_region:GB|name=   Arrandene Open Space and Featherstone Hill }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 226 920}}</small>|| P || M ||This site's fields, which are divided by ancient hedgerows, were rated by the LEU as one of the best examples of old hay meadows in London. Wild flowers are abundant in the summer, with each field having its own specialities. The woods and scrub are important habitats for birds.<ref>Hewlett, pp. 41\u201343</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=M038&sType=sinc|title=Arrandene Open Space and Featherstone Hill|publisher=Greenspace Information for Greater London|year=2013|accessdate=16 August 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927012410/http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=M038&sType=sinc|archivedate=27 September 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Ashley Lane (Hendon)|Ashley Lane]]\n|[[File:Ashley Lane.JPG|100px|alt=Ashley Lane in autumn]]|| 1 || [[Hendon]]<br/><small> {{coord| 51.601|-0.217  |type:landmark_region:GB|name=  Ashley Lane  }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 236 906}}</small>|| P || B2 ||This ancient trackway is over 400 years old. It has retained its ancient hedgerows along much of its length. Old oak and ash trees line the lane, and there are also some [[Sorbus torminalis|wild service-trees]]. The hedgerows have diverse shrub species.<ref>Hewlett, p. 76</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Avenue House Grounds]] \n|[[File:Avenue House Grounds pond.JPG|100px|alt=Ornamental pond in Avenue House Grounds]]||  3.5 || [[Church End, Barnet|Church End]]<br/><small> {{coord|  51.5975|-0.1937 |type:landmark_region:GB|name=    Avenue House Grounds }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 251 902}}</small>|| P || L || This small public park is the garden of [[Avenue House]]. It has a terrace with ornamental plants and a rockery. There is a pond which has [[Ceratophyllum|hornwort]], [[yellow iris]] and water-lilies, together with [[common frog]]s and [[koi carp]]. There are large areas of shrubbery.<ref name=\"Hewlett, p. 89\">Hewlett, p. 89</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Barfield Allotments Nature Park]]\n|[[File:Barfield Allotments Nature Park.JPG|100px|alt=Barfield Allotments Nature Park]]||  0.9 || [[Whetstone, London|Whetstone]]<br/><small> {{coord| 51.627|-0.158  |type:landmark_region:GB|name= Barfield Allotments Nature Park   }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 276 935}}</small>|| V || L || This small wildlife site is adjacent to a playground. Its scrub and grassland provide a haven for [[common lizard]]s and [[slowworm]]s, both legally protected species.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaL21&sType=sinc|title=Barfield Allotments Nature Park|publisher=Greenspace Information for Greater London|year=2013|accessdate=16 August 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927012346/http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaL21&sType=sinc|archivedate=27 September 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Barnet Countryside Centre]]\n|[[File:Barnet Countryside Centre from Byng Road.JPG|100px|alt=View of Barnet Countryside Centre from Byng Road]]|| 2.8  || [[Chipping Barnet|High Barnet]]<br/><small> {{coord| 51.658|-0.216  |type:landmark_region:GB|name=   Countryside Centre }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 234 969}}</small>|| V || L || The centre was established in the 1970s to provide schoolchildren with contact with farm animals and wildlife. After a period of closure the now renamed Barnet Environment Centre operates a full programme of environmental education visits for school children from Nursery to A level. Its woodland has a wide range of birds. Ponds support aquatic life and more open areas have a wide variety of insects.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaL04&sType=sinc|title=Barnet Countryside Centre|publisher=Greenspace Information for Greater London|year=2013|accessdate=16 August 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927012405/http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaL04&sType=sinc|archivedate=27 September 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fobcc.org.uk/drupal/|title=Home page|publisher=Friends of the Barnet Countryside Centre|accessdate=22 March 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080924032209/http://www.fobcc.org.uk/drupal/|archivedate=24 September 2008}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Bell's Hill Burial Ground]] \n|[[File:Bells Hill Burial Ground 2.JPG|100px|alt=Bells Hill Burial Ground]]|| 2.8 || [[Chipping Barnet|High Barnet]]<br/><small> {{coord| 51.649|-0.215  |type:landmark_region:GB|name=  Bell's Hill Burial Ground  }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 235 959}}</small>|| P || L ||This small cemetery has mown grass in the western part, but in the east it is less managed, and has a wide variety of wild flowers. The LEU described it as a fine site for butterflies, including [[Gatekeeper (butterfly)|gatekeeper]], [[small skipper]] and [[meadow brown]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaL05&sType=sinc|title=Bell's Hill Burial Ground|publisher=Greenspace Information for Greater London|year=2013|accessdate=16 August 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927012401/http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaL05&sType=sinc|archivedate=27 September 2013}}</ref><ref>Hewlett, p. 88</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Belmont Open Space, Cockfosters]] \n|[[File:Belmont Open Space Cockfosters.JPG|100px|alt=Belmont Open Space]]||  1.0 || [[Cockfosters]]<br/><small> {{coord| 51.647|-0.157  |type:landmark_region:GB|name= Belmont Open Space   }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 275 958}}</small>|| P || L || This site is a secluded small park, which has a fair number of wild flowers and mature trees, together with an old hedgerow. The local [[Royal Society for the Protection of Birds]] has recorded a wide range of birds for a small suburban park.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaL22&sType=sinc|title=Belmont Open Space, Cockfosters|publisher=Greenspace Information for Greater London|year=2013|accessdate=16 August 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927012322/http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaL22&sType=sinc|archivedate=27 September 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Big Wood and Little Wood]]\n|[[File:Big Wood, N2.JPG|100px|alt=A path in Big Wood in spring]]|| 8.6  || [[Hampstead Garden Suburb]] <br/><small>{{coord|  51.583| -0.190 |type:landmark_region:GB|name=  Big Wood  }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 255 887}}<BR/>{{coord|  51.586| -0.193 |type:landmark_region:GB|name=  Little Wood  }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 253 890}}</small>|| P || B1 LNR || These woods are remnants of an ancient large forest. Big Wood has a wide variety of trees and shrubs, with [[pedunculate oak]] the dominant species. There are several old [[Sorbus torminalis|wild service-trees]]. All the common woodland species of birds are present in the woods, and Little Wood has a small theatre.<ref>Hewlett, pp. 57\u201358</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Brent Reservoir|Brent Reservoir (Welsh Harp)]]\n|[[File:Brent Res view.JPG|100px|alt=Brent Reservoir]]|| 46{{efn|Brent Reservoir is partly in the [[London Borough of Brent]], and 46 hectares out of the total of 96 is in Barnet.}} || [[Hendon]]<br/><small> {{coord| 51.571 |-0.245  |type:landmark_region:GB|name=   Brent Reservoir }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 215 871}}</small>|| P || M LNR SSSI || Brent Reservoir is Barnet's only [[Site of Special Scientific Interest]]. It is an important breeding site for waterfowl and other birds, including one of Britain's largest breeding populations of [[great crested grebe]]. It has many uncommon wetland plants and insects, including over forty rare species of invertebrates. It is also one of the few London sites with [[Eurasian water shrew|water shrews]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=M035&sType=sinc|title=Brent Reservoir (Welsh Harp)|publisher=Greenspace Information for Greater London|year=2013|accessdate=16 August 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927012412/http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=M035&sType=sinc|archivedate=27 September 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Moat Mount Open Space and Mote End Farm#Bruno's Field|Bruno's Field]]\n|[[File:Bruno's Field.JPG|100px|alt=Bruno's Field is hidden behind houses, and this is a view of trees in the field from Worcester Crescent]] || 6.6  || [[Mill Hill]] <br/><small>{{coord|  51.626| -0.246 |type:landmark_region:GB|name=   Bruno's Field }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 215 934}}</small>|| NO || B2 || This steeply sloping site has a varied topography. On higher ground there are dry areas, while lower down there are areas of bog crossed by several small streams. The field has typical pasture herbs, a scattering of mature trees and a wide variety of birds.<ref>Hewlett, p. 72</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Burtonhole Lane and Pasture]]\n|[[File:Burtonhole Lane.JPG|100px|alt=Burtonhole Lane]]|| 8.5  || [[Mill Hill]] <br/><small>{{coord| 51.620|-0.207  |type:landmark_region:GB|name=   Burtonhole Lane and Pasture }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 242 927}}</small>|| PP || B2 || Burtonhole Lane is an old green lane which is now a bridleway and footpath. Its hedgerow has several species of trees, such as [[Sorbus torminalis|wild service-tree]] and [[Dioscorea communis|black bryony]], which suggest that it is ancient, and its verge is rich in wild flowers. The pasture area is dominated by [[Holcus lanatus|Yorkshire Fog]]. It is crossed by Burtonhole Brook, which supports a number of uncommon plant species.<ref>Hewlett, pp. 76\u201377</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Cherry Tree Wood]] \n|[[File:Cherry Tree Wood 2.JPG|alt=Cherry Tree Wood in winter|100px]]|| 4.7  || [[East Finchley]] <br/><small>{{coord|  51.586|-0.160 |type:landmark_region:GB|name=  Cherry Tree Wood  }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 275 890}}</small>|| P || L || This local park was once part of the [[Bishop of London]]'s Great Hornsey Park. it has an inner area of lawn with a playground and tennis courts, which is surrounded by the surviving ancient woodland. Its tree canopy is mainly oak and hornbeam, and its sparse undergrowth has a number of species associated with ancient woodland, such as [[Allium ursinum|wild garlic]] and [[wood-sedge]].<ref>Hewlett, p. 92</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Clarefield Park]]\n|[[File:Clarefield Park.JPG|100px|alt=Clarefield Park in spring]]|| 3.2  || [[Brent Cross]] <br/><small>{{coord| 51.572|-0.221  |type:landmark_region:GB|name=  Clarefield Park  }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 232 874}}</small>|| P || L || This small park has mown grass, a children's playground, scented shrubs and a small wildlife pond.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaL16&sType=sinc|title=Clarefield Park|publisher=Greenspace Information for Greater London|year=2013|accessdate=16 August 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927012408/http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaL16&sType=sinc|archivedate=27 September 2013}}</ref> In October 2010 Barnet Council gave planning consent for the [[Brent Cross#Development|Brent Cross Cricklewood Planning Application]], which includes closure of the Clarefield Park and development of the area.<ref>Planning report PDU/1483/01, Greater London Authority, 11 February 2009, p. 41</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.barnet.gov.uk/info/940028/cricklewood_brent_cross/530/cricklewood_brent_cross|title=Cricklewood Brent Cross|publisher=London Borough of Barnet|accessdate=18 February 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130508053629/http://www.barnet.gov.uk/info/940028/cricklewood_brent_cross/530/cricklewood_brent_cross|archivedate=8 May 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Clay Lane]]\n|[[File:Clay Lane.JPG|100px|alt=Clay Lane]]|| 1.8 || [[Edgware]] <br/><small>{{coord|   51.630|-0.273|type:landmark_region:GB|name=   Clay Lane }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 194 939}}</small>|| P || L || This is an ancient green lane which leads from Edgwarebury into the Hertfordshire countryside. An old hedge bank and herbaceous plants associated with ancient woodland suggest that it is of considerable antiquity. Its canopy has fine old oaks above an understorey of [[midland hawthorn]], [[blackthorn]] and hazel.<ref name=\"Hewlett, p. 86\">Hewlett, p. 86</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Clitterhouse Recreation Ground]]\n|[[File:Clitterhouse Recreation Ground.JPG|100px|alt=Clitterhouse Recreation Ground]]|| 16 || [[Brent Cross]]<br/><small> {{coord| 51.569|-0.215  |type:landmark_region:GB|name= Clitterhouse Recreation Ground   }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 238 871}}</small>|| P || L || This large recreation ground is managed as a sports field, and its main wildlife interest is in the unmanaged perimeter which has species such as crab apple which are typical of ancient hedgerows.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaL06&sType=sinc|title=Clitterhouse Recreation Ground|publisher=Greenspace Information for Greater London|year=2013|accessdate=16 August 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927012414/http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaL06&sType=sinc|archivedate=27 September 2013}}</ref> The Brent Cross Cricklewood scheme includes improvements to the Recreation Ground.<ref>Planning report PDU/1483/01, p. 4</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[College Farm]]\n|[[File:College Farm2009.JPG|100px|alt=College Farm driveway]]|| 4.5  || [[Finchley]]<br/><small> {{coord| 51.593|-0.202  |type:landmark_region:GB|name=  College Farm  }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 246 897}}</small>|| PP || L || College Farm in central Finchley was a working farm open to the public from 1980 until the foot and mouth epidemic in 2001. A charitable trust purchased the site in 2006, but as of March 2013 efforts to re-open the farm have failed, and the farm buildings are an equestrian shop. The site has trees and scrub which provide a habitat for birds, and [[pipistrelle bats]] have been recorded.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaL14&sType=sinc|title=College Farm|publisher=Greenspace Information for Greater London|year=2013|accessdate=16 August 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927012351/http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaL14&sType=sinc|archivedate=27 September 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Coppett's Wood and Scrublands|Coppett's Wood and Scrublands Local Nature Reserve]]\n|[[File:Coppett's Wood.JPG|100px|alt=Path in Coppett's Wood]]|| 12 || [[Colney Hatch]]<br/><small> {{coord|   51.609|-0.157|type:landmark_region:GB|name=  Coppett's Wood and Scrublands  }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 277 915}}</small>|| P || B1 LNR || These sites provide a range of wildlife habitats. Coppett's Wood has a population of [[juneberry]], and a pond which has [[yellow iris]] and breeding [[common frog]]s and [[smooth newt]]s. Scrublands is on the site of a former sewage works. It has a number of rare plant and insect species.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaBI06&sType=sinc|title=Coppett's Wood and Scrublands Local Nature Reserve|publisher=Greenspace Information for Greater London|year=2013|accessdate=16 August 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131022204028/http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaBI06&sType=sinc|archivedate=22 October 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Copthall Railway Walk and Copthall Old Common]]\n|[[File:Copthall Railway Walk.JPG|100px|alt=The path of the old railway line along Copthall Railway Walk]]|| 11  || [[Mill Hill]]<br/><small> {{coord| 51.607|-0.223  |type:landmark_region:GB|name=  Copthall Railway Walk and Copthall Old Common  }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 231 912}}</small>|| P || B2 || This is a green path along an old railway line, with Copthall Old Common at one side. The grassland on the walk is mostly [[false oat-grass]], with a wide diversity of wild flowers. The hedges have some fine old oaks and areas of bluebells. A pond on the common has [[yellow iris]] and [[water-starwort]]. The site also has a range of birds and invertebrates, including [[Lampyris noctiluca|glow-worm]]s, a scarce and declining species.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaBII11&sType=sinc|title=Copthall Railway Walk and Copthall Old Common|publisher=Greenspace Information for Greater London|year=2013|accessdate=16 August 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927012334/http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaBII11&sType=sinc|archivedate=27 September 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Copthall South Fields]]\n|[[File:Copthall South Fields hedgrerow.JPG|100px|alt=Hedgerow in Copthall South Fields]]|| 6  || [[Mill Hill]] <br/><small>{{coord|  51.602|-0.233 |type:landmark_region:GB|name=   Copthall South Fields }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 225 908}}</small>|| P || L || The fields have what the LEU described as \"a surprisingly rural quality\", even though they lie alongside the [[A1 in London|A1 road]]. The hedgerow trees are oak, ash and [[field maple]], and the fields contain flowers typical of clay grassland, such as [[Lathyrus pratensis|meadow vetchling]], [[Ranunculus acris|meadow buttercup]] and [[Sorrel|common sorrel]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaL23&sType=sinc|title=Copthall South Fields|publisher=Greenspace Information for Greater London|year=2013|accessdate=16 August 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927012336/http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaL23&sType=sinc|archivedate=27 September 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Deans Brook]] and [[Stoneyfields Park]] \n! scope=\"row\"| [[File:Deans Brook.JPG|100px|alt=Deans Brook in Stoneyfields Park]]\n||3.3  || [[Edgware]] <br/><small>{{coord|  51.625|-0.263 |type:landmark_region:GB|name=   Deans Brook and Stoneyfields Park }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 203 929}}</small>|| PP || B2 || [[Kingfisher]]s and [[grey wagtail]]s are often seen along the two kilometre Deans Brook, which largely follows a natural course. In Stoneyfields Park it has been widened into an ornamental lake, which has a wide fringe of tall water plants such as [[Typha latifolia|great]] and [[Typha angustifolia|lesser reedmace]], and breeding birds such as coots, moorhens and mallards. The woodland in the park is oak and hazel, and the hedgerows have plants which show that it is ancient, such as [[Carex sylvatica|wood-sedge]] and [[Allium ursinum|ramsons]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaBII03&sType=sinc|title=Deans Brook and Stoneyfields Park|publisher=Greenspace Information for Greater London|year=2013|accessdate=16 August 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927012349/http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaBII03&sType=sinc|archivedate=27 September 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Drivers Hill]]\n|[[File:Drivers Hill field.JPG|100px|alt=Drivers Hill]] || 10 || [[Mill Hill]]<br/><small> {{coord| 51.616|-0.221  |type:landmark_region:GB|name=  Drivers Hill  }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 231 920}}</small>|| V || B2 || This site consists of several fields and two small woods. The pasture areas have a variety of grasses and wild flowers, including some typical of old pasture, such as [[Cynosurus cristatus|crested dog's-tail]] and [[Carex leporina|oval sedge]]. Wetter areas have plants such as [[Deschampsia cespitosa|tufted hair-grass]] and [[Lotus pedunculatus|greater bird's-foot-trefoil]], while the woods are mainly oak, ash and sycamore.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaBII10&sType=sinc|title=Drivers Hill|publisher=Greenspace Information for Greater London|year=2013|accessdate=16 August 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927012340/http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaBII10&sType=sinc|archivedate=27 September 2013}}</ref> \n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[East Finchley Cemetery]]\n|[[File:East Finchley cemetery.jpg|100px|alt=Chapel and gravestones in East Finchley Cemetery]]||  16|| [[East Finchley]]<br/><small> {{coord|  51.592|-0.184 |type:landmark_region:GB|name=  East Finchley Cemetery  }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 258 896}}</small>|| P || L || Most of this cemetery is formally managed, but it has some old oaks which have survived from its rural past, and evergreen trees such as [[Cedrus libani|cedar of Lebanon]] and [[Sequoiadendron giganteum|Wellingtonia]] provide a habitat for [[goldcrest]] and [[coal tit]]. In less managed areas there are wild flowers such as [[Pimpinella saxifraga|burnet saxifrage]], and around the edges of the site ash and sycamore are evolving into woodland.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaL08&sType=sinc|title=East Finchley Cemetery|publisher=Greenspace Information for Greater London|year=2013|accessdate=16 August 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927012356/http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaL08&sType=sinc|archivedate=27 September 2013}}</ref> \n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Edgware Way Grassland|Edgware Way Rough]] \n|[[File:Edgware Way Grassland.JPG|100px|alt=Edgware Way Rough]]|| 5.5  || [[Edgware]] <br/><small>{{coord|  51.625|-0.288 |type:landmark_region:GB|name= Edgware Way Rough   }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 185 932}}</small>|| F || M || This site is [[London Clay]] pasture which has not been cultivated for many years. In areas of damp grassland it has London's largest population of the herb [[Sanguisorba officinalis|great burnet]], and other rare plants characteristic of old meadows include [[Achillea ptarmica|sneezewort]] and [[Succisa pratensis|devil's-bit scabious]]. Breeding birds include the [[yellowhammer]] and [[spotted flycatcher]], both of which are declining species.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=M126&sType=sinc|title=Edgware Way Rough|publisher=Greenspace Information for Greater London|year=2013|accessdate=16 August 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927012332/http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=M126&sType=sinc|archivedate=27 September 2013}}</ref> \n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Edgwarebury Brook]]\n|[[File:Edgwarebury Brook in Edgwarebury Park.JPG|100px|alt=Edgwarebury Brook in Edgwarebury Park]]||  5 || [[Edgware]]<br/><small> {{coord|  51.624|-0.284 |type:landmark_region:GB|name=   Edgwarebury Brook }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 188 935}}</small>|| V || B2 || This stream rises among fields and flows through Edgware Way Rough on to suburban Edgware, where it join Deans Brook. The most important section ecologically is the upper part, which was rated by the LEU as one of the best areas of wetland vegetation in Barnet. There is a mass of [[Glyceria fluitans|floating sweet-grass]] with clumps of [[Veronica beccabunga|brooklime]] and [[Persicaria hydropiper|water pepper]]. The banks have clumps of [[Persicaria hydropiper|great willowherb]] and [[Bidens tripartita|trifid bur-marigold]].<ref name=\"Hewlett, p. 67\">Hewlett, p. 67</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Edgwarebury Park]]\n|[[File:Edgwarebury Park.JPG|100px|alt=Edgwarebury Park]]|| 15  || [[Edgware]]<br/><small> {{coord| 51.625|-0.283  |type:landmark_region:GB|name=   Edgwarebury Park }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 190 934}}</small>|| P || L || The hedgerows in this large park have fine oak and ash trees, and the presence of [[Sorbus torminalis|wild service-trees]] is considered an indicator that the hedges are ancient. It has a variety of wild flowers in damp areas and nesting birds include [[song thrush]], [[mistle thrush]], [[great spotted woodpecker]] and [[common whitethroat]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaL19&sType=sinc|title=Edgwarebury Park|publisher=Greenspace Information for Greater London|year=2013|accessdate=16 August 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927012358/http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaL19&sType=sinc|archivedate=27 September 2013}}</ref> \n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Folly Brook]] and [[Darland's Lake Nature Reserve]]\n|[[File:Darlands Lake 2.JPG|100px|alt=Darland's Lake]]|| 11  || [[Arkley]]/[[Woodside Park (Barnet, London)|Woodside Park]]<br/><small> {{coord| 51.625|-0.205  |type:landmark_region:GB|name=  Folly Brook and Darland's Lake Nature Reserve  }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 240 934}}</small>|| P || B1 || Darland's Lake, which is now a nature reserve, was originally an ornamental feature created by damming Folly Brook. The water quality is good, and Darland's Lake has extensive reed beds. On its margin there is a boggy wood of willows and alder, a scarce habitat in London. The site has a number of tree species typical of ancient woodland, and a diverse bird and invertebrate population, while eighteen species of mammal have been recorded.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaBI02&sType=sinc|title=Folly Brook and Darland's Lake Nature Reserve|publisher=Greenspace Information for Greater London|year=2013|accessdate=16 August 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927012354/http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaBI02&sType=sinc|archivedate=27 September 2013}}</ref> \n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Friary Park]]\n|[[File:Friary Park formal garden.JPG|100px|alt=Formal garden in Friary Park]]|| 8.8 || [[Friern Barnet]] <br/><small>{{coord| 51.618|-0.162  |type:landmark_region:GB|name= Friary Park   }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 273 926}}</small>|| P || L || Old oak trees date from before the foundation of the park, and they support woodland birds such as [[nuthatch]] and [[treecreeper]]. Near a small stream, a tributary of [[Pymme's Brook]], there are wildflowers such as [[Anthriscus sylvestris|cow parsley]], [[lesser celandine]], [[Viola riviniana|dog violet]] and [[Alliaria petiolata|garlic mustard]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaL12&sType=sinc|title=Friary Park|publisher=Greenspace Information for Greater London|year=2013|accessdate=16 August 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927012343/http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaL12&sType=sinc|archivedate=27 September 2013}}</ref> \n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Glebe Lane Pastures]]\n|[[File:Glebe Lane Pastures.JPG|100px|alt=Horses grazing in Glebe Lane Pastures]]|| 11  || [[Arkley]]<br/><small> {{coord|   51.645|-0.234|type:landmark_region:GB|name=   Glebe Lane Pastures }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 223 954}}</small>|| V || B1 ||This is an area of five fields which was once part of a communal pasture called Barnet Common. The grassland is unimproved clay grassland, a relic of the old common. It has many species of wild flowers, and the most important aspect of the site is its diverse old meadow plants. Some of the rarities have been found in temporary pools, such as [[Minuartia stricta|bog stitchwort]] and [[Ranunculus peltatus|pond]] and [[Ranunculus hederaceus|ivy-leaved crowfoot]].<ref>Hewlett, p. 52</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Glebelands Local Nature Reserve]]\n|[[File:Glebelands.JPG|100px|alt=Glebelands nature reserves]]||  7.5 || [[Colney Hatch]] <br/><small>{{coord| 51.604|-0.169 |type:landmark_region:GB|name=Glebelands Local Nature Reserve}} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 270 911}}</small>|| P || B1 LNR || This is a fragment of the old [[Finchley Common]]. It has tall scrub and woodland, together with numerous streams and seasonal ponds. The pools have a number of rare species, and it is the only known London site for [[lesser water-plantain]]. Other rarities are thread-leaved water-crowfoot (''[[Ranunculus trichophyllus]]'') and [[Veronica scutellata|marsh speedwell]], and the site has diverse breeding birds.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaBI07&sType=sinc|title=Glebelands Local Nature Reserve|publisher=Greenspace Information for Greater London|year=2013|accessdate=16 August 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927012338/http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaBI07&sType=sinc|archivedate=27 September 2013}}</ref> \n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Greenhill Gardens]]\n|[[File:Greenhill Gardens lake.JPG|100px|alt=Lake in Greenhill Gardens]]||  1.5 || [[Chipping Barnet|High Barnet]] <br/><small>{{coord| 51.6446|-0.1824  |type:landmark_region:GB|name=   Greenhill Gardens }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 258 955}}</small>|| P || L ||  The principal feature of this small park is its large lake, with a wooded island. Water birds include [[mallard]], [[mute swan]], [[coot]] and [[moorhen]], and [[pipistrelle]] and [[Common noctule|noctule]] bats have been seen foraging.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaL10&sType=sinc|title=Greenhill Gardens|publisher=Greenspace Information for Greater London|year=2013|accessdate=16 August 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927012325/http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaL10&sType=sinc|archivedate=27 September 2013}}</ref>  \n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Hadley Green]] \n|[[File:Hadley Green.JPG|100px|alt=Path in Hadley Green]]|| 10  || [[Monken Hadley]]<br/><small> {{coord| 51.661|-0.199  |type:landmark_region:GB|name=  Hadley Green  }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 246 973}}</small>|| P || M || Hadley Green was the site of one of the major battles of the [[Wars of the Roses]], the [[Battle of Barnet]] in 1471. It is mainly acid grassland with some wetter areas and several ponds. It has a number of rare species of plant, such as [[Nardus stricta|mat-grass]] and [[Carex leporina|oval sedge]] in the grassland, [[Ranunculus flammula|lesser spearwort]] and [[Senecio congestus|marsh ragwort]] in the ditches, and [[Myosotis laxa|tufted forget-me-not]] and [[Rumex pulcher|fiddle dock]] in the ponds. There are also eleven species of dragonflies and damselflies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=M032&sType=sinc|title=Hadley Green|publisher=Greenspace Information for Greater London|year=2013|accessdate=16 August 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927012329/http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=M032&sType=sinc|archivedate=27 September 2013}}</ref> \n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Hampstead Heath#Extension|Hampstead Heath Extension]] and [[Golders Hill Park]]\n|[[File:Golders Hill Park in 2006.jpg|100px|alt=Formal garden in Golders Hill Park]]|| 46{{efn|Hampstead Heath SINC is composed of the main [[Hampstead Heath|Heath]] in the [[London Borough of Camden]] and Hampstead Heath Extension and Golders Hill Park in Barnet. 46 hectares is in Barnet out of the total of 329.}} || [[Golders Green]]<br/><small> {{coord|   51.575|-0.186|type:landmark_region:GB|name=   Hampstead Heath Extension and Golders Hill Park }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 258 878}} </small>|| P || M ||The LEU described the hedges of Hampstead Heath Extension as some of the best on the Heath. It also has a chain of seven ponds which have a wide variety of aquatic and pond margin plant species. Golders Hill Park has areas of formal and less managed parkland. Swan Pond is a large ornamental lake which has a variety of exotic and native wildfowl.<ref>Hewlett, pp. 44\u201345</ref> \n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Hendon Park|Hendon Park and Northern Line Railway Cutting]]\n|[[File:Hendon Park.JPG|100px|alt=Hendon Park]]|| 14  || [[Hendon]]<br/><small> {{coord|51.582|-0.222   |type:landmark_region:GB|name=  Hendon Park and Northern Line Railway Cutting  }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 233 884}}</small>|| P || L || The site is mainly informal parkland, with mown grass and mature trees. A variety of small birds forage among the tall hedgerows at the northern end. The railway cutting has rough grassland and patches of woodland, which provide a habitat for birds such as the [[great spotted woodpecker]] and [[goldcrest]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaL18&sType=sinc|title=Hendon Park and Northern Line Railway Cutting|publisher=Greenspace Information for Greater London|year=2013|accessdate=16 August 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927012403/http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaL18&sType=sinc|archivedate=27 September 2013}}</ref> \n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[King George's Fields (Monken Hadley)|King George's Fields]]\n|[[File:King George's Fields.JPG|100px|alt=King George's Fields]]|| 27 || [[Monken Hadley]]<br/><small> {{coord|  51.656|-0.195 |type:landmark_region:GB|name=  King George's Fields  }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 250 969}}</small>|| P || B2 || This site is mainly covered with coarse grasses, but it also has herb-rich fields dominated by [[Agrostis stolonifera|creeping bent]] and [[Festuca rubra|red fescue]], together with wild flowers commonly found on unimproved grassland. Oak trees grow in old hedges, and breeding birds include sparrowhawk and [[stock dove]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaBII15&sType=sinc|title=King George's Fields|publisher=Greenspace Information for Greater London|year=2013|accessdate=16 August 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927012304/http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaBII15&sType=sinc|archivedate=27 September 2013}}</ref>  \n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Lakeside Nature Reserve]]\n|[[File:Lakeside Nature Reserve.JPG|100px|alt=View of Lakeside Nature Reserve from a footpath off Strathmore Gardens]]||  0.6 || [[Church End, Barnet|Church End]]<br/><small> {{coord|   51.5994|-0.1850|type:landmark_region:GB|name= Lakeside Nature Reserve   }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 257 904}}</small>|| V || L || This site is a lake with a small island behind an office block, surrounded by a belt of trees. The island provides a safe breeding ground for wildfowl, away from mammalian predators. The lake also has fish, frogs, toads and terrapins.<ref>Hewlett, p. 94</ref> \n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Dollis Brook|Lower Dollis Brook]], [[Brent Park (Hendon)|Brent Park]] and [[River Brent]]\n|[[File:Dollis brook windsor open space.JPG|100px|alt=Dollis Brook in Windsor Open Space]]|| 28 || [[Woodside Park]]/[[Hendon]]<br/><small> {{coord| 51.572|-0.236  |type:landmark_region:GB|name= Lower Dollis Brook   }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 243 906}}</small>|| P || B2 || This site covers Dollis Brook between Woodside Park and its end in [[Temple Fortune]], where it becomes the River Brent, the Brent as far as the [[A1 in London|A1]], and Brent Park. At the Woodside Park end there is a wild area with old ivy-clad oaks and alder. Brent Park has a lake which may have been created by the abbots of [[Westminster Abbey|Westminster]] almost a thousand years ago. It has a wooded island which provides a refuge for birds.<ref>Hewlett, pp. 79\u201380</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Scratchwood#Mill Hill Golf Course|Mill Hill Golf Course]]\n|[[File:Mill Hill Golf Course 2.JPG|100px|alt=Mill Hill Golf Course]] ||60 || [[Mill Hill]] <br/><small>{{coord| 51.634| -0.259  |type:landmark_region:GB|name=  Mill Hill Golf Course  }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 206 942}}</small>|| NO || B1 || The golf course has several small streams which meet in Stoneyfields Lake, which was formed by damming Deans Brook. On the edges of the fairways there is a variety of wild flowers, some of them relics of old farm meadows. The most important area ecologically is acid grassland which contains the rare plant [[Genista tinctoria|dyer's greenweed]].<ref>Hewlett, pp. 64\u201365</ref> \n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Mill Hill Old Railway Nature Reserve]] \n|[[File:Mill Hill Old Railway.JPG|100px|alt=Path following the route of the old railway line in Mill Hill Old Railway Nature Reserve]]|| 9  || [[Mill Hill]]<br/><small> {{coord|  51.612|-0.257 |type:landmark_region:GB|name=  Mill Hill Old Railway Nature Reserve  }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 203 917}}</small>|| PL|| B2 || This linear nature reserve on the site of an old railway line is managed by the [[London Wildlife Trust]]. Trees in the woodland canopy include oak and sycamore, and there is a scrub layer of hawthorn, [[blackthorn]] and [[Salix atrocinerea|grey willow]]. The grassland has a range of wild flowers, and the site has a large population of [[Anguis|slow-worms]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaBII04&sType=sinc|title=Mill Hill Old Railway Nature Reserve|publisher=Greenspace Information for Greater London|year=2013|accessdate=16 August 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160129053633/http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaBII04&sType=sinc|archivedate=29 January 2016}}</ref>  \n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Mill Hill Substation Pastures]] \n|[[File:Mill Hill Substation Pastures 2.JPG|100px|alt=Mill Hill Substation Pastures]]||  15 || [[Mill Hill]] <br/><small>{{coord|   51.6168|-0.2106|type:landmark_region:GB|name= Mill Hill Substation Pastures   }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 240 925}}</small>|| V || M || The LEU described this site as a \"remarkable example of unimproved herb-rich pasture on damp clay soil, with substantial populations of attractive and locally uncommon wild flowers\". Burtonhole Brook crosses the site, providing a corridor of damp habitat, and old hedgerows and small areas of woodland provide a refuge for birds.<ref>Hewlett, pp. 47\u201348</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Moat Mount Open Space and Mote End Farm|Moat Mount Open Space]] and [[Barnet Gate Wood]]\n|[[File:Leg of Mutton Pond.JPG|100px|alt=Leg of Mutton Pond in Moat Mount Open Space]]||110  || [[Mill Hill]] <br/><small>{{coord|  51.634|-0.253 |type:landmark_region:GB|name=  Moat Mount Open Space and Barnet Gate Wood  }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 215 943}}</small>|| P || B2 LNR || Moat Mount is a large hilly area, which slopes down to valleys, which have open fields crossed by old hedgerows. Towards the top of the hill woodland opens out to Leg of Mutton Pond, which has clumps of water-lilies and [[Elodea nuttallii|Nuttall's waterweed]]. The site also includes the neighbouring Barnet Gate Wood, which is probably a remnant of an ancient forest.<ref>Hewlett, pp. 70\u201372</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Monken Hadley Common]]\n|[[File:Monken Hadley Common 1.JPG|100px|alt=Monken Hadley Common]]|| 72  || [[Monken Hadley]] <br/><small>{{coord|  51.660|-0.177 |type:landmark_region:GB|name=  Monken Hadley Common  }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 263 972}}</small>|| P || B1 CL || This large common is mostly wooded, with small areas of grassland. [[Daubenton's bat]]s forage over an artificial lake called Jack's Lake. The principal trees are oak, hornbeam and beech, and the ground flora includes several plants which are normally only present in ancient woodland. Breeding birds include sparrowhawk, [[tawny owl]] and cuckoo.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaBI03&sType=sinc|title=Monken Hadley Common|publisher=Greenspace Information for Greater London|year=2013|accessdate=16 August 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927012311/http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaBI03&sType=sinc|archivedate=27 September 2013}}</ref>  \n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Mutton Brook]]\n|[[File:Mutton Brook in Brookside Walk.JPG|100px|alt=Mutton Brook in Brookside Walk]]||13  || [[Hampstead Garden Suburb]]<br/><small> {{coord| 51.587|-0.210  |type:landmark_region:GB|name=  Mutton Brook  }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 251 892}}</small>|| P || L || The brook is a tributary of the [[River Brent]]. Oak, ash and willow trees fringe the bank, providing a habitat for birds, and [[grey wagtail]]s forage at the water's edge. Woodland wild flowers include [[Mercurialis perennis|dog's mercury]] and [[Petasites fragrans|winter heliotrope]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaL09&sType=sinc|title=The Mutton Brook|publisher=Greenspace Information for Greater London|year=2013|accessdate=16 August 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927012315/http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaL09&sType=sinc|archivedate=27 September 2013}}</ref><ref>Hewlett, p. 91</ref>  \n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[New Southgate Cemetery]]\n|[[File:Brunswick Park Cemetery, London N11 - geograph.org.uk - 759207.jpg|100px|alt=New Southgate Cemetery]]||  20 || [[Brunswick Park]] <br/><small>{{coord|   51.624|-0.144|type:landmark_region:GB|name=   New Southgate Cemetery }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 286 933}}</small>|| P || B2 || The cemetery is closely managed in the vicinity of recent burials, but woodland has developed in other areas, where young oak, ash, birch and sycamore are growing between mature oak and yew trees. There is a range of breeding birds such as [[European green woodpecker|green]] and [[great spotted woodpecker]]s, [[coal tit]] and [[nuthatch]], and the cemetery is the most northerly known site for the dusky cockroach, a native species.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaBII21&sType=sinc|title=New Southgate Cemetery|publisher=Greenspace Information for Greater London|year=2013|accessdate=16 August 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927012251/http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaBII21&sType=sinc|archivedate=27 September 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Friary Park#North Middlesex Golf Course Ponds|North Middlesex Golf Course Ponds]] \n|[[File:North Middlesex Golf Club ponds 2.JPG|100px|alt=Pond at North Middlesex Golf Course]]|| |0.8  || [[Whetstone, London|Whetstone]] <br/><small>{{coord| 51.621| -0.168  |type:landmark_region:GB|name=  North Middlesex Golf Course Ponds  }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 269 930}}</small>|| NO || B2 || These ponds have one of few known populations of [[palmate newt]]s in Barnet, and there is also a colony of the more common [[smooth newt]]. The pond edges have some Michaelmas daisies and [[Mentha aquatica|water mint]]. A ditch leads to a small area of woodland, and this is probably an important corridor for amphibia.<ref>Hewlett, pp. 80\u201381</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Northern Line Embankment, High Barnet]]\n|[[File:Northern Line Embankment, High Barnet.JPG|100px|alt=Northern Line railway embankment from a footbridge off Wyatts Farm Open Space]]||| 6.5 || [[Totteridge]]/[[High Barnet]] <br/><small>{{coord|  51.641|-0.185 |type:landmark_region:GB|name= Northern Line Embankment, High Barnet   }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 256 951}}</small>|| V || B2 || The vegetation varies between low bramble scrub and light woodland, and it provides a habitat for small birds such as tits and finches. The main ecological significance of the site lies in one of Barnet's few known colonies of the [[common lizard]], which are protected by the absence of pesticides, and freedom from dogs, cats and people.<ref>Hewlett, p. 80</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Oak Hill Wood]]\n|[[File:Oak Hill Wood.JPG|100px|alt=Oak Hill Wood in East Barnet]]||  10 || [[East Barnet]] <br/><small>{{coord|  51.6409|-0.1521 |type:landmark_region:GB|name= Oak Hill Wood   }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 280 951}}</small>|| P || B1 LNR || This wood is managed by the [[London Wildlife Trust]]. The canopy is oak, hornbeam and ash, with some horse chestnut trees. Ground plants include bluebell and wood speedwell. A small stream flows through the wood, and a meadow has common wild flowers and butterflies. The site also has several bat species.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaBI04&sType=sinc|title=Oak Hill Wood Local Nature Reserve|publisher=Greenspace Information for Greater London|year=2013|accessdate=16 August 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160127133958/http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaBI04&sType=sinc|archivedate=27 January 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Oakleigh Park Rail Cutting]] \n|[[File:Oakleigh Park Rail Cutting looking south.jpg|100px|alt=Oakleigh Park Rail Cutting looking south]]|| 8.0  || [[Oakleigh Park]] <br/><small>{{coord|  51.633|-0.162 |type:landmark_region:GB|name=  Oakleigh Park Rail Cutting  }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 272 944}}</small>|| V || L || This site has a diverse habitat. The eastern bank has an open expanse of bramble scrub with clumps of [[blackthorn]], hawthorn and [[dog-rose]]. The western bank has a mature woodland of oak, ash and sycamore, with [[Salix caprea|goat willow]] in wetter areas. Tall herbs are useful to seed eating birds such [[European goldfinch|goldfinch]], wrens and [[dunnock]]s.<ref>Hewlett, pp. 91\u201392</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Princes Park, Temple Fortune|Princes Park]]\n|[[File:Princes Park tree.JPG|100px|alt=Princes Park in Temple Fortune]]||  1.2 || [[Temple Fortune]] <br/><small>{{coord|  51.5820|-0.2061 |type:landmark_region:GB|name=    Princes Park }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 243 885}}</small>|| P || L || This small park is highly managed, with mown lawns and flowerbeds, but some of the old trees pre-date the surrounding houses. In the south-east corner a small woodland appears to be a fragment of an old farm wood. Mature hawthorns around the perimeter may be relics of old farm hedgerows.<ref>Hewlett, p. 93</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Pymmes Brook|Pymme's Brook]]\n|[[File:Pymme's Brook in Oak Hill Park 2.JPG|100px|alt=Pymme's Brook in Oak Hill Park]]||13  || [[Monken Hadley]]/[[New Southgate]]<br/><small> {{coord| 51.6320| -0.1462  |type:landmark_region:GB|name=  Pymme's Brook  }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 284 942}} </small>|| P || B2 || Two separate sections of Pymme's Brook are included in this site. The northern section, which runs 500 metres from Monken Hadley, goes through rough grassland and scattered scrub, with a narrow strip of oak woodland. The three kilometre southern stretch to the boundary with [[London Borough of Enfield|Enfield]] is largely wooded. One part is ancient, with an understorey which includes [[Sorbus torminalis|wild service-trees]], [[midland hawthorn]], [[field maple]] and crab apple.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaBII20&sType=sinc|title=Pymme's Brook|publisher=Greenspace Information for Greater London|year=2013|accessdate=16 August 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927012256/http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaBII20&sType=sinc|archivedate=27 September 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Rowley Green Common]]\n|[[File:Rowley Green Common.JPG|alt=Rowley Green Common, Arkley|100px]]|| 4.9  || [[Arkley]] <br/><small>{{coord| 51.6502|-0.2433  |type:landmark_region:GB|name=  Rowley Green Common  }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 217 960}}</small>|| P || M LNR CL || This site has a mosaic of habitats with different conditions and many rare species. Most of it is woodland with fairly young trees, and the most important area ecologically is a [[bog|sphagnum bog]], described by the LEU as an extremely rare habitat in south-east England. The site also has an area of acid grassland and a pond which supports diverse wetland plants.<ref>Hewlett, pp. 32\u201333</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Rowley Lodge Field]] \n|[[File:Rowley Lodge Field 1.JPG|100px|alt=Rowley Lodge Field, Arkley]]||  4.4 || [[Arkley]]<br/><small> {{coord|   51.6456|-0.2410|type:landmark_region:GB|name=   Rowley Lodge Field }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 218 955}}</small>|| F || B2|| This is an old hay meadow with a few oak trees and small patches of scrub. It has diverse wild flowers, including [[Sanguisorba officinalis|great burnet]] and pignut. Areas of acid grassland are dominated by [[Festuca rubra|red fescue]], together with [[Rumex acetosella|sheep's sorrel]] and [[Potentilla erecta|tormentil]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaBII23&sType=sinc|title=Rowley Lodge field|publisher=Greenspace Information for Greater London|year=2013|accessdate=16 August 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927012244/http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaBII23&sType=sinc|archivedate=27 September 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Scratchwood]]\n|[[File:Scratchwood.JPG|100px|alt=Path in Scratchwood, Mill Hill]]||57 || [[Mill Hill]] <br/><small>{{coord|  51.640|-0.264 |type:landmark_region:GB|name=   Scratchwood }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 201 948}}</small>|| P || M LNR || Part of Scratchwood is ancient woodland, possibly dating back to the end of the last ice age, which has small streams, tall [[Quercus petraea|sessile oaks]] and old hornbeams. Other areas include Bluebell Wood, which is more open and has extensive carpets of wild flowers, and Scratchwood Pond which has marshy areas nearby described by the LEU as botanically very rich.<ref>Hewlett, pp. 48\u201351</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Silk Stream]] and [[Burnt Oak Brook]] \n|[[File:Silk Stream in Silkstream Park.jpg|100px|alt=Silk Stream in Silkstream Park]]|| 8 || [[Edgware]]<br/><small> {{coord|  51.599| -0.259 |type:landmark_region:GB|name=  Silk Stream and Burnt Oak Brook  }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 207 903}}</small>|| PP || B2 || These streams were described by the LEU as valuable wildlife corridors through suburban housing. [[Mallard]]s and [[grey wagtail]]s are often seen along the banks, and fish include [[three-spined stickleback]]. The streams are best seen when they go through parks, such as Silkstream Park, Montrose Recreation Ground and Rushgrove Park.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaBII05&sType=sinc|title=Silk Stream and Burnt Oak Brook|publisher=Greenspace Information for Greater London|year=2013|accessdate=16 August 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927012313/http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaBII05&sType=sinc|archivedate=27 September 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[St Pancras and Islington Cemetery]]\n|[[File:Islington St Pancras Cemetery.JPG|100px|alt=Gravestones in St Pancras and Islington Cemetery]]|| 74  || [[East Finchley]]<br/><small> {{coord|  51.600|-0.165 |type:landmark_region:GB|name= St Pancras and Islington Cemetery    }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 272 907}}</small>|| P || B2 || Parts of this cemetery which are no longer used for burials are managed for nature conservation. These areas have woodland and open grassland, while Strawberry Vale Brook which flows through the north-east corner. The LEU considered the understorey of the wood as surprisingly rich, including pignut, [[Ranunculus auricomus|goldilocks buttercup]], [[Cardamine pratensis|cuckooflower]], primrose, [[Fragaria vesca|wild]] and [[Potentilla sterilis|barren strawberries]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaBII19&sType=sinc|title=St Pancras and Islington Cemetery|publisher=Greenspace Information for Greater London|year=2013|accessdate=16 August 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927012308/http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaBII19&sType=sinc|archivedate=27 September 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Sulloniacis#Sulloniacis Pastures|Sulloniacis Pastures]]\n|[[File:Sulloniacis plaque 2.jpg|100px|alt=Plaque for Sullionacis Roman site]] ||  4.2|| [[Edgware]]<br/><small> {{coord|51.632| -0.302   |type:landmark_region:GB|name=  Sulloniacis Pastures  }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 176 940}}</small>|| V || B2 || Most of this site is herb-rich grassland on London Clay, and it has many flowers typical of clay pasture such as [[Lotus pedunculatus|greater bird's-foot-trefoil]], [[Pimpinella saxifraga|burnet saxifrage]], [[Agrimonia eupatoria|agrimony]] and [[Succisa pratensis|devil's-bit scabious]]. There are also small plots of woodland and scrub.<ref name=\"Hewlett, p. 67\"/> \n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Sunny Hill Park]] and [[St Mary's Churchyard, Hendon|Hendon Churchyard]]\n|[[File:SNV30109.jpg|100px|alt=Sunny Hill Park]]||  22 || [[Hendon]] <br/><small>{{coord|   51.597|-0.230|type:landmark_region:GB|name=   Sunny Hill Park and Hendon Churchyard }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 227 901}}</small>|| P || L || Most of this site is formal parkland, but at the southern end there is a wild flower meadow with [[Centaurea nigra|black knapweed]], [[Sorrel|common sorrel]], [[Stellaria graminea|lesser stitchwort]] and three species of buttercup. An area at the northern end is managed to preserve [[Anguis|slow-worms]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaL03&sType=sinc|title=Sunny Hill Park and Hendon Churchyard|publisher=Greenspace Information for Greater London|year=2013|accessdate=16 August 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927012253/http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaL03&sType=sinc|archivedate=27 September 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[The Mill Field]]\n|[[File:The Mill Field.JPG|100px|alt=Path in The Mill Field, Mill Hill]]|| 3.4|| [[Mill Hill]]<br/><small> {{coord|   51.622|-0.236|type:landmark_region:GB|name=   The Mill Field }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 221 929}}</small>|| P || B2 || The grassland in the more natural part of this site has scattered oak and willow scrub, and mature trees and hedgerows on the periphery. There is a variety of wild flowers, and the [[Lycaena phlaeas|small copper butterfly]] has been recorded. A small pond has rich aquatic flora including [[Bidens cernua|nodding bur-marigold]] and [[Sparganium|branched bur-reed]].<ref>Hewlett, pp. 72\u201373</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Totteridge Common]]\n|[[File:Totteridge Common pond.JPG|100px|alt=Pink Cottage Pond on Totteridge Common]]||  3 || [[Totteridge]] <br/><small>{{coord| 51.6315|-0.2227  |type:landmark_region:GB|name=  Totteridge Common  }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 230 939}}</small>|| P || B2 CL || The trees on this site are mostly sycamore and elm, but it also has two [[Populus nigra|black poplars]], which are considered England's most threatened native tree.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.naturalengland.org.uk/ourwork/conservation/biodiversity/iyb/blackpoplar.aspx|publisher=Natural England|title=Black Poplar|date=25 January 2010|accessdate=23 March 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927112751/http://www.naturalengland.org.uk/ourwork/conservation/biodiversity/iyb/blackpoplar.aspx|archivedate=27 September 2013}}</ref> The most important feature ecologically is a chain of old ponds, which are valuable for dragonflies, other insects and amphibians. Plants in deep water include [[Nymphaea alba|white water-lily]] and [[Potamogeton crispus|curled]] and [[Potamogeton natans|broad-leaved pondweeds]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaBII09&sType=sinc|title=Totteridge Common|publisher=Greenspace Information for Greater London|year=2013|accessdate=16 August 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927012306/http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaBII09&sType=sinc|archivedate=27 September 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Totteridge Green#Totteridge Croft Field (or Dell's Down Acre)|Totteridge Croft Field (or Dell's Down Acre)]]\n| [[File:Totteridge Dell Croft.JPG|100px|alt=View north-west from a footpath towards Totteridge Dell Croft nature reserve]]|| 2.4  || [[Totteridge]]<br/><small> {{coord|  51.626| -0.198 |type:landmark_region:GB|name= Totteridge Croft Field   }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 248 934}}</small>|| NO || B1 || This site was described by the LEU as an interesting example of unimproved clay grassland. Much of it is covered with [[Deschampsia cespitosa|tufted hair-grass]], but there is considerable variety between the different fields. There is a variety of wild flowers, including uncommon species such as [[Achillea ptarmica|sneezewort]] and pignut.<ref>Hewlett, pp. 62\u201364</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Totteridge Fields|Totteridge Fields and Highwood Hill]]\n|[[File:Totteridge Fields.JPG|100px|alt=Totteridge Fields Local Nature Reserve, Arkley]]|| 103 || [[Arkley]]<br/><small>  {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 231 945}}<br>{{coord|   51.632|-0.234|type:landmark_region:GB|name= Totteridge Fields    }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 222 935}} </small>|| PP || M LNR || This site has large areas of uncultivated grassland with old hedgerows. Part of it is a local nature reserve managed by the [[London Wildlife Trust]]. There is a wide range of wild flowers, including some that are locally uncommon, and breeding birds include the [[Eurasian skylark|skylark]], which is a declining species. A number of beetles and spiders found here are nationally rare.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=M034&sType=sinc|title=Totteridge Fields and Highwood Hill|publisher=Greenspace Information for Greater London|year=2013|accessdate=16 August 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924040716/http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=M034&sType=sinc|archivedate=24 September 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Totteridge Green]] \n|[[File:Totteridge Green, Laurel Farm Pond.JPG|100px|alt=Laurel Farm Pond in Totteridge Green]]||  4.6 || [[Totteridge]]<br/><small> {{coord| 51.6281|-0.1953  |type:landmark_region:GB|name=   Totteridge Green }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 250 936}}</small>|| P || B2 CL || This is a typical English village green with open grassland, scattered trees, small areas of scrubby woodland and a pond. The main grasses are [[Lolium perenne|perennial rye-grass]] and other coarse meadow species. There are several damp hollows, probably former ponds, which have uncommon wild flowers such as [[Sanguisorba officinalis|great burnet]] and [[Minuartia stricta|bog stitchwort]]. Woodland plants include [[Polystichum setiferum|soft shield-fern]], which is rare locally.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaBII14&sType=sinc|title=Totteridge Green|publisher=Greenspace Information for Greater London|year=2013|accessdate=16 August 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927012317/http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaBII14&sType=sinc|archivedate=27 September 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Turner's Wood]]\n|[[File:Turner's Wood path.JPG|100px|alt=Entrance to Turner's Wood, Hampstead Garden Suburb]]||  2.4 || [[Hampstead Garden Suburb]]<br/><small> {{coord|  51.5722|-0.1785 |type:landmark_region:GB|name=  Turner's Wood  }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 263 875}}</small>|| NO || B2 || This private nature reserve is a fragment of Bishops Wood, part of the [[Bishop of London]]'s medieval estate. The landscape is undulating, with two small streams going through the centre. The main tree in the canopy is [[sessile oak]], with a rich understorey including [[rowan]], [[midland hawthorn]] and some [[Sorbus torminalis|wild service-trees]]. The site is managed for nature conservation, especially for birds.<ref>Hewlett, p. 84</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Dollis Brook|Upper Dollis Brook]]\n|[[File:Dollis Brook in Brook Farm open space.JPG|100px|alt=Dollis Brook in Brook Farm Open Space]]||  40|| [[Mill Hill]]/[[Woodside Park]]<br/><small> {{coord|   51.5717|-0.2361|type:landmark_region:GB|name=  Upper Dollis Brook  }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 253 943}}</small>|| P || B1 || This six kilometre long stretch runs from Arkley to Woodside Park, and the site also includes neighbouring areas such as Whetstone Stray and Wyatt's Open Space, which have flower-rich meadows divided by old hedges. The hedges have uncommon shrubs such as [[Euonymus|spindle]] and [[buckthorn]]. Birds seen along the stream include [[kingfisher]]s, [[grey wagtail]]s and [[moorhen]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaBI08&sType=sinc|title=Upper Dollis Brook|publisher=Greenspace Information for Greater London|year=2013|accessdate=16 August 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927012258/http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaBI08&sType=sinc|archivedate=27 September 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Woodridge Nature Reserve|Woodridge School Nature Reserve]] \n|[[File:Woodridge Nature Reserve.JPG|100px|alt=Woodridge Nature Reserve in Woodside Park]]|| 2.5 || [[Woodside Park]]<br/><small> {{coord| 51.6227|-0.1955  |type:landmark_region:GB|name=  Woodridge School Nature Reserve  }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 250 930}}</small>|| P || L || This small site was established as a nature garden for local primary schools. It has young oak woodland and rough grassland, which has wild flowers such as pignut and [[Lamium galeobdolon|yellow archangel]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaL20&sType=sinc|title=Woodridge School Nature Reserve|publisher=Greenspace Information for Greater London|year=2013|accessdate=16 August 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927012247/http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaL20&sType=sinc|archivedate=27 September 2013}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==See also==\n{{commons category|Nature reserves in the London Borough of Barnet|Nature reserves in Barnet}}\n*[[Barnet parks and open spaces]]\n*[[List of Sites of Special Scientific Interest in Greater London]]\n*[[List of local nature reserves in Greater London]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|20em}}\n\n==Sources==\n*{{cite book|title=Nature Conservation in Barnet|first1=Jan|last1 =Hewlett|first2=Ian|last2=Yarham|first3=David|last3=Curson|publisher=London Ecology Unit|year=1997|isbn=1 871045 27 4}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/|title=iGiGL the data portal of Greenspace Information for London|publisher=Greenspace Information for Greater London|year=2013|access-date=2013-08-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140114132930/http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/|archive-date=2014-01-14|url-status=dead}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.barnet.gov.uk/info/930058/unitary_development_plan/701/unitary_development_plan|title=Barnet Unitary Development Plan, adopted 2006 (updated 2009)|publisher=London Borough of Barnet|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130118023803/http://www.barnet.gov.uk/info/930058/unitary_development_plan/701/unitary_development_plan|archivedate=2013-01-18}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.london.gov.uk/olc/docs/brent-cross-report.pdf|format=pdf|date=11 February 2009|title=Planning report PDU/1483/01, Brent Cross Cricklewood in the London Borough of Barnet, planning application no. C/17559/08|accessdate=23 July 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120827065230/http://www.london.gov.uk/olc/docs/brent-cross-report.pdf|archivedate=27 August 2012}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.finchleysociety.org.uk/actenvspaceslist.htm |publisher=Finchley Society |title=Finchley and Friern Barnet Green Spaces List |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120109065448/http://www.finchleysociety.org.uk/actenvspaceslist.htm |archivedate=2012-01-09 }}\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.londongardensonline.org.uk/select-borough-results.asp?Borough=Barnet&Submit=Go|title=London Gardens Online: Barnet|publisher=London Parks & Gardens Trust|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120118203741/http://www.londongardensonline.org.uk/select-borough-results.asp?Borough=Barnet&Submit=Go|archivedate=2012-01-18}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.barnet.gov.uk/directory/15/parks |title=Parks and open spaces in the Barnet area |publisher=London Borough of Barnet |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121029072254/http://www.barnet.gov.uk/directory/15/parks |archivedate=2012-10-29 }}\n{{Nature reserves in Barnet}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nature reserves in the London Borough of Barnet}}\n[[Category:Conservation in London]]\n[[Category:Nature reserves in the London Borough of Barnet| ]]\n[[Category:Geography of the London Borough of Barnet]]\n[[Category:Parks and open spaces in the London Borough of Barnet| ]]\n[[Category:London nature-related lists]]\n", "text_old": "{{featured list}}\n[[File:Beech Hill Lake.jpg|thumb|Beech Hill Lake in [[Monken Hadley Common]]|350px|alt=Beech Hill Lake in Monken Hadley Common ]]\nThe [[London Borough of Barnet]], on the northern outskirts of London, is mainly residential, but it has large areas of green space and farmland. The spread of suburban development into the countryside was halted by the designation of a statutory [[Metropolitan Green Belt|Green Belt]] around London after the Second World War, and almost one third of Barnet's area of {{convert|8663|ha|acre}} is Green Belt. Without this control, Barnet would be very different today, and this list of nature reserves would be much shorter.<ref>Hewlett, pp. 2, 11\u201313</ref>\n\nMost of Barnet lies over [[London Clay]], which is poor for agriculture, and open land is mainly used for activities such as horse grazing, playing fields, parks and golf courses. Features of the traditional agricultural landscape have survived, such as old hedgerows, ancient trees and areas of herb-rich grassland. Some hay meadows have a large diversity of wild flowers, and the [[London Ecology Unit]] (LEU){{efn|The London Ecology Unit was established to provide advice to London boroughs following the abolition of the [[Greater London Council]] in 1986. In 2000 it was abolished and absorbed into the [[Greater London Authority]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wildlondon.org.uk/activism-for-change|publisher=London Wildlife Trust|title=Activism for Change|accessdate=16 July 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121025102530/http://www.wildlondon.org.uk/activism-for-change|archivedate=25 October 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://legacy.london.gov.uk/mayor/strategies/biodiversity/docs/Building_Green_main_text.pdf|publisher=Mayor of London|title=Building Green: A guide to using plants on roofs, walls and pavements|isbn=1 85261 637 7|year=2004|accessdate=16 July 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120816005511/http://legacy.london.gov.uk/mayor/strategies/biodiversity/docs/Building_Green_main_text.pdf|archivedate=16 August 2012}}</ref>}} described them as one of Barnet's most important ecological assets.<ref>Hewlett, pp. 2\u20133, 6</ref>\n\nBarnet has large areas with designations intended to protect them from \"inappropriate development\", and to \"provide the strongest protection for the preservation of Barnet's green and natural open spaces\". As well as {{convert|2466|ha|acre}} of Green Belt, Barnet has another {{convert|690|ha|acre}} of [[Metropolitan Open Land]], which receive a similar level of protection. [[Watling Chase Community Forest]]{{efn|[[Community forests in England|Community Forests']] objects include revitalising derelict land, providing new leisure facilities, preparing for climate change and increasing biodiversity.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.communityforest.org.uk/aboutenglandsforests.htm|title=About England\u2019s Community Forests|publisher=England\u2019s Community Forests|accessdate=14 November 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151117030515/http://www.communityforest.org.uk/aboutenglandsforests.htm|archivedate=17 November 2015}}</ref>}} covers {{convert|72|sqmi|sqkm}}, extending north and west from Totteridge into south Hertfordshire.<ref>Barnet Unitary Development Plan, Chapter 5, pp. 65\u201367, 83\u201384</ref>\n\nIn 1992 Barnet Council commissioned the LEU to carry out a survey of wildlife habitats in the borough, which looked at green sites covering {{convert|4055|ha|acre}}, 45% of the borough. In 1997 the LEU published ''Nature Conservation in Barnet'', which described 67 [[Site of Nature Conservation Interest|Sites of Importance for Nature Conservation]] (SINCs).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.london.gov.uk/priorities/environment/greening-london/biodiversity/sites-importance-nature-conservation|title=Sites of Importance for Nature Conservation|publisher=[[Mayor of London]]|accessdate=24 February 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130119130405/http://london.gov.uk/priorities/environment/greening-london/biodiversity/sites-importance-nature-conservation|archivedate=19 January 2013}}</ref><ref>Hewlett, pp. 14\u201315</ref> This formed the basis of Barnet's nature conservation policies in its 2006 ''Unitary Development Plan'', designated as \"a material planning consideration\" to be used as \"non-statutory guidance\".<ref>Barnet Unitary Development Plan, Chapter 5, p. 79</ref> The table below lists SINCs described in ''Nature Conservation in Barnet''.<ref name=NCB>Hewlett et al, ''Nature Conservation in Barnet''</ref>{{efn|''Nature Conservation in Barnet'' lists 67 sites, but only 66 are shown in this table because Grahame Park SINC no longer exists. It has been re-modelled and renamed Heybourne Park.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://barnet.moderngov.co.uk/documents/s260/Regeneration%20New%20Dwellings%20Report%20FINAL.pdf|format=pdf|title=Budget and Performance Overview and Scrutiny Committee: Number of New Dwellings Started on Regeneration Schemes \u2013 Performance Update|date=15 March 2012|publisher=London Borough of Barnet|accessdate=15 February 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305003457/http://barnet.moderngov.co.uk/documents/s260/Regeneration%20New%20Dwellings%20Report%20FINAL.pdf|archivedate=5 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaL02&sType=sinc|title=Grahame Park|publisher=Greenspace Information for Greater London|year=2013|accessdate=16 August 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141218191918/http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaL02&sType=sinc|archivedate=18 December 2014}}</ref> The sites were listed on the [[Mayor of London]]'s Wildweb website, which was taken down in December 2010. In spring 2012 it was replaced by a new site hosted by [[Greenspace Information for Greater London]] (GiGL), London's environmental record centre.<ref>{{cite web|first=Boris|last=Johnson|url=http://london.gov.uk/mqt/public/question.do?id=39724|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130917102952/http://london.gov.uk/mqt/public/question.do?id=39724|url-status=dead|archive-date=17 September 2013|title=London Wildweb site|publisher=The London Assembly|date=25 January 2012|accessdate=17 September 2013}}</ref> This new website covers most SINCs, but others are left out, some which are not publicly accessible and others in error. Wildweb included maps of every site, but ''Nature Conservation in Barnet'' only has maps of the most important ones, the 'Sites of Metropolitan Importance'. GiGL has maps for the sites it lists,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/|title=iGiGL the data portal of Greenspace Information for London|publisher=Greenspace Information for Greater London|year=2013|accessdate=14 August 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140114132930/http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/|archivedate=14 January 2014}}</ref> but the only map for the other sites is the map of the whole borough inside the back cover of ''Nature Conservation in Barnet''. The list of SINCs in ''Nature Conservation in Barnet'' has not been updated and is still the basis for GiGL's database.}} SINCs do not have statutory protection, but some sites are also wholly or partly designated as [[Site of Special Scientific Interest|Sites of Special Scientific Interest]]{{efn|There are 36 [[List of Sites of Special Scientific Interest in Greater London|Sites of Special Scientific Interest in Greater London]]. The only one in Barnet is Brent Reservoir.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sssi.naturalengland.org.uk/special/sssi/searchresults.cfm?sssi_name=&frmcounty=1017|publisher=Natural England|title=Sites of Special Scientific Interest, Search results for Greater London|accessdate=24 February 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121024044922/http://www.sssi.naturalengland.org.uk/special/sssi/searchresults.cfm?sssi_name=&frmcounty=1017|archivedate=24 October 2012}}</ref> Darland's Lake was formerly an SSSI but the designation was withdrawn when it was found that the rare [[fritillaries]] on the site had probably been planted.<ref>Hewlett, p. 53</ref>}} or [[local nature reserve]]s,{{efn|[[Natural England]] lists 141 [[local nature reserve]]s in Greater London. Seven of these are in Barnet, but two of these are divided into separate SINCs. Scratchwood and Moat Mount is one LNR but two SINCs, and the same applies to Coppett's Wood and Glebelands. Nine SINCs are thus also LNRs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lnr.naturalengland.org.uk/special/lnr/lnr_results.asp?N=&C=17&Submit=Search |publisher=Natural England |title=Local Nature Reserves, Search Results for Greater London |accessdate=24 February 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927113247/http://www.lnr.naturalengland.org.uk/special/lnr/lnr_results.asp?N=&C=17&Submit=Search |archivedate=27 September 2013 }}</ref>}} which do have statutory protection.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.naturalengland.org.uk/ourwork/conservation/designations/lnr/default.aspx|publisher=Natural England|title=Local Nature Reserves|accessdate=22 September 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130923032955/http://www.naturalengland.org.uk/ourwork/conservation/designations/lnr/default.aspx|archivedate=23 September 2013}}</ref> According to a report of the [[Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs]], 39% of Barnet's SINCs were \"in positive conservation management\" in 2009\u201310. Barnet Council did not supply figures for 2010\u201311, 2011\u201312 or 2012-13.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/env10-local-sites-in-positive-conservation-management|title=Nature Conservation: Local Sites in Positive Conservation Management in England, 2008/9 to 2012/13|accessdate=2 February 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140219080420/https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/env10-local-sites-in-positive-conservation-management|archivedate=19 February 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Nature reserves==\n\n===Key===\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n;Access\n* '''P '''  = free public access to all or most of the site\n* '''PP''' = free public access to part of the site\n* '''PL''' = public at limited times\n* '''F '''  = access on public footpaths only\n* '''V '''  = can be viewed from adjacent paths or roads only\n* '''NO''' = no public access\n{{col-2}}\n;Type\n* '''M '''    = Site of Metropolitan Importance \u2013 the best examples of London's habitats, or which contain rare species<ref name=Hewlett27>Hewlett, p. 27</ref>\n* '''B1 '''   = Site of Borough Importance Grade 1 \u2013 of significant value to the borough<ref name=Hewlett27/>\n* '''B2 '''   = Site of Borough Importance, Grade 2 \u2013 as B1, but not as important<ref name=Hewlett27/>\n* '''L '''    = Site of local importance \u2013 of particular value to nearby residents or schools<ref name=Hewlett27/>\n* '''LNR '''  = [[Local nature reserve]] \u2013 of special interest locally for wildlife or geological features<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lnr.naturalengland.org.uk/special/lnr/office.htm|title=Local Nature Reserves|publisher=Natural England|accessdate=7 March 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130525090416/http://www.lnr.naturalengland.org.uk/special/lnr/office.htm|archivedate=25 May 2013}}</ref>\n* '''SSSI''' = [[Site of Special Scientific Interest]] \u2013 the country's best wildlife and geological sites<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.naturalengland.org.uk/ourwork/conservation/designations/sssi/default.aspx|publisher=Natural England|title=Sites of Special Scientific Interest|accessdate=7 March 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130314103950/http://www.naturalengland.org.uk/ourwork/conservation/designations/sssi/default.aspx|archivedate=14 March 2013}}</ref>\n* '''CL'''  = [[Common land|registered common land]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archive.defra.gov.uk/rural/documents/protected/common-land/biosurvey-glondon.pdf |title=The Common Lands of Greater London: A Biological Survey |publisher=[[Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs]] |accessdate=24 February 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20130402151656/http://archive.defra.gov.uk/rural/documents/protected/common-land/biosurvey-glondon.pdf |archivedate=2 April 2013 }}</ref> \u2013 free public access to all of site<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.naturalengland.org.uk/ourwork/access/openaccess/default.aspx|publisher=Natural England|title=Open Access land|accessdate=25 February 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130201131041/http://www.naturalengland.org.uk/ourwork/access/openaccess/default.aspx|archivedate=1 February 2013}}</ref>\n{{col-end}}\n{{kml}}\n\n===Sites===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"width:98%\"\n!scope=\"col\" | Site\n!scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\"| Photograph\n!scope=\"col\" | Hectares{{efn|The figures for area are taken from ''Nature Conservation in Barnet''.}}\n!scope=\"col\" | Location{{efn|The grid references are taken from ''Nature Conservation in Barnet''. Click on the grid reference and then select a map to see the location of the reserve.}}\n!scope=\"col\" | Access\n!scope=\"col\" | Type\n!scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\"| Description\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Arkley Lane and Pastures]]\n|[[File:Arkley Lane.JPG|100px|alt=Arkley Lane in autumn]]|| 52 || [[Arkley]] <br/><small>{{coord|51.655|-0.230   |type:landmark_region:GB|name= Arkley Lane and Pastures   }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 225 965}}</small>|| PP || B2 || The site covers Arkley Lane, a neighbouring woodland and fields on either side. The lane, now a quiet country path, is thought to be an old drovers' road. The hedges have massive gnarled oak trees, lofty ash and mature field maples, while the hedge bottoms have a diverse range of plants. The woodland is probably ancient, and supports a variety of nesting birds.<ref>Hewlett, p. 83</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Arkley South Fields]]\n|[[File:Arkley South Field.JPG|100px|alt=Birds in Arkley South Field]]|| 38 || [[Arkley]] <br/><small>{{coord|  51.641|-0.232 |type:landmark_region:GB|name=  Arkley South Fields  }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 224 951}}</small> || V  || B2 ||This is an extensive area of open grassland crossed by ditches and with mature hedgerows. Its importance lies in its breeding grassland birds, including [[Eurasian skylark|skylarks]] and [[meadow pipit]]s, and it is the main site in the borough for these species. Skylarks have declined in recent years, and they are a priority species in the UK Biodiversity Action Plan.<ref>Hewlett, pp. 84\u201385</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://jncc.defra.gov.uk/page-5163|publisher=Joint Nature Conservation Committee, Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs|title=UK Biodiversity Action Plan priority bird species|accessdate=7 March 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130513164420/http://jncc.defra.gov.uk/page-5163|archivedate=13 May 2013}}\n</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Arrandene Open Space and Featherstone Hill]] \n|[[File:Arrandene Open Space.JPG|alt=Arrandene Open Space|100px]]|| 25 || [[Mill Hill]] <br/><small>{{coord| 51.613|-0.230  |type:landmark_region:GB|name=   Arrandene Open Space and Featherstone Hill }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 226 920}}</small>|| P || M ||This site's fields, which are divided by ancient hedgerows, were rated by the LEU as one of the best examples of old hay meadows in London. Wild flowers are abundant in the summer, with each field having its own specialities. The woods and scrub are important habitats for birds.<ref>Hewlett, pp. 41\u201343</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=M038&sType=sinc|title=Arrandene Open Space and Featherstone Hill|publisher=Greenspace Information for Greater London|year=2013|accessdate=16 August 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927012410/http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=M038&sType=sinc|archivedate=27 September 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Ashley Lane (Hendon)|Ashley Lane]]\n|[[File:Ashley Lane.JPG|100px|alt=Ashley Lane in autumn]]|| 1 || [[Hendon]]<br/><small> {{coord| 51.601|-0.217  |type:landmark_region:GB|name=  Ashley Lane  }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 236 906}}</small>|| P || B2 ||This ancient trackway is over 400 years old. It has retained its ancient hedgerows along much of its length. Old oak and ash trees line the lane, and there are also some [[Sorbus torminalis|wild service-trees]]. The hedgerows have diverse shrub species.<ref>Hewlett, p. 76</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Avenue House Grounds]] \n|[[File:Avenue House Grounds pond.JPG|100px|alt=Ornamental pond in Avenue House Grounds]]||  3.5 || [[Church End, Barnet|Church End]]<br/><small> {{coord|  51.5975|-0.1937 |type:landmark_region:GB|name=    Avenue House Grounds }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 251 902}}</small>|| P || L || This small public park is the garden of [[Avenue House]]. It has a terrace with ornamental plants and a rockery. There is a pond which has [[Ceratophyllum|hornwort]], [[yellow iris]] and water-lilies, together with [[common frog]]s and [[koi carp]]. There are large areas of shrubbery.<ref name=\"Hewlett, p. 89\">Hewlett, p. 89</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Barfield Allotments Nature Park]]\n|[[File:Barfield Allotments Nature Park.JPG|100px|alt=Barfield Allotments Nature Park]]||  0.9 || [[Whetstone, London|Whetstone]]<br/><small> {{coord| 51.627|-0.158  |type:landmark_region:GB|name= Barfield Allotments Nature Park   }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 276 935}}</small>|| V || L || This small wildlife site is adjacent to a playground. Its scrub and grassland provide a haven for [[common lizard]]s and [[slowworm]]s, both legally protected species.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaL21&sType=sinc|title=Barfield Allotments Nature Park|publisher=Greenspace Information for Greater London|year=2013|accessdate=16 August 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927012346/http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaL21&sType=sinc|archivedate=27 September 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Barnet Countryside Centre]]\n|[[File:Barnet Countryside Centre from Byng Road.JPG|100px|alt=View of Barnet Countryside Centre from Byng Road]]|| 2.8  || [[Chipping Barnet|High Barnet]]<br/><small> {{coord| 51.658|-0.216  |type:landmark_region:GB|name=   Countryside Centre }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 234 969}}</small>|| V || L || The centre was established in the 1970s to provide schoolchildren with contact with farm animals and wildlife. After a period of closure the now renamed Barnet Environment Centre operates a full programme of environmental education visits for school children from Nursery to A level. Its woodland has a wide range of birds. Ponds support aquatic life and more open areas have a wide variety of insects.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaL04&sType=sinc|title=Barnet Countryside Centre|publisher=Greenspace Information for Greater London|year=2013|accessdate=16 August 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927012405/http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaL04&sType=sinc|archivedate=27 September 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fobcc.org.uk/drupal/|title=Home page|publisher=Friends of the Barnet Countryside Centre|accessdate=22 March 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080924032209/http://www.fobcc.org.uk/drupal/|archivedate=24 September 2008}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Bell's Hill Burial Ground]] \n|[[File:Bells Hill Burial Ground 2.JPG|100px|alt=Bells Hill Burial Ground]]|| 2.8 || [[Chipping Barnet|High Barnet]]<br/><small> {{coord| 51.649|-0.215  |type:landmark_region:GB|name=  Bell's Hill Burial Ground  }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 235 959}}</small>|| P || L ||This small cemetery has mown grass in the western part, but in the east it is less managed, and has a wide variety of wild flowers. The LEU described it as a fine site for butterflies, including [[Gatekeeper (butterfly)|gatekeeper]], [[small skipper]] and [[meadow brown]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaL05&sType=sinc|title=Bell's Hill Burial Ground|publisher=Greenspace Information for Greater London|year=2013|accessdate=16 August 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927012401/http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaL05&sType=sinc|archivedate=27 September 2013}}</ref><ref>Hewlett, p. 88</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Belmont Open Space, Cockfosters]] \n|[[File:Belmont Open Space Cockfosters.JPG|100px|alt=Belmont Open Space]]||  1.0 || [[Cockfosters]]<br/><small> {{coord| 51.647|-0.157  |type:landmark_region:GB|name= Belmont Open Space   }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 275 958}}</small>|| P || L || This site is a secluded small park, which has a fair number of wild flowers and mature trees, together with an old hedgerow. The local [[Royal Society for the Protection of Birds]] has recorded a wide range of birds for a small suburban park.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaL22&sType=sinc|title=Belmont Open Space, Cockfosters|publisher=Greenspace Information for Greater London|year=2013|accessdate=16 August 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927012322/http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaL22&sType=sinc|archivedate=27 September 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Big Wood and Little Wood]]\n|[[File:Big Wood, N2.JPG|100px|alt=A path in Big Wood in spring]]|| 8.6  || [[Hampstead Garden Suburb]] <br/><small>{{coord|  51.583| -0.190 |type:landmark_region:GB|name=  Big Wood  }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 255 887}}<BR/>{{coord|  51.586| -0.193 |type:landmark_region:GB|name=  Little Wood  }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 253 890}}</small>|| P || B1 LNR || These woods are remnants of an ancient large forest. Big Wood has a wide variety of trees and shrubs, with [[pedunculate oak]] the dominant species. There are several old [[Sorbus torminalis|wild service-trees]]. All the common woodland species of birds are present in the woods, and Little Wood has a small theatre.<ref>Hewlett, pp. 57\u201358</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Brent Reservoir|Brent Reservoir (Welsh Harp)]]\n|[[File:Brent Res view.JPG|100px|alt=Brent Reservoir]]|| 46{{efn|Brent Reservoir is partly in the [[London Borough of Brent]], and 46 hectares out of the total of 96 is in Barnet.}} || [[Hendon]]<br/><small> {{coord| 51.571 |-0.245  |type:landmark_region:GB|name=   Brent Reservoir }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 215 871}}</small>|| P || M LNR SSSI || Brent Reservoir is Barnet's only [[Site of Special Scientific Interest]]. It is an important breeding site for waterfowl and other birds, including one of Britain's largest breeding populations of [[great crested grebe]]. It has many uncommon wetland plants and insects, including over forty rare species of invertebrates. It is also one of the few London sites with [[Eurasian water shrew|water shrews]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=M035&sType=sinc|title=Brent Reservoir (Welsh Harp)|publisher=Greenspace Information for Greater London|year=2013|accessdate=16 August 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927012412/http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=M035&sType=sinc|archivedate=27 September 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Moat Mount Open Space and Mote End Farm#Bruno's Field|Bruno's Field]]\n|[[File:Bruno's Field.JPG|100px|alt=Bruno's Field is hidden behind houses, and this is a view of trees in the field from Worcester Crescent]] || 6.6  || [[Mill Hill]] <br/><small>{{coord|  51.626| -0.246 |type:landmark_region:GB|name=   Bruno's Field }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 215 934}}</small>|| NO || B2 || This steeply sloping site has a varied topography. On higher ground there are dry areas, while lower down there are areas of bog crossed by several small streams. The field has typical pasture herbs, a scattering of mature trees and a wide variety of birds.<ref>Hewlett, p. 72</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Burtonhole Lane and Pasture]]\n|[[File:Burtonhole Lane.JPG|100px|alt=Burtonhole Lane]]|| 8.5  || [[Mill Hill]] <br/><small>{{coord| 51.620|-0.207  |type:landmark_region:GB|name=   Burtonhole Lane and Pasture }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 242 927}}</small>|| PP || B2 || Burtonhole Lane is an old green lane which is now a bridleway and footpath. Its hedgerow has several species of trees, such as [[Sorbus torminalis|wild service-tree]] and [[Dioscorea communis|black bryony]], which suggest that it is ancient, and its verge is rich in wild flowers. The pasture area is dominated by [[Holcus lanatus|Yorkshire Fog]]. It is crossed by Burtonhole Brook, which supports a number of uncommon plant species.<ref>Hewlett, pp. 76\u201377</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Cherry Tree Wood]] \n|[[File:Cherry Tree Wood 2.JPG|alt=Cherry Tree Wood in winter|100px]]|| 4.7  || [[East Finchley]] <br/><small>{{coord|  51.586|-0.160 |type:landmark_region:GB|name=  Cherry Tree Wood  }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 275 890}}</small>|| P || L || This local park was once part of the [[Bishop of London]]'s Great Hornsey Park. it has an inner area of lawn with a playground and tennis courts, which is surrounded by the surviving ancient woodland. Its tree canopy is mainly oak and hornbeam, and its sparse undergrowth has a number of species associated with ancient woodland, such as [[Allium ursinum|wild garlic]] and [[wood-sedge]].<ref>Hewlett, p. 92</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Clarefield Park]]\n|[[File:Clarefield Park.JPG|100px|alt=Clarefield Park in spring]]|| 3.2  || [[Brent Cross]] <br/><small>{{coord| 51.572|-0.221  |type:landmark_region:GB|name=  Clarefield Park  }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 232 874}}</small>|| P || L || This small park has mown grass, a children's playground, scented shrubs and a small wildlife pond.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaL16&sType=sinc|title=Clarefield Park|publisher=Greenspace Information for Greater London|year=2013|accessdate=16 August 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927012408/http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaL16&sType=sinc|archivedate=27 September 2013}}</ref> In October 2010 Barnet Council gave planning consent for the [[Brent Cross#Development|Brent Cross Cricklewood Planning Application]], which includes closure of the Clarefield Park and development of the area.<ref>Planning report PDU/1483/01, Greater London Authority, 11 February 2009, p. 41</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.barnet.gov.uk/info/940028/cricklewood_brent_cross/530/cricklewood_brent_cross|title=Cricklewood Brent Cross|publisher=London Borough of Barnet|accessdate=18 February 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130508053629/http://www.barnet.gov.uk/info/940028/cricklewood_brent_cross/530/cricklewood_brent_cross|archivedate=8 May 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Clay Lane]]\n|[[File:Clay Lane.JPG|100px|alt=Clay Lane]]|| 1.8 || [[Edgware]] <br/><small>{{coord|   51.630|-0.273|type:landmark_region:GB|name=   Clay Lane }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 194 939}}</small>|| P || L || This is an ancient green lane which leads from Edgwarebury into the Hertfordshire countryside. An old hedge bank and herbaceous plants associated with ancient woodland suggest that it is of considerable antiquity. Its canopy has fine old oaks above an understorey of [[midland hawthorn]], [[blackthorn]] and hazel.<ref name=\"Hewlett, p. 86\">Hewlett, p. 86</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Clitterhouse Recreation Ground]]\n|[[File:Clitterhouse Recreation Ground.JPG|100px|alt=Clitterhouse Recreation Ground]]|| 16 || [[Brent Cross]]<br/><small> {{coord| 51.569|-0.215  |type:landmark_region:GB|name= Clitterhouse Recreation Ground   }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 238 871}}</small>|| P || L || This large recreation ground is managed as a sports field, and its main wildlife interest is in the unmanaged perimeter which has species such as crab apple which are typical of ancient hedgerows.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaL06&sType=sinc|title=Clitterhouse Recreation Ground|publisher=Greenspace Information for Greater London|year=2013|accessdate=16 August 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927012414/http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaL06&sType=sinc|archivedate=27 September 2013}}</ref> The Brent Cross Cricklewood scheme includes improvements to the Recreation Ground.<ref>Planning report PDU/1483/01, p. 4</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[College Farm]]\n|[[File:College Farm2009.JPG|100px|alt=College Farm driveway]]|| 4.5  || [[Finchley]]<br/><small> {{coord| 51.593|-0.202  |type:landmark_region:GB|name=  College Farm  }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 246 897}}</small>|| PP || L || College Farm in central Finchley was a working farm open to the public from 1980 until the foot and mouth epidemic in 2001. A charitable trust purchased the site in 2006, but as of March 2013 efforts to re-open the farm have failed, and the farm buildings are an equestrian shop. The site has trees and scrub which provide a habitat for birds, and [[pipistrelle bats]] have been recorded.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaL14&sType=sinc|title=College Farm|publisher=Greenspace Information for Greater London|year=2013|accessdate=16 August 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927012351/http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaL14&sType=sinc|archivedate=27 September 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Coppett's Wood and Scrublands|Coppett's Wood and Scrublands Local Nature Reserve]]\n|[[File:Coppett's Wood.JPG|100px|alt=Path in Coppett's Wood]]|| 12 || [[Colney Hatch]]<br/><small> {{coord|   51.609|-0.157|type:landmark_region:GB|name=  Coppett's Wood and Scrublands  }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 277 915}}</small>|| P || B1 LNR || These sites provide a range of wildlife habitats. Coppett's Wood has a population of [[juneberry]], and a pond which has [[yellow iris]] and breeding [[common frog]]s and [[smooth newt]]s. Scrublands is on the site of a former sewage works. It has a number of rare plant and insect species.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaBI06&sType=sinc|title=Coppett's Wood and Scrublands Local Nature Reserve|publisher=Greenspace Information for Greater London|year=2013|accessdate=16 August 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131022204028/http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaBI06&sType=sinc|archivedate=22 October 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Copthall Railway Walk and Copthall Old Common]]\n|[[File:Copthall Railway Walk.JPG|100px|alt=The path of the old railway line along Copthall Railway Walk]]|| 11  || [[Mill Hill]]<br/><small> {{coord| 51.607|-0.223  |type:landmark_region:GB|name=  Copthall Railway Walk and Copthall Old Common  }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 231 912}}</small>|| P || B2 || This is a green path along an old railway line, with Copthall Old Common at one side. The grassland on the walk is mostly [[false oat-grass]], with a wide diversity of wild flowers. The hedges have some fine old oaks and areas of bluebells. A pond on the common has [[yellow iris]] and [[water-starwort]]. The site also has a range of birds and invertebrates, including [[Lampyris noctiluca|glow-worm]]s, a scarce and declining species.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaBII11&sType=sinc|title=Copthall Railway Walk and Copthall Old Common|publisher=Greenspace Information for Greater London|year=2013|accessdate=16 August 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927012334/http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaBII11&sType=sinc|archivedate=27 September 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Copthall South Fields]]\n|[[File:Copthall South Fields hedgrerow.JPG|100px|alt=Hedgerow in Copthall South Fields]]|| 6  || [[Mill Hill]] <br/><small>{{coord|  51.602|-0.233 |type:landmark_region:GB|name=   Copthall South Fields }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 225 908}}</small>|| P || L || The fields have what the LEU described as \"a surprisingly rural quality\", even though they lie alongside the [[A1 in London|A1 road]]. The hedgerow trees are oak, ash and [[field maple]], and the fields contain flowers typical of clay grassland, such as [[Lathyrus pratensis|meadow vetchling]], [[Ranunculus acris|meadow buttercup]] and [[Sorrel|common sorrel]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaL23&sType=sinc|title=Copthall South Fields|publisher=Greenspace Information for Greater London|year=2013|accessdate=16 August 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927012336/http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaL23&sType=sinc|archivedate=27 September 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Deans Brook]] and [[Stoneyfields Park]] \n! scope=\"row\"| [[File:Deans Brook.JPG|100px|alt=Deans Brook in Stoneyfields Park]]\n||3.3  || [[Edgware]] <br/><small>{{coord|  51.625|-0.263 |type:landmark_region:GB|name=   Deans Brook and Stoneyfields Park }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 203 929}}</small>|| PP || B2 || [[Kingfisher]]s and [[grey wagtail]]s are often seen along the two kilometre Deans Brook, which largely follows a natural course. In Stoneyfields Park it has been widened into an ornamental lake, which has a wide fringe of tall water plants such as [[Typha latifolia|great]] and [[Typha angustifolia|lesser reedmace]], and breeding birds such as coots, moorhens and mallards. The woodland in the park is oak and hazel, and the hedgerows have plants which show that it is ancient, such as [[Carex sylvatica|wood-sedge]] and [[Allium ursinum|ramsons]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaBII03&sType=sinc|title=Deans Brook and Stoneyfields Park|publisher=Greenspace Information for Greater London|year=2013|accessdate=16 August 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927012349/http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaBII03&sType=sinc|archivedate=27 September 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Drivers Hill]]\n|[[File:Drivers Hill field.JPG|100px|alt=Drivers Hill]] || 10 || [[Mill Hill]]<br/><small> {{coord| 51.616|-0.221  |type:landmark_region:GB|name=  Drivers Hill  }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 231 920}}</small>|| V || B2 || This site consists of several fields and two small woods. The pasture areas have a variety of grasses and wild flowers, including some typical of old pasture, such as [[Cynosurus cristatus|crested dog's-tail]] and [[Carex leporina|oval sedge]]. Wetter areas have plants such as [[Deschampsia cespitosa|tufted hair-grass]] and [[Lotus pedunculatus|greater bird's-foot-trefoil]], while the woods are mainly oak, ash and sycamore.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaBII10&sType=sinc|title=Drivers Hill|publisher=Greenspace Information for Greater London|year=2013|accessdate=16 August 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927012340/http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaBII10&sType=sinc|archivedate=27 September 2013}}</ref> \n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[East Finchley Cemetery]]\n|[[File:East Finchley cemetery.jpg|100px|alt=Chapel and gravestones in East Finchley Cemetery]]||  16|| [[East Finchley]]<br/><small> {{coord|  51.592|-0.184 |type:landmark_region:GB|name=  East Finchley Cemetery  }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 258 896}}</small>|| P || L || Most of this cemetery is formally managed, but it has some old oaks which have survived from its rural past, and evergreen trees such as [[Cedrus libani|cedar of Lebanon]] and [[Sequoiadendron giganteum|Wellingtonia]] provide a habitat for [[goldcrest]] and [[coal tit]]. In less managed areas there are wild flowers such as [[Pimpinella saxifraga|burnet saxifrage]], and around the edges of the site ash and sycamore are evolving into woodland.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaL08&sType=sinc|title=East Finchley Cemetery|publisher=Greenspace Information for Greater London|year=2013|accessdate=16 August 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927012356/http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaL08&sType=sinc|archivedate=27 September 2013}}</ref> \n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Edgware Way Grassland|Edgware Way Rough]] \n|[[File:Edgware Way Grassland.JPG|100px|alt=Edgware Way Rough]]|| 5.5  || [[Edgware]] <br/><small>{{coord|  51.625|-0.288 |type:landmark_region:GB|name= Edgware Way Rough   }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 185 932}}</small>|| F || M || This site is [[London Clay]] pasture which has not been cultivated for many years. In areas of damp grassland it has London's largest population of the herb [[Sanguisorba officinalis|great burnet]], and other rare plants characteristic of old meadows include [[Achillea ptarmica|sneezewort]] and [[Succisa pratensis|devil's-bit scabious]]. Breeding birds include the [[yellowhammer]] and [[spotted flycatcher]], both of which are declining species.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=M126&sType=sinc|title=Edgware Way Rough|publisher=Greenspace Information for Greater London|year=2013|accessdate=16 August 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927012332/http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=M126&sType=sinc|archivedate=27 September 2013}}</ref> \n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Edgwarebury Brook]]\n|[[File:Edgwarebury Brook in Edgwarebury Park.JPG|100px|alt=Edgwarebury Brook in Edgwarebury Park]]||  5 || [[Edgware]]<br/><small> {{coord|  51.624|-0.284 |type:landmark_region:GB|name=   Edgwarebury Brook }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 188 935}}</small>|| V || B2 || This stream rises among fields and flows through Edgware Way Rough on to suburban Edgware, where it join Deans Brook. The most important section ecologically is the upper part, which was rated by the LEU as one of the best areas of wetland vegetation in Barnet. There is a mass of [[Glyceria fluitans|floating sweet-grass]] with clumps of [[Veronica beccabunga|brooklime]] and [[Persicaria hydropiper|water pepper]]. The banks have clumps of [[Persicaria hydropiper|great willowherb]] and [[Bidens tripartita|trifid bur-marigold]].<ref name=\"Hewlett, p. 67\">Hewlett, p. 67</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Edgwarebury Park]]\n|[[File:Edgwarebury Park.JPG|100px|alt=Edgwarebury Park]]|| 15  || [[Edgware]]<br/><small> {{coord| 51.625|-0.283  |type:landmark_region:GB|name=   Edgwarebury Park }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 190 934}}</small>|| P || L || The hedgerows in this large park have fine oak and ash trees, and the presence of [[Sorbus torminalis|wild service-trees]] is considered an indicator that the hedges are ancient. It has a variety of wild flowers in damp areas and nesting birds include [[song thrush]], [[mistle thrush]], [[great spotted woodpecker]] and [[common whitethroat]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaL19&sType=sinc|title=Edgwarebury Park|publisher=Greenspace Information for Greater London|year=2013|accessdate=16 August 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927012358/http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaL19&sType=sinc|archivedate=27 September 2013}}</ref> \n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Folly Brook]] and [[Darland's Lake Nature Reserve]]\n|[[File:Darlands Lake 2.JPG|100px|alt=Darland's Lake]]|| 11  || [[Arkley]]/[[Woodside Park (Barnet, London)|Woodside Park]]<br/><small> {{coord| 51.625|-0.205  |type:landmark_region:GB|name=  Folly Brook and Darland's Lake Nature Reserve  }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 240 934}}</small>|| P || B1 || Darland's Lake, which is now a nature reserve, was originally an ornamental feature created by damming Folly Brook. The water quality is good, and Darland's Lake has extensive reed beds. On its margin there is a boggy wood of willows and alder, a scarce habitat in London. The site has a number of tree species typical of ancient woodland, and a diverse bird and invertebrate population, while eighteen species of mammal have been recorded.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaBI02&sType=sinc|title=Folly Brook and Darland's Lake Nature Reserve|publisher=Greenspace Information for Greater London|year=2013|accessdate=16 August 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927012354/http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaBI02&sType=sinc|archivedate=27 September 2013}}</ref> \n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Friary Park]]\n|[[File:Friary Park formal garden.JPG|100px|alt=Formal garden in Friary Park]]|| 8.8 || [[Friern Barnet]] <br/><small>{{coord| 51.618|-0.162  |type:landmark_region:GB|name= Friary Park   }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 273 926}}</small>|| P || L || Old oak trees date from before the foundation of the park, and they support woodland birds such as [[nuthatch]] and [[treecreeper]]. Near a small stream, a tributary of [[Pymme's Brook]], there are wildflowers such as [[Anthriscus sylvestris|cow parsley]], [[lesser celandine]], [[Viola riviniana|dog violet]] and [[Alliaria petiolata|garlic mustard]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaL12&sType=sinc|title=Friary Park|publisher=Greenspace Information for Greater London|year=2013|accessdate=16 August 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927012343/http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaL12&sType=sinc|archivedate=27 September 2013}}</ref> \n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Glebe Lane Pastures]]\n|[[File:Glebe Lane Pastures.JPG|100px|alt=Horses grazing in Glebe Lane Pastures]]|| 11  || [[Arkley]]<br/><small> {{coord|   51.645|-0.234|type:landmark_region:GB|name=   Glebe Lane Pastures }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 223 954}}</small>|| V || B1 ||This is an area of five fields which was once part of a communal pasture called Barnet Common. The grassland is unimproved clay grassland, a relic of the old common. It has many species of wild flowers, and the most important aspect of the site is its diverse old meadow plants. Some of the rarities have been found in temporary pools, such as [[Minuartia stricta|bog stitchwort]] and [[Ranunculus peltatus|pond]] and [[Ranunculus hederaceus|ivy-leaved crowfoot]].<ref>Hewlett, p. 52</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Glebelands Local Nature Reserve]]\n|[[File:Glebelands.JPG|100px|alt=Glebelands nature reserves]]||  7.5 || [[Colney Hatch]] <br/><small>{{coord| 51.604|-0.169 |type:landmark_region:GB|name=Glebelands Local Nature Reserve}} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 270 911}}</small>|| P || B1 LNR || This is a fragment of the old [[Finchley Common]]. It has tall scrub and woodland, together with numerous streams and seasonal ponds. The pools have a number of rare species, and it is the only known London site for [[lesser water-plantain]]. Other rarities are thread-leaved water-crowfoot (''[[Ranunculus trichophyllus]]'') and [[Veronica scutellata|marsh speedwell]], and the site has diverse breeding birds.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaBI07&sType=sinc|title=Glebelands Local Nature Reserve|publisher=Greenspace Information for Greater London|year=2013|accessdate=16 August 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927012338/http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaBI07&sType=sinc|archivedate=27 September 2013}}</ref> \n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Greenhill Gardens]]\n|[[File:Greenhill Gardens lake.JPG|100px|alt=Lake in Greenhill Gardens]]||  1.5 || [[Chipping Barnet|High Barnet]] <br/><small>{{coord| 51.6446|-0.1824  |type:landmark_region:GB|name=   Greenhill Gardens }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 258 955}}</small>|| P || L ||  The principal feature of this small park is its large lake, with a wooded island. Water birds include [[mallard]], [[mute swan]], [[coot]] and [[moorhen]], and [[pipistrelle]] and [[Common noctule|noctule]] bats have been seen foraging.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaL10&sType=sinc|title=Greenhill Gardens|publisher=Greenspace Information for Greater London|year=2013|accessdate=16 August 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927012325/http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaL10&sType=sinc|archivedate=27 September 2013}}</ref>  \n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Hadley Green]] \n|[[File:Hadley Green.JPG|100px|alt=Path in Hadley Green]]|| 10  || [[Monken Hadley]]<br/><small> {{coord| 51.661|-0.199  |type:landmark_region:GB|name=  Hadley Green  }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 246 973}}</small>|| P || M || Hadley Green was the site of one of the major battles of the [[Wars of the Roses]], the [[Battle of Barnet]] in 1471. It is mainly acid grassland with some wetter areas and several ponds. It has a number of rare species of plant, such as [[Nardus stricta|mat-grass]] and [[Carex leporina|oval sedge]] in the grassland, [[Ranunculus flammula|lesser spearwort]] and [[Senecio congestus|marsh ragwort]] in the ditches, and [[Myosotis laxa|tufted forget-me-not]] and [[Rumex pulcher|fiddle dock]] in the ponds. There are also eleven species of dragonflies and damselflies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=M032&sType=sinc|title=Hadley Green|publisher=Greenspace Information for Greater London|year=2013|accessdate=16 August 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927012329/http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=M032&sType=sinc|archivedate=27 September 2013}}</ref> \n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Hampstead Heath#Extension|Hampstead Heath Extension]] and [[Golders Hill Park]]\n|[[File:Golders Hill Park in 2006.jpg|100px|alt=Formal garden in Golders Hill Park]]|| 46{{efn|Hampstead Heath SINC is composed of the main [[Hampstead Heath|Heath]] in the [[London Borough of Camden]] and Hampstead Heath Extension and Golders Hill Park in Barnet. 46 hectares is in Barnet out of the total of 329.}} || [[Golders Green]]<br/><small> {{coord|   51.575|-0.186|type:landmark_region:GB|name=   Hampstead Heath Extension and Golders Hill Park }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 258 878}} </small>|| P || M ||The LEU described the hedges of Hampstead Heath Extension as some of the best on the Heath. It also has a chain of seven ponds which have a wide variety of aquatic and pond margin plant species. Golders Hill Park has areas of formal and less managed parkland. Swan Pond is a large ornamental lake which has a variety of exotic and native wildfowl.<ref>Hewlett, pp. 44\u201345</ref> \n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Hendon Park|Hendon Park and Northern Line Railway Cutting]]\n|[[File:Hendon Park.JPG|100px|alt=Hendon Park]]|| 14  || [[Hendon]]<br/><small> {{coord|51.582|-0.222   |type:landmark_region:GB|name=  Hendon Park and Northern Line Railway Cutting  }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 233 884}}</small>|| P || L || The site is mainly informal parkland, with mown grass and mature trees. A variety of small birds forage among the tall hedgerows at the northern end. The railway cutting has rough grassland and patches of woodland, which provide a habitat for birds such as the [[great spotted woodpecker]] and [[goldcrest]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaL18&sType=sinc|title=Hendon Park and Northern Line Railway Cutting|publisher=Greenspace Information for Greater London|year=2013|accessdate=16 August 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927012403/http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaL18&sType=sinc|archivedate=27 September 2013}}</ref> \n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[King George's Fields (Monken Hadley)|King George's Fields]]\n|[[File:King George's Fields.JPG|100px|alt=King George's Fields]]|| 27 || [[Monken Hadley]]<br/><small> {{coord|  51.656|-0.195 |type:landmark_region:GB|name=  King George's Fields  }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 250 969}}</small>|| P || B2 || This site is mainly covered with coarse grasses, but it also has herb-rich fields dominated by [[Agrostis stolonifera|creeping bent]] and [[Festuca rubra|red fescue]], together with wild flowers commonly found on unimproved grassland. Oak trees grow in old hedges, and breeding birds include sparrowhawk and [[stock dove]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaBII15&sType=sinc|title=King George's Fields|publisher=Greenspace Information for Greater London|year=2013|accessdate=16 August 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927012304/http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaBII15&sType=sinc|archivedate=27 September 2013}}</ref>  \n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Lakeside Nature Reserve]]\n|[[File:Lakeside Nature Reserve.JPG|100px|alt=View of Lakeside Nature Reserve from a footpath off Strathmore Gardens]]||  0.6 || [[Church End, Barnet|Church End]]<br/><small> {{coord|   51.5994|-0.1850|type:landmark_region:GB|name= Lakeside Nature Reserve   }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 257 904}}</small>|| V || L || This site is a lake with a small island behind an office block, surrounded by a belt of trees. The island provides a safe breeding ground for wildfowl, away from mammalian predators. The lake also has fish, frogs, toads and terrapins.<ref>Hewlett, p. 94</ref> \n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Dollis Brook|Lower Dollis Brook]], [[Brent Park (Hendon)|Brent Park]] and [[River Brent]]\n|[[File:Dollis brook windsor open space.JPG|100px|alt=Dollis Brook in Windsor Open Space]]|| 28 || [[Woodside Park]]/[[Hendon]]<br/><small> {{coord| 51.572|-0.236  |type:landmark_region:GB|name= Lower Dollis Brook   }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 243 906}}</small>|| P || B2 || This site covers Dollis Brook between Woodside Park and its end in [[Temple Fortune]], where it becomes the River Brent, the Brent as far as the [[A1 in London|A1]], and Brent Park. At the Woodside Park end there is a wild area with old ivy-clad oaks and alder. Brent Park has a lake which may have been created by the abbots of [[Westminster Abbey|Westminster]] almost a thousand years ago. It has a wooded island which provides a refuge for birds.<ref>Hewlett, pp. 79\u201380</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Scratchwood#Mill Hill Golf Course|Mill Hill Golf Course]]\n|[[File:Mill Hill Golf Course 2.JPG|100px|alt=Mill Hill Golf Course]] ||60 || [[Mill Hill]] <br/><small>{{coord| 51.634| -0.259  |type:landmark_region:GB|name=  Mill Hill Golf Course  }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 206 942}}</small>|| NO || B1 || The golf course has several small streams which meet in Stoneyfields Lake, which was formed by damming Deans Brook. On the edges of the fairways there is a variety of wild flowers, some of them relics of old farm meadows. The most important area ecologically is acid grassland which contains the rare plant [[Genista tinctoria|dyer's greenweed]].<ref>Hewlett, pp. 64\u201365</ref> \n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Mill Hill Old Railway Nature Reserve]] \n|[[File:Mill Hill Old Railway.JPG|100px|alt=Path following the route of the old railway line in Mill Hill Old Railway Nature Reserve]]|| 9  || [[Mill Hill]]<br/><small> {{coord|  51.612|-0.257 |type:landmark_region:GB|name=  Mill Hill Old Railway Nature Reserve  }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 203 917}}</small>|| PL|| B2 || This linear nature reserve on the site of an old railway line is managed by the [[London Wildlife Trust]]. Trees in the woodland canopy include oak and sycamore, and there is a scrub layer of hawthorn, [[blackthorn]] and [[Salix atrocinerea|grey willow]]. The grassland has a range of wild flowers, and the site has a large population of [[Anguis|slow-worms]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaBII04&sType=sinc|title=Mill Hill Old Railway Nature Reserve|publisher=Greenspace Information for Greater London|year=2013|accessdate=16 August 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160129053633/http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaBII04&sType=sinc|archivedate=29 January 2016}}</ref>  \n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Mill Hill Substation Pastures]] \n|[[File:Mill Hill Substation Pastures 2.JPG|100px|alt=Mill Hill Substation Pastures]]||  15 || [[Mill Hill]] <br/><small>{{coord|   51.6168|-0.2106|type:landmark_region:GB|name= Mill Hill Substation Pastures   }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 240 925}}</small>|| V || M || The LEU described this site as a \"remarkable example of unimproved herb-rich pasture on damp clay soil, with substantial populations of attractive and locally uncommon wild flowers\". Burtonhole Brook crosses the site, providing a corridor of damp habitat, and old hedgerows and small areas of woodland provide a refuge for birds.<ref>Hewlett, pp. 47\u201348</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Moat Mount Open Space and Mote End Farm|Moat Mount Open Space]] and [[Barnet Gate Wood]]\n|[[File:Leg of Mutton Pond.JPG|100px|alt=Leg of Mutton Pond in Moat Mount Open Space]]||110  || [[Mill Hill]] <br/><small>{{coord|  51.634|-0.253 |type:landmark_region:GB|name=  Moat Mount Open Space and Barnet Gate Wood  }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 215 943}}</small>|| P || B2 LNR || Moat Mount is a large hilly area, which slopes down to valleys, which have open fields crossed by old hedgerows. Towards the top of the hill woodland opens out to Leg of Mutton Pond, which has clumps of water-lilies and [[Elodea nuttallii|Nuttall's waterweed]]. The site also includes the neighbouring Barnet Gate Wood, which is probably a remnant of an ancient forest.<ref>Hewlett, pp. 70\u201372</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Monken Hadley Common]]\n|[[File:Monken Hadley Common 1.JPG|100px|alt=Monken Hadley Common]]|| 72  || [[Monken Hadley]] <br/><small>{{coord|  51.660|-0.177 |type:landmark_region:GB|name=  Monken Hadley Common  }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 263 972}}</small>|| P || B1 CL || This large common is mostly wooded, with small areas of grassland. [[Daubenton's bat]]s forage over an artificial lake called Jack's Lake. The principal trees are oak, hornbeam and beech, and the ground flora includes several plants which are normally only present in ancient woodland. Breeding birds include sparrowhawk, [[tawny owl]] and cuckoo.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaBI03&sType=sinc|title=Monken Hadley Common|publisher=Greenspace Information for Greater London|year=2013|accessdate=16 August 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927012311/http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaBI03&sType=sinc|archivedate=27 September 2013}}</ref>  \n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Mutton Brook]]\n|[[File:Mutton Brook in Brookside Walk.JPG|100px|alt=Mutton Brook in Brookside Walk]]||13  || [[Hampstead Garden Suburb]]<br/><small> {{coord| 51.587|-0.210  |type:landmark_region:GB|name=  Mutton Brook  }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 251 892}}</small>|| P || L || The brook is a tributary of the [[River Brent]]. Oak, ash and willow trees fringe the bank, providing a habitat for birds, and [[grey wagtail]]s forage at the water's edge. Woodland wild flowers include [[Mercurialis perennis|dog's mercury]] and [[Petasites fragrans|winter heliotrope]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaL09&sType=sinc|title=The Mutton Brook|publisher=Greenspace Information for Greater London|year=2013|accessdate=16 August 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927012315/http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaL09&sType=sinc|archivedate=27 September 2013}}</ref><ref>Hewlett, p. 91</ref>  \n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[New Southgate Cemetery]]\n|[[File:Brunswick Park Cemetery, London N11 - geograph.org.uk - 759207.jpg|100px|alt=New Southgate Cemetery]]||  20 || [[Brunswick Park]] <br/><small>{{coord|   51.624|-0.144|type:landmark_region:GB|name=   New Southgate Cemetery }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 286 933}}</small>|| P || B2 || The cemetery is closely managed in the vicinity of recent burials, but woodland has developed in other areas, where young oak, ash, birch and sycamore are growing between mature oak and yew trees. There is a range of breeding birds such as [[European green woodpecker|green]] and [[great spotted woodpecker]]s, [[coal tit]] and [[nuthatch]], and the cemetery is the most northerly known site for the dusky cockroach, a native species.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaBII21&sType=sinc|title=New Southgate Cemetery|publisher=Greenspace Information for Greater London|year=2013|accessdate=16 August 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927012251/http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaBII21&sType=sinc|archivedate=27 September 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Friary Park#North Middlesex Golf Course Ponds|North Middlesex Golf Course Ponds]] \n|[[File:North Middlesex Golf Club ponds 2.JPG|100px|alt=Pond at North Middlesex Golf Course]]|| |0.8  || [[Whetstone, London|Whetstone]] <br/><small>{{coord| 51.621| -0.168  |type:landmark_region:GB|name=  North Middlesex Golf Course Ponds  }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 269 930}}</small>|| NO || B2 || These ponds have one of few known populations of [[palmate newt]]s in Barnet, and there is also a colony of the more common [[smooth newt]]. The pond edges have some Michaelmas daisies and [[Mentha aquatica|water mint]]. A ditch leads to a small area of woodland, and this is probably an important corridor for amphibia.<ref>Hewlett, pp. 80\u201381</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Northern Line Embankment, High Barnet]]\n|[[File:Northern Line Embankment, High Barnet.JPG|100px|alt=Northern Line railway embankment from a footbridge off Wyatts Farm Open Space]]||| 6.5 || [[Totteridge]]/[[High Barnet]] <br/><small>{{coord|  51.641|-0.185 |type:landmark_region:GB|name= Northern Line Embankment, High Barnet   }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 256 951}}</small>|| V || B2 || The vegetation varies between low bramble scrub and light woodland, and it provides a habitat for small birds such as tits and finches. The main ecological significance of the site lies in one of Barnet's few known colonies of the [[common lizard]], which are protected by the absence of pesticides, and freedom from dogs, cats and people.<ref>Hewlett, p. 80</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Oak Hill Wood]]\n|[[File:Oak Hill Wood.JPG|100px|alt=Oak Hill Wood in East Barnet]]||  10 || [[East Barnet]] <br/><small>{{coord|  51.6409|-0.1521 |type:landmark_region:GB|name= Oak Hill Wood   }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 280 951}}</small>|| P || B1 LNR || This wood is managed by the [[London Wildlife Trust]]. The canopy is oak, hornbeam and ash, with some horse chestnut trees. Ground plants include bluebell and wood speedwell. A small stream flows through the wood, and a meadow has common wild flowers and butterflies. The site also has several bat species.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaBI04&sType=sinc|title=Oak Hill Wood Local Nature Reserve|publisher=Greenspace Information for Greater London|year=2013|accessdate=16 August 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160127133958/http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaBI04&sType=sinc|archivedate=27 January 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Oakleigh Park Rail Cutting]] \n|[[File:Oakleigh Park Rail Cutting looking south.jpg|100px|alt=Oakleigh Park Rail Cutting looking south]]|| 8.0  || [[Oakleigh Park]] <br/><small>{{coord|  51.633|-0.162 |type:landmark_region:GB|name=  Oakleigh Park Rail Cutting  }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 272 944}}</small>|| V || L || This site has a diverse habitat. The eastern bank has an open expanse of bramble scrub with clumps of [[blackthorn]], hawthorn and [[dog-rose]]. The western bank has a mature woodland of oak, ash and sycamore, with [[Salix caprea|goat willow]] in wetter areas. Tall herbs are useful to seed eating birds such [[European goldfinch|goldfinch]], wrens and [[dunnock]]s.<ref>Hewlett, pp. 91\u201392</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Princes Park, Temple Fortune|Princes Park]]\n|[[File:Princes Park tree.JPG|100px|alt=Princes Park in Temple Fortune]]||  1.2 || [[Temple Fortune]] <br/><small>{{coord|  51.5820|-0.2061 |type:landmark_region:GB|name=    Princes Park }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 243 885}}</small>|| P || L || This small park is highly managed, with mown lawns and flowerbeds, but some of the old trees pre-date the surrounding houses. In the south-east corner a small woodland appears to be a fragment of an old farm wood. Mature hawthorns around the perimeter may be relics of old farm hedgerows.<ref>Hewlett, p. 93</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Pymmes Brook|Pymme's Brook]]\n|[[File:Pymme's Brook in Oak Hill Park 2.JPG|100px|alt=Pymme's Brook in Oak Hill Park]]||13  || [[Monken Hadley]]/[[New Southgate]]<br/><small> {{coord| 51.6320| -0.1462  |type:landmark_region:GB|name=  Pymme's Brook  }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 284 942}} </small>|| P || B2 || Two separate sections of Pymme's Brook are included in this site. The northern section, which runs 500 metres from Monken Hadley, goes through rough grassland and scattered scrub, with a narrow strip of oak woodland. The three kilometre southern stretch to the boundary with [[London Borough of Enfield|Enfield]] is largely wooded. One part is ancient, with an understorey which includes [[Sorbus torminalis|wild service-trees]], [[midland hawthorn]], [[field maple]] and crab apple.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaBII20&sType=sinc|title=Pymme's Brook|publisher=Greenspace Information for Greater London|year=2013|accessdate=16 August 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927012256/http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaBII20&sType=sinc|archivedate=27 September 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Rowley Green Common]]\n|[[File:Rowley Green Common.JPG|alt=Rowley Green Common, Arkley|100px]]|| 4.9  || [[Arkley]] <br/><small>{{coord| 51.6502|-0.2433  |type:landmark_region:GB|name=  Rowley Green Common  }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 217 960}}</small>|| P || M LNR CL || This site has a mosaic of habitats with different conditions and many rare species. Most of it is woodland with fairly young trees, and the most important area ecologically is a [[bog|sphagnum bog]], described by the LEU as an extremely rare habitat in south-east England. The site also has an area of acid grassland and a pond which supports diverse wetland plants.<ref>Hewlett, pp. 32\u201333</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Rowley Lodge Field]] \n|[[File:Rowley Lodge Field 1.JPG|100px|alt=Rowley Lodge Field, Arkley]]||  4.4 || [[Arkley]]<br/><small> {{coord|   51.6456|-0.2410|type:landmark_region:GB|name=   Rowley Lodge Field }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 218 955}}</small>|| F || B2|| This is an old hay meadow with a few oak trees and small patches of scrub. It has diverse wild flowers, including [[Sanguisorba officinalis|great burnet]] and pignut. Areas of acid grassland are dominated by [[Festuca rubra|red fescue]], together with [[Rumex acetosella|sheep's sorrel]] and [[Potentilla erecta|tormentil]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaBII23&sType=sinc|title=Rowley Lodge field|publisher=Greenspace Information for Greater London|year=2013|accessdate=16 August 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927012244/http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaBII23&sType=sinc|archivedate=27 September 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Scratchwood]]\n|[[File:Scratchwood.JPG|100px|alt=Path in Scratchwood, Mill Hill]]||57 || [[Mill Hill]] <br/><small>{{coord|  51.640|-0.264 |type:landmark_region:GB|name=   Scratchwood }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 201 948}}</small>|| P || M LNR || Part of Scratchwood is ancient woodland, possibly dating back to the end of the last ice age, which has small streams, tall [[Quercus petraea|sessile oaks]] and old hornbeams. Other areas include Bluebell Wood, which is more open and has extensive carpets of wild flowers, and Scratchwood Pond which has marshy areas nearby described by the LEU as botanically very rich.<ref>Hewlett, pp. 48\u201351</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Silk Stream]] and [[Burnt Oak Brook]] \n|[[File:Silk Stream in Silkstream Park.jpg|100px|alt=Silk Stream in Silkstream Park]]|| 8 || [[Edgware]]<br/><small> {{coord|  51.599| -0.259 |type:landmark_region:GB|name=  Silk Stream and Burnt Oak Brook  }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 207 903}}</small>|| PP || B2 || These streams were described by the LEU as valuable wildlife corridors through suburban housing. [[Mallard]]s and [[grey wagtail]]s are often seen along the banks, and fish include [[three-spined stickleback]]. The streams are best seen when they go through parks, such as Silkstream Park, Montrose Recreation Ground and Rushgrove Park.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaBII05&sType=sinc|title=Silk Stream and Burnt Oak Brook|publisher=Greenspace Information for Greater London|year=2013|accessdate=16 August 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927012313/http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaBII05&sType=sinc|archivedate=27 September 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[St Pancras and Islington Cemetery]]\n|[[File:Islington St Pancras Cemetery.JPG|100px|alt=Gravestones in St Pancras and Islington Cemetery]]|| 74  || [[East Finchley]]<br/><small> {{coord|  51.600|-0.165 |type:landmark_region:GB|name= St Pancras and Islington Cemetery    }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 272 907}}</small>|| P || B2 || Parts of this cemetery which are no longer used for burials are managed for nature conservation. These areas have woodland and open grassland, while Strawberry Vale Brook which flows through the north-east corner. The LEU considered the understorey of the wood as surprisingly rich, including pignut, [[Ranunculus auricomus|goldilocks buttercup]], [[Cardamine pratensis|cuckooflower]], primrose, [[Fragaria vesca|wild]] and [[Potentilla sterilis|barren strawberries]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaBII19&sType=sinc|title=St Pancras and Islington Cemetery|publisher=Greenspace Information for Greater London|year=2013|accessdate=16 August 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927012308/http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaBII19&sType=sinc|archivedate=27 September 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Sulloniacis#Sulloniacis Pastures|Sulloniacis Pastures]]\n|[[File:Sulloniacis plaque 2.jpg|100px|alt=Plaque for Sullionacis Roman site]] ||  4.2|| [[Edgware]]<br/><small> {{coord|51.632| -0.302   |type:landmark_region:GB|name=  Sulloniacis Pastures  }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 176 940}}</small>|| V || B2 || Most of this site is herb-rich grassland on London Clay, and it has many flowers typical of clay pasture such as [[Lotus pedunculatus|greater bird's-foot-trefoil]], [[Pimpinella saxifraga|burnet saxifrage]], [[Agrimonia eupatoria|agrimony]] and [[Succisa pratensis|devil's-bit scabious]]. There are also small plots of woodland and scrub.<ref name=\"Hewlett, p. 67\"/> \n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Sunny Hill Park]] and [[St Mary's Churchyard, Hendon|Hendon Churchyard]]\n|[[File:SNV30109.jpg|100px|alt=Sunny Hill Park]]||  22 || [[Hendon]] <br/><small>{{coord|   51.597|-0.230|type:landmark_region:GB|name=   Sunny Hill Park and Hendon Churchyard }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 227 901}}</small>|| P || L || Most of this site is formal parkland, but at the southern end there is a wild flower meadow with [[Centaurea nigra|black knapweed]], [[Sorrel|common sorrel]], [[Stellaria graminea|lesser stitchwort]] and three species of buttercup. An area at the northern end is managed to preserve [[Anguis|slow-worms]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaL03&sType=sinc|title=Sunny Hill Park and Hendon Churchyard|publisher=Greenspace Information for Greater London|year=2013|accessdate=16 August 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927012253/http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaL03&sType=sinc|archivedate=27 September 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[The Mill Field]]\n|[[File:The Mill Field.JPG|100px|alt=Path in The Mill Field, Mill Hill]]|| 3.4|| [[Mill Hill]]<br/><small> {{coord|   51.622|-0.236|type:landmark_region:GB|name=   The Mill Field }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 221 929}}</small>|| P || B2 || The grassland in the more natural part of this site has scattered oak and willow scrub, and mature trees and hedgerows on the periphery. There is a variety of wild flowers, and the [[Lycaena phlaeas|small copper butterfly]] has been recorded. A small pond has rich aquatic flora including [[Bidens cernua|nodding bur-marigold]] and [[Sparganium|branched bur-reed]].<ref>Hewlett, pp. 72\u201373</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Totteridge Common]]\n|[[File:Totteridge Common pond.JPG|100px|alt=Pink Cottage Pond on Totteridge Common]]||  3 || [[Totteridge]] <br/><small>{{coord| 51.6315|-0.2227  |type:landmark_region:GB|name=  Totteridge Common  }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 230 939}}</small>|| P || B2 CL || The trees on this site are mostly sycamore and elm, but it also has two [[Populus nigra|black poplars]], which are considered England's most threatened native tree.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.naturalengland.org.uk/ourwork/conservation/biodiversity/iyb/blackpoplar.aspx|publisher=Natural England|title=Black Poplar|date=25 January 2010|accessdate=23 March 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927112751/http://www.naturalengland.org.uk/ourwork/conservation/biodiversity/iyb/blackpoplar.aspx|archivedate=27 September 2013}}</ref> The most important feature ecologically is a chain of old ponds, which are valuable for dragonflies, other insects and amphibians. Plants in deep water include [[Nymphaea alba|white water-lily]] and [[Potamogeton crispus|curled]] and [[Potamogeton natans|broad-leaved pondweeds]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaBII09&sType=sinc|title=Totteridge Common|publisher=Greenspace Information for Greater London|year=2013|accessdate=16 August 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927012306/http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaBII09&sType=sinc|archivedate=27 September 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Totteridge Green#Totteridge Croft Field (or Dell's Down Acre)|Totteridge Croft Field (or Dell's Down Acre)]]\n| [[File:Totteridge Dell Croft.JPG|100px|alt=View north-west from a footpath towards Totteridge Dell Croft nature reserve]]|| 2.4  || [[Totteridge]]<br/><small> {{coord|  51.626| -0.198 |type:landmark_region:GB|name= Totteridge Croft Field   }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 248 934}}</small>|| NO || B1 || This site was described by the LEU as an interesting example of unimproved clay grassland. Much of it is covered with [[Deschampsia cespitosa|tufted hair-grass]], but there is considerable variety between the different fields. There is a variety of wild flowers, including uncommon species such as [[Achillea ptarmica|sneezewort]] and pignut.<ref>Hewlett, pp. 62\u201364</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Totteridge Fields|Totteridge Fields and Highwood Hill]]\n|[[File:Totteridge Fields.JPG|100px|alt=Totteridge Fields Local Nature Reserve, Arkley]]|| 103 || [[Arkley]]<br/><small>  {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 231 945}}<br>{{coord|   51.632|-0.234|type:landmark_region:GB|name= Totteridge Fields    }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 222 935}} </small>|| PP || M LNR || This site has large areas of uncultivated grassland with old hedgerows. Part of it is a local nature reserve managed by the [[London Wildlife Trust]]. There is a wide range of wild flowers, including some that are locally uncommon, and breeding birds include the [[Eurasian skylark|skylark]], which is a declining species. A number of beetles and spiders found here are nationally rare.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=M034&sType=sinc|title=Totteridge Fields and Highwood Hill|publisher=Greenspace Information for Greater London|year=2013|accessdate=16 August 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924040716/http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=M034&sType=sinc|archivedate=24 September 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Totteridge Green]] \n|[[File:Totteridge Green, Laurel Farm Pond.JPG|100px|alt=Laurel Farm Pond in Totteridge Green]]||  4.6 || [[Totteridge]]<br/><small> {{coord| 51.6281|-0.1953  |type:landmark_region:GB|name=   Totteridge Green }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 250 936}}</small>|| P || B2 CL || This is a typical English village green with open grassland, scattered trees, small areas of scrubby woodland and a pond. The main grasses are [[Lolium perenne|perennial rye-grass]] and other coarse meadow species. There are several damp hollows, probably former ponds, which have uncommon wild flowers such as [[Sanguisorba officinalis|great burnet]] and [[Minuartia stricta|bog stitchwort]]. Woodland plants include [[Polystichum setiferum|soft shield-fern]], which is rare locally.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaBII14&sType=sinc|title=Totteridge Green|publisher=Greenspace Information for Greater London|year=2013|accessdate=16 August 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927012317/http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaBII14&sType=sinc|archivedate=27 September 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Turner's Wood]]\n|[[File:Turner's Wood path.JPG|100px|alt=Entrance to Turner's Wood, Hampstead Garden Suburb]]||  2.4 || [[Hampstead Garden Suburb]]<br/><small> {{coord|  51.5722|-0.1785 |type:landmark_region:GB|name=  Turner's Wood  }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 263 875}}</small>|| NO || B2 || This private nature reserve is a fragment of Bishops Wood, part of the [[Bishop of London]]'s medieval estate. The landscape is undulating, with two small streams going through the centre. The main tree in the canopy is [[sessile oak]], with a rich understorey including [[rowan]], [[midland hawthorn]] and some [[Sorbus torminalis|wild service-trees]]. The site is managed for nature conservation, especially for birds.<ref>Hewlett, p. 84</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Dollis Brook|Upper Dollis Brook]]\n|[[File:Dollis Brook in Brook Farm open space.JPG|100px|alt=Dollis Brook in Brook Farm Open Space]]||  40|| [[Mill Hill]]/[[Woodside Park]]<br/><small> {{coord|   51.5717|-0.2361|type:landmark_region:GB|name=  Upper Dollis Brook  }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 253 943}}</small>|| P || B1 || This six kilometre long stretch runs from Arkley to Woodside Park, and the site also includes neighbouring areas such as Whetstone Stray and Wyatt's Open Space, which have flower-rich meadows divided by old hedges. The hedges have uncommon shrubs such as [[Euonymus|spindle]] and [[buckthorn]]. Birds seen along the stream include [[kingfisher]]s, [[grey wagtail]]s and [[moorhen]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaBI08&sType=sinc|title=Upper Dollis Brook|publisher=Greenspace Information for Greater London|year=2013|accessdate=16 August 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927012258/http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaBI08&sType=sinc|archivedate=27 September 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| [[Woodridge Nature Reserve|Woodridge School Nature Reserve]] \n|[[File:Woodridge Nature Reserve.JPG|100px|alt=Woodridge Nature Reserve in Woodside Park]]|| 2.5 || [[Woodside Park]]<br/><small> {{coord| 51.6227|-0.1955  |type:landmark_region:GB|name=  Woodridge School Nature Reserve  }} <br/> {{gbmappingsmall|TQ 250 930}}</small>|| P || L || This small site was established as a nature garden for local primary schools. It has young oak woodland and rough grassland, which has wild flowers such as pignut and [[Lamium galeobdolon|yellow archangel]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaL20&sType=sinc|title=Woodridge School Nature Reserve|publisher=Greenspace Information for Greater London|year=2013|accessdate=16 August 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130927012247/http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/site-Details.aspx?sID=BaL20&sType=sinc|archivedate=27 September 2013}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==See also==\n{{commons category|Nature reserves in the London Borough of Barnet|Nature reserves in Barnet}}\n*[[Barnet parks and open spaces]]\n*[[List of Sites of Special Scientific Interest in Greater London]]\n*[[List of local nature reserves in Greater London]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|20em}}\n\n==Sources==\n*{{cite book|title=Nature Conservation in Barnet|first1=Jan|last1 =Hewlett|first2=Ian|last2=Yarham|first3=David|last3=Curson|publisher=London Ecology Unit|year=1997|isbn=1 871045 27 4}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/|title=iGiGL the data portal of Greenspace Information for London|publisher=Greenspace Information for Greater London|year=2013|access-date=2013-08-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140114132930/http://www.gigl.org.uk/online/|archive-date=2014-01-14|url-status=dead}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.barnet.gov.uk/info/930058/unitary_development_plan/701/unitary_development_plan|title=Barnet Unitary Development Plan, adopted 2006 (updated 2009)|publisher=London Borough of Barnet|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130118023803/http://www.barnet.gov.uk/info/930058/unitary_development_plan/701/unitary_development_plan|archivedate=2013-01-18}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.london.gov.uk/olc/docs/brent-cross-report.pdf|format=pdf|date=11 February 2009|title=Planning report PDU/1483/01, Brent Cross Cricklewood in the London Borough of Barnet, planning application no. C/17559/08|accessdate=23 July 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120827065230/http://www.london.gov.uk/olc/docs/brent-cross-report.pdf|archivedate=27 August 2012}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.finchleysociety.org.uk/actenvspaceslist.htm |publisher=Finchley Society |title=Finchley and Friern Barnet Green Spaces List |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120109065448/http://www.finchleysociety.org.uk/actenvspaceslist.htm |archivedate=2012-01-09 }}\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.londongardensonline.org.uk/select-borough-results.asp?Borough=Barnet&Submit=Go|title=London Gardens Online: Barnet|publisher=London Parks & Gardens Trust|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120118203741/http://www.londongardensonline.org.uk/select-borough-results.asp?Borough=Barnet&Submit=Go|archivedate=2012-01-18}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.barnet.gov.uk/directory/15/parks |title=Parks and open spaces in the Barnet area |publisher=London Borough of Barnet |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121029072254/http://www.barnet.gov.uk/directory/15/parks |archivedate=2012-10-29 }}\n{{Nature reserves in Barnet}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nature reserves in the London Borough of Barnet}}\n[[Category:Conservation in London]]\n[[Category:Nature reserves in the London Borough of Barnet| ]]\n[[Category:Geography of the London Borough of Barnet]]\n[[Category:Parks and open spaces in the London Borough of Barnet| ]]\n[[Category:London nature-related lists]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 2012-13 \u2192 2012\u201313", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_nature_reserves_in_the_London_Borough_of_Barnet"}
{"title_page": "Fatland (Audubon, Pennsylvania)", "text_new": "{{Infobox building\n| name                = \"Fatland\"\n| image               = Fatlands II MontCo PA Planning 713d5b o.jpg\n| image_size          = 300px\n| architectural_style = [[Greek Revival architecture|Greek Revival]]\n| classification      = \n| location            = \n| address             = 1248 Pawlings Road\n| location_town       = Audubon, Pennsylvania\n| location_country    = \n| coordinates = {{coord|40|07|09|N|75|26|35|W|display=inline,title}}\n| start_date          = 1843\n| stop_date           = \n| est_completion      = \n| topped_out_date     = \n| completion_date     = 1845\n| opened_date         = \n| inauguration_date   = \n| relocated_date      = \n| renovation_date     = 1990s\n| closing_date        = \n| material            = stuccoed brick & stone<br>wooden square columns<br> marble Ionic columns\n| grounds_area        = \n| architect           = [[John Haviland]]\n| architecture_firm   = \n| main_contractor     = \n| rooms               = <!-- or | unit_count          = -->\n| parking             =  \n| website             = \n| embed               = \n| embedded            = \n| references          = \n| footnotes           = \n}}\n'''Fatland (Audubon, Pennsylvania)''' &ndash; also known as \"Fatland Farm,\" \"Fatland Ford\" and, currently, \"Vaux Hill\" &ndash; is a Greek Revival mansion and estate in [[Audubon, Pennsylvania]]. Located on the north side of the [[Schuylkill River]], opposite [[Valley Forge, Pennsylvania|Valley Forge]], the property was part of the [[Valley Forge|Continental Army's 1777-78 winter encampment]]. On consecutive days in September 1777, its stone farmhouse served as headquarters for General [[George Washington]] and British General Sir [[William Howe, 5th Viscount Howe|William Howe]]. \n\nThe farmhouse was demolished about 1843, and the mansion was built on its site about 1845. The Wetherill Family owned the property for 121 years&mdash;1825 to 1946. A private cemetery contains the graves of some of Fatland's owners, and of [[Free Quakers]] who supported the Revolutionary War.\n\n==Fatland Farm==\nThe [[Perkiomen Creek]] empties in to the Schuylkill River just north of Valley Forge. The river curves in an [[Meander|oxbow]] and forms a peninsula with the creek. Early settlers called the area the \"Fatlands of Egypt\" because of its frequent flooding and rich [[alluvial]] soil.<ref>Thaddeus Vanderslice, ''Henry Pawling, a British Soldier and Some of His Descendants'' (Philadelphia: privately printed, 1904).</ref>\n\nJames Morgan dammed the creek and built a grist mill and miller's house on the north side of the Perkiomen Peninsula in 1749.<ref name=\"Herrick\"/>{{rp|104}} He built the country seat \"Mill Grove\" in 1762.<ref name=\"Herrick\"/>{{rp|104}} In a February 28, 1771 advertisement in ''The Pennsylvania Gazette'', he announced the upcoming auction of two adjacent properties, Fatland Farm and Mill Grove Farm:<blockquote>To be sold at public venue on the 4th day of March, upon the premises, if not sold before at private sale, by the subscriber, in Providence township, Philadelphia county, two valuable plantations, one of which consisting of 300 acres (Fatland farm), bounding near a mile on the Schuylkill river, whereas a good shad fishery; it also bounds the lands of Henry Pawling, Esq., and extends along the same to the Perkiomen; there are about 150 acres cleared, 20 whereof are good watered meadow and a great quantity more may be made; the woodland well timbered and the whole well watered, with the conveniency of watering every field on the plantation; there is a good stone dwelling house, brew house, with a large frame barn, three good bearing apple orchards, with a large peach orchard bearing plentifully. The other contains 250 acres [Mill Grove Farm] ...\"<ref name=\"MCHS\">Dr. W. H. Reed, \"Audubon. Its History, Tradition and Reminiscences,\" ''Historical Sketches: A Collection of Papers Prepared for the Historical Society of Montgomery County, Pennsylvania, Volume 4'', (Montgomery County Historical Society, 1909), pp. 173-224.</ref>{{rp|180-81}}</blockquote> \nThis auction took place, but neither property sold.<ref name=\"MCHS\"/>{{rp|181}} Instead, James Vaux (1748&ndash;1842) purchased Fatland Farm by private sale more than a year later, on June 18, 1772.<ref name=\"MCHS\"/>{{rp|181}}\n\n==Vaux Hill==\n[[File:Valley Forge Station circa 1910.jpg|thumb|Schuylkill River at Valley Forge, looking east, circa 1910. Fatland Island and Fatland Ford are in the background, center.]]\nVaux renamed the property \"Vaux Hill.\" The 300-acre (121.4 hectares) farm spanned the middle of the peninsula.<ref name=\"Vaux Papers\">[http://www2.hsp.org/collections/manuscripts/v/vaux684.htm Abstract - Vaux Family Papers], from Historical Society of Pennsylvania.</ref> Part of its western boundary, shared with Henry Pawling's farm, was the road south to Fatland Ford, a shallow crossing of the Schuylkill River, opposite Valley Forge.<ref name=\"VAFO, p.43\">National Park Service, ''Cultural Landscapes Inventory&mdash;Valley Forge National Historical Park'', 1999.[https://irma.nps.gov/DataStore/DownloadFile/454295 (PDF)]</ref> \n\nVaux was an English farmer and [[Society of Friends|Quaker]], who emigrated to Pennsylvania in 1771.<ref name=\"JFHS\">''Journal of the Friends' Historical Society, Volume 6'', (London: Friends' Historical Society, 1909), p. 186.[https://books.google.com/books?id=t5M5AQAAMAAJ&pg=PA186&lpg=PA186&dq=susanna+warder+vaux&source=bl&ots=XU8z9EeLrb&sig=x6YVeLHj-KLdJn3gaoJN4L6YVbQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiIvN6ug__UAhUIrD4KHcIjDAQQ6AEIKDAB#v=onepage&q=susanna%20warder%20vaux&f=false]</ref> He expanded the existing stone farmhouse in 1776,<ref name=\"MCHS\"/>{{rp|200}} and constructed its stone barn.<ref>[https://www.loc.gov/pictures/collection/hh/item/pa0904/ Vaux-Wetherill Stone Barn,] from HABS.</ref> The following year he married Susanna Warder (1749&ndash;1812) of Philadelphia, also a Quaker.<ref name=\"JFHS\"/>\n\nVaux took no side in the [[American Revolutionary War|Revolutionary War]]. On September 21, 1777, General [[George Washington]], accompanied by a detachment of [[Commander-in-Chief's Guard|his life guard]] and [[Washington's Aides-de-Camp|aide-de-camp]] [[Tench Tilghman]], [[Surveillance|surveilled]] British troops at Valley Forge from the north side of the river.<ref name=\"MCHS\"/>{{rp|201}} The river was swollen, which prevented the British from crossing. At Washington's direction, his aide urgently wrote to General [[Alexander McDougall]]&mdash;\"... the River has fallen and is fordable at almost any place, the Enemy can have no Reason to delay passing much longer. He would have wrote {{sic}} you personally, but is employed in viewing the ground and making disposition of the Army which arrived yesterday.\"<ref>[https://founders.archives.gov/documents/Washington/03-11-02-0302#GEWN-03-11-02-0302-fn-0002 Tench Tilghman for Gen. George Washington to Gen. Alexander McDougall, 21 Sept. 1777 (See note 2),] from National Archives.</ref> Vaux invited Washington to dine and stay the night&mdash;the life guard secured Fatland Ford overnight.<ref name=\"MCHS\"/>{{rp|201}} Washington and his troops departed early the following morning. \n\nThat same morning, British Captain John Montroser recorded in his journal: \"[September] 22nd. &mdash; At 5 this morning ... the Light Infantry and Grenadiers passed over the Schuylkill at Fatland Ford without a single shot and took post.\"<ref name=\"MCHS\"/>{{rp|185}} Early that evening, General Howe crossed the ford and made Vaux Hill his headquarters. Vaux dined with Howe, who asked about the rebel officer who had been spotted the previous day. When informed that it had been Washington himself, Howe reportedly replied: \"Oh, I wish I had known that. I would have tried to catch him!\"<ref name=\"Eberlein\"/>{{rp|412}} The opposing commanders-in-chief probably slept in the same bed on consecutive nights.<ref name=\"Eberlein & Lippincott\">Harold Donaldson Eberlein and Horace Mather Lippincott, ''Colonial Homes of Philadelphia and Its Neighbourhood'', (Philadelphia: J. B. Lippincott Company, 1912).</ref>{{rp|192-93}} As Howe slept, the British Army began a night crossing from Valley Forge. Montroser: \"[September] 23rd. &mdash; Just after 12 o'clock this night the whole army moved to the opposite side, on the north side of the river Schuylkill by the way of Fatland Ford, and by 10 a. m. the whole baggage and all had happily passed it. After the principal body had got on the north side of the Schuylkill about one mile the army halted to dry themselves and rest.\"<ref name=\"MCHS\"/>{{rp|185}}\n[[File:Valley Forge Park Burt 1920 inset.jpg|thumb|230px|left|''Valley Forge Park and Vicinity'' (1908). \"Old Fatland Ford\" is marked at the center top.]]\nGeneral Washington and the Continental Army returned to the area in December 1777 for the six month [[Valley Forge]] encampment. The majority of troops encamped south of the river, but Vaux's farm was the site of troop encampments and support facilities.<ref name=\"VAFO, p.43\"/> General [[John Sullivan (general)|John Sullivan]] supervised construction of a [[Pontoon bridge|floating-log bridge]] slightly downstream from Fatland Ford.<ref name=\"VAFO, p.43\"/> This bridge provided a river crossing in times of [[flood|high water]], and an escape route in the event of a British attack.<ref name=\"VAFO, p.43\"/> The floating bridge was destroyed by ice in 1779.<ref name=\"VAFO, p.43\"/>\n<blockquote>The British army, in September, 1777, passed from Valley Forge to the left bank of the Schuylkill by the Fatland Ford; not many months later [June 19, 1778], when the American forces evacuated Valley Forge, they crossed at the same place, as just mentioned. Both armies swarmed over the Vaux Hill plantation like devastating clouds of locusts. Tearing down fences, destroying trees and doing thousands of pounds' worth of damage in various ways, they wrought such havoc that Mr. Vaux's estate was seriously embarrassed in consequence.<ref name=\"Eberlein\"/>{{rp|410-11}}</blockquote>\nThe Commonwealth of Pennsylvania paid Vaux \u00a31,000 in compensation for damage done to his property during the war.<ref name=\"MCHS\"/>{{rp|202}} \"In the 1785 assessment of Providence township, James Vaux is recorded as a farmer, owning a farm of 300 acres of land, dwelling, four horses, six cows, one servant (colored), and one riding chair.\"<ref name=\"MCHS\"/>{{rp|206}} He later served in the [[Pennsylvania Legislature]].<ref name=\"Eberlein\"/>{{rp|412}} Vaux sold Vaux Hill to John Echline Allen, about 1794.<ref name=\"Vaux Papers\"/>\n\nThere are no known images of the \"good stone dwelling house\" described in 1771, or of the house as expanded by Vaux.<ref name=\"Eberlein\">Harold Donaldson Eberlein, ''Portrait of a Colonial City: Philadelphia 1670&ndash;1838'', (Philadelphia: J. B. Lippincott Company, 1939).</ref>{{rp|410}}\n\n==Fatland Ford==\n[[File:Bakewells, MCHS, 1910, opp. p.206.jpg|thumb|210px|William and Lucy Green Bakewell]]\nBy 1803, the farm was owned by James S. Ewing, who advertised it for sale in September. He listed its buildings: \"... a dwelling-house 45x35 feet, built of stone, ... Smith's house and Shop, Ice house, spring house, poultry house, smoke house, large stone barn with stables for 40 head of horses and cows ...\"<ref>''The Norristown Newspaper'', September 22, 1803, quoted in Stark, p. 113.</ref> \n\nEwing sold the property to Englishman William Woodhouse Bakewell (1759&ndash;1821) who, with his wife, 4 daughters and 2 sons,<ref name=\"MCHS\"/>{{rp|209}} occupied it in January 1804.<ref name=\"Herrick\"/>{{rp|99, n.1}} Bakewell's wife, Lucy Green Bakewell (1765&ndash;1804), died during their first year living there. Their eldest daughter, also named Lucy (1787&ndash;1874), took on the duties of hostess. \n\nBakewell renamed the property \"Fatland Ford,\"<ref>''The Norristown Newspaper'', September 8, 1813, quoted in Stark, p. 113.</ref> and operated it as a [[gentleman's farm]]. Robert Sutcliff, a relative of Bakewell's estate manager, visited in August 1804:<blockquote>This plantation, consists of 300 acres of good land, 200 of which are cleared, and 100 covered with wood. On the estate is a well finished square stone house, about 15 yards [13.7 m] in length, with a wide boarded floor piazza, both in back and front. These afford excellent accommodation during the summer season ... Besides the dwelling house, there is an excellent kitchen, and offices adjoining; with a large barn, and stables sufficient to accommodate 40 horses and cows; all well built of stone. The estate extends the whole breadth betwixt the Schuylkill and Perkiomen. On the former river there is a [[Shad]] Fishery which is of considerable value ... This estate, with all its appendages, cost about ''3600\u00a3'' sterling, which is but ''12\u00a3'' per acre, the buildings included. The house is so situated that it commands one of the finest prospects in Pennsylvania, and, being on a rising ground, is dry and healthy. The whole together forms one of the most beautiful spots I have seen in the United States.<ref name=\"Sutcliff\">Robert Sutcliff, ''Travels in Some Parts of North America, in the Years 1804, 1805 & 1806'',  (York, England: printed by C. Peacock, 1811).</ref>{{rp|30-31}}</blockquote>\n\n===Audubon===\n[[File:Mill Grove Mansion.jpg|thumb|Mill Grove, in 2012.]]\nSutcliff also visited [[Mill Grove]], then owned by Jean Audubon, a retired French sea captain living in [[Nantes, France]].<ref name=\"Arthur\">Stanley Clisby Arthur, ''Audubon: An Intimate Life of the American Woodsman'', (Gretna, Louisiana: Pelican Publishing, 1937).</ref>{{rp|478}} [[Lead]] deposits had been discovered on the farm, and Captain Audubon formed a partnership with French businessman Francis Dacosta to mine the ore.<ref name=\"Arthur\"/>{{rp|37-38}} Sutcliff wrote: \"In the plantation adjoining to my relation's, we visited a lead mine on the banks of the Perkiomin {{sic}}, which was then worked by a Frenchman. He invited us to go down into it, where, at the depth of about 12 feet, I saw a vein of lead ore 18 inches in thickness; and as it is wrought at a very easy expense, there was a great probability of its being a very valuable acquisition.\"<ref name=\"Sutcliff\"/>{{rp|34}} \n\nThe \"Frenchman\" Sutcliff met may have been Dacosta, or it may have been the captain's 19-year-old son (and future naturalist) [[John James Audubon]]&mdash;they had arrived in America together the year before.<ref name=\"Herrick\"/>{{rp|xxv}} Audubon and 17-year-old [[Lucy Bakewell Audubon|Lucy Bakewell]] fell in love, although her father thought both of them too young to marry.<ref name=\"Arthur\"/>{{rp|37-38}} Informed by letter of his son's intentions, Captain Audubon initially opposed the marriage.<ref name=\"Arthur\"/>{{rp|40}} With money borrowed from the Bakewells, Audubon sailed for France in January 1805 to sort out what to do about Mill Grove and the lead mine, and to obtain his father's permission to marry.<ref name=\"Arthur\"/>{{rp|39}} He returned to the United States in May 1806 having attained his majority and his father's blessing.<ref name=\"Arthur\"/>{{rp|46-47}} Bakewell also consented to the engagement. Audubon sold Mill Grove and his father's interest in the lead mine to Dacosta in September 1806,<ref name=\"Herrick\"/>{{rp|xxvi}} and moved to New York City to work as a clerk in the [[counting house]] of Bakewell's brother.<ref name=\"Herrick\"/>{{rp|xxvi}} In August 1807, he and a partner opened a pioneer store in Louisville, Kentucky.<ref name=\"Herrick\"/>{{rp|xxvii}} On April 8, 1808, John James Audubon and Lucy Bakewell were married at \"Fatland Ford.\"<ref name=\"Journals\">John James Audubon, ''Audubon and His Journals'', edited by Maria R. Audubon, (New York: Charles Scribner's Sons, 1899).</ref>{{rp|28}} The next morning, the newlyweds departed for Louisville, where Audubon continued his short-lived career as a merchant.<ref name=\"Journals\"/>{{rp|28-29}}\n\nWhen Bakewell advertised Fatland Ford for sale in 1813, he listed \"a [steam] threshing-mill, which threshes 12 bushels of barley in an hour,\" and livestock of \"200 Sheep of the English Morena breeds, span of oxen and other cattle, 4 asses, 7 horses, ... 30 pigs of the English Berkshire breed.\"<ref>''The Norristown Newspaper'', August 7, 1813, quoted in John T. Faris, ''Old Roads Out of Philadelphia'', (Philadelphia and London: J. B. Lippincott Company, 1917), p. 198.[https://archive.org/stream/oldroadsoutphil01farigoog#page/n264/mode/2up/search/Wetherill]</ref> The sale was not successful; Bakewell was still the owner of the property when he died there in 1821.<ref name=\"Woodman\">Henry Woodman, ''The History of Valley Forge'', (Oaks, PA: John U. Francis, Sr., 1922)</ref>{{rp|110}}\n\nLucy Green Bakewell had been buried at \"Fatland Ford\" in 1804.<ref name=\"MCHS\"/>{{rp|208}} Bakewell remarried, and was initially buried in Philadelphia.<ref name=\"MCHS\"/>{{rp|208-09}} His descendants later had him reinterred beside his first wife.<ref>[https://www.findagrave.com/cgi-bin/fg.cgi?page=gr&GScid=46619&GRid=38635090& William Woodhouse Bakewell,] from Find-A-Grave.</ref>\n\n==Fatland==\n[[File:Fatland Faris Old Roads 1917 opp. p.192.jpg|thumb|left|\"Fatland,\" from the northwest, in 1917.]]\n[[File:Audubon and his journals (1897) (14752067971).jpg|thumb|left|\"Fatland,\" from the south, in the 1890s.]]\nDacosta's lead mine initially was unprofitable, with costs too great to compete with imported lead from England.<ref name=\"Herrick\">Francis Hobart Herrick, ''Audubon the Naturalist: A History of His Life and Time, Volume 1'', (New York and London: D. Appleton and Company, 1917).</ref>{{rp|115}} The [[War of 1812]] caused imports to be cut off, and the price of lead in the United States to soar.<ref name=\"PCP\">''The First Century of the Philadelphia College of Pharmacy, 1821-1921'', (Philadelphia College of Pharmacy and Science, 1922).</ref>{{rp|38}} Samuel Wetherill, Jr., a Philadelphia white lead importer and paint manufacturer, purchased Mill Grove for $7,000 in 1813.<ref name=\"Herrick\"/>{{rp|169}} Wetherill & Son reopened the mine, and \"mined and smelted over 100 tons from small veins on Perkiomen Creek in Montgomery County, Pa., on Mill Grove farm.\"<ref name=\"PCP\"/>{{rp|36}} The depleted mine was closed again in the 1820s.<ref name=\"Woodman\"/>{{rp|108}} \n\nSamuel Wetherill 3rd (1764&ndash;1829) purchased \"Fatland Ford\" in 1825, and changed its name to just \"Fatland.\" He had been his father's partner, and inherited the family business. He and his wife, Rachel Price (1766&ndash;1844), had 5 sons and a daughter.<ref name=\"Jordan\"/>{{rp|996}} Wetherill inherited Mill Grove, bought up farms owned by the Bakewells and the Pawlings, and became the great landowner of the peninsula.<ref name=\"VAFO, p.43\"/>{{rp|46}} He subsequently bequeathed the properties to his children and grandchildren.<ref>Stark, p. 3.</ref> \"These properties were improved with stately mansions and outbuildings with beautiful lawns and surroundings. (Also erected were summer residences on some of the properties.)\"<ref name=\"VAFO, p.43\"/>{{rp|46}} \n\nDr. William Wetherill (1804&ndash;1872), inherited Fatland.<ref name=\"Eberlein & Lippincott\"/>{{rp|196}} He was a Philadelphia physician, and partner &ndash; with his brother John, who inherited Mill Grove &ndash; in the Wetherill White Lead Works.<ref name=\"Jordan\"/>{{rp|1004}} He and his wife Isabella Macomb (1807&ndash;1871) had 16 children, 12 of whom lived to adulthood.<ref name=\"Jordan\"/>{{rp|1004}} Dr. Wetherill demolished Fatland's stone farmhouse, about 1843, and replaced it with a [[Greek Revival architecture|Greek Revival]] mansion built upon the farmhouse's foundations.<ref name=\"Eberlein & Lippincott\"/>{{rp|196-97}}<ref>Linda Stein, [http://www.mainlinemedianews.com/mainlinesuburbanlife/life/fabulous-antiques-from-vaux-hill-to-be-auctioned/article_b5b19e72-5313-53e8-93e9-81c4555a2ccb.html \"Fabulous antiques from Vaux Hill to be auctioned,\"] ''Main Line Suburban Life'', September 18, 2013.</ref> \n\nPossibly inspired by [[Andalusia (estate)|\"Andalusia\"]] (1834-36), [[Nicholas Biddle (banker)|Nicholas Biddle]]'s great Greek Revival mansion overlooking the [[Delaware River]], architect [[John Haviland]] designed a \"western counterpart\" for Dr. Wetherill, \"Fatland Hall,\" overlooking the Schuylkill River.<ref name=\"Thomas\">George E. Thomas, ''Buildings of Pennsylvania &ndash; Philadelphia and Eastern Pennsylvania'', (Charlottesville and London: University of Virginia Press, 2010), p. 201.</ref> The size and arrangement of the mansion's [[Central-passage house|center hall]] and formal rooms were similar to James Vaux's expanded farmhouse,<ref name=\"Eberlein\"/> but with much higher ceilings: \"Fatland is special for the scale of the portico and its juxtaposed miniature service wing.\"<ref name=\"Thomas\"/> The overall composition was asymmetrical,<ref name=\"Eberlein\"/> the first floor of the single wing (to the east) consisted of the formal dining room, and pantries and the family dining room in the [[Pavilion|end pavilion]]. The kitchen was in the basement below, and servant rooms were above.<ref name=\"Eberlein\"/> The end pavilion featured painted-wood-columned [[portico]]es on the front and rear facades.<ref name=\"Eberlein\"/> The great [[Ionic column]]s of the main block's porticoes were of white marble.<ref name=\"Eberlein\"/> The mansion was completed about 1845.<ref name=\"Eberlein\"/> A stone tablet in its south gable reads: \"J. Vaux, 1776; rebuilt by William Wetherill, 1843.\"<ref name=\"MCHS\"/>{{rp|200}} \"[[Bayard Taylor]], the historian and traveler, claimed [the view from the piazza] was the most beautiful view along the beautiful Schuylkill river.\"<ref name=\"Jordan\"/>{{rp|1006}}\n\nFatland was inherited by Dr. Wetherill's son, Col. John Macomb Wetherill (1828&ndash;1895), a [[American Civil War|Civil War]] veteran who managed the family's Pennsylvania coal lands, and never married.<ref name=\"Jordan\">John Woolf Jordan, ''Colonial Families of Philadelphia, Volume 2'', (Lewis Publishing Company, 1911).[https://books.google.com/books?id=3kc2AQAAMAAJ&pg=PA1004&dq=john+macomb+wetherill&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj5oYPQnPvUAhUFGj4KHXJUBVMQ6AEIKDAB#v=onepage&q=john%20macomb%20wetherill&f=false]</ref>{{rp|1004}} He gave permission for William Bakewell's remains to be reinterred at Fatland,<ref name=\"MCHS\"/>{{rp|209}} and directed that he himself be buried there.<ref name=\"Journals\"/>{{rp|43, n.3}} In his will, Col. Wetherill deeded the private cemetery to a trust, directed that it be expanded and improved, and established an endowment for its maintenance.<ref name=\"Journals\"/>{{rp|43, n.3}} \n\nOwnership of Fatland passed to the colonel's younger brother, William H. Wetherill, Jr. (1838&ndash;1927) and wife Elizabeth Proctor (1842&ndash;1914), under whom the property was \"greatly beautified.\"<ref name=\"Jordan\"/>{{rp|1006}} He carried out the improvements to the private cemetery, and had Wetherill ancestors and others reburied there.\n \nDr. Henry Emerson Wetherill (1871&ndash;1946), the eldest son of William H. and a U.S. Army surgeon and inventor, inherited Fatland in 1927. He had been a member of [[Robert Peary]]'s 1893-94 [[Greenland]] expedition, on which he collected plant specimens.<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/pearyauxiliaryex00brya#page/70/mode/2up \"List of Plants Obtained on the Peary Auxiliary Expedition of 1894,\"]</ref>  He also delivered [[Josephine Diebitsch Peary|Mrs. Peary]]'s daughter Marie, whom the popular press dubbed the \"Snow Baby.\"<ref>\"Dr. H. E. Wetherill, Peary Arctic Aide, Delivered Child to Admiral's Wife on 1893 Expedition &ndash; Surgeon, Inventor Dies,\" ''The New York Times'', March 9, 1946.</ref> An inveterate tinkerer, his diagnostic medical devices were awarded the 1906 Longstreth Medal by the [[Franklin Institute]].<ref>[https://www.fi.edu/laureates/henry-emerson-wetherill Henry Emerson Wetherill,] from The Franklin Institute.</ref> He also invented navigational instruments for ships,<ref>Henry Emerson Wetherill, \"New Aids for Navigation,\" ''Journal of the Franklin Institute'', September 1908.</ref> and a musical instrument called a [[Slide whistle|trombone flute]].<ref>[http://memory.loc.gov/diglib/ihas/loc.music.dcmphot.a0493/default.html \"Dr. Henry Emerson Wetherill (photograph),] from Library of Congress.</ref> Dr. Wetherill never married, and was buried in the private cemetery. He was the last Wetherill to own Fatland.\n\n===Free Quaker - Wetherill Cemetery===\n[[File:Free Quaker - Wetherill Cemetery.jpg|thumb|Free Quaker - Wetherill Cemetery, in 2017.]]\nSamuel Wetherill, Jr. provided supplies to the Continental Army at Valley Forge, and was \"read out of meeting\" (disowned) by the [[Society of Friends]] in 1779, after refusing to renounce those actions.<ref name=\"Wetherill\">Charles Wetherill, ''History of The Religious Society of Friends, Called by Some The Free Quakers, in the City of Philadelphia'', (Philadelphia: privately printed, 1894).</ref> Defying the [[pacifism]] of their religion, \"[[Free Quakers]]\" supported or fought in the Revolutionary War. Wetherill became a founder of Philadelphia's Free Quaker Meeting (chartered February 20, 1781),<ref name=\"Wetherill\"/> and served as its clerk and preacher.<ref name=\"Wetherill\"/> With brother-in-law Timothy Matlack, another charter member, he designed its [[Free Quaker Meetinghouse|meeting house]] (1783-84), at 5th and Arch Streets.<ref name=\"Peterson\">Charles E. Peterson, ''Notes on the Free Quaker Meeting House'', (Washington, D.C.: Ross & Perry, 2002).</ref> The meeting established its own burying ground, on the east side of 5th Street between Locust and Spruce Streets.<ref name=\"Ault\">Walter Ault, \"The Fighting Quakers Cemetery,\" ''The Times Herald'', September 14, 2009.[http://www.timesherald.com/article/JR/20090914/NEWS01/309149996]</ref> Membership dwindled as the Free Quakers died off, and their meeting house was closed in 1836.<ref name=\"Peterson\"/> As the turn of the 20th century approached, the Free Quaker Burying Ground plot became attractive for commercial development.<ref name=\"Ault\"/> It was in anticipation of its sale that Col. John Macomb Wetherill (Samuel Wetherill, Jr.'s great-grandson) directed in his 1895 will that the private cemetery at Fatland be expanded.<ref name=\"Ault\"/> \n\nIn 1905, remains from sixty-one graves were removed from the Free Quaker Burying Ground and reinterred at Fatland.<ref name=\"Ault\"/> Included were those of Samuel Wetherill, Jr. and his wife and relatives, including [[Timothy Matlack]],<ref>[https://www.findagrave.com/cgi-bin/fg.cgi?page=gr&GRid=16365624 Timothy Matlack,] from Find-A-Grave.</ref> scribe of the [[Second Continental Congress]]&mdash;whose [[penmanship]] can be seen in the [[United States Declaration of Independence|Declaration of Independence]]. Many of the tombstones had severely eroded, and were illegible or identifiable only by initials. The remains of [[Ira Allen]], one of Vermont's [[Green Mountain Boys]], had been lost with the closing of another Philadelphia cemetery, and his [[cenotaph]] also was moved to Fatland.<ref>[https://www.findagrave.com/cgi-bin/fg.cgi?page=gr&GRid=38633277 Ira Allen,] from Find-A-Grave.</ref>\n\nNumerous Wetherill family members have been and continue to be buried in the private cemetery.<ref>[https://www.findagrave.com/cgi-bin/fg.cgi?page=gsr&GScid=46619 Wetherill Cemetery - Interments,] from Find-A-Grave.</ref>\n\n===Saint Gabriel's Hall===\n[[File:St. Gabriel's Hall from Rte. 422.jpg|thumb|Saint Gabriel's Hall from the Pottstown Expressway, in 2017.]]\nOn November 19, 1895, the [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Philadelphia]] purchased a 185-acre tract of land adjacent to Fatland, to the west.<ref name=\"Kirlin\">Joseph Louis J. Kirlin, ''Catholicity in Philadelphia: From the Earliest Missionaries down to the Present Time'', (Philadelphia: J. J. McVey, 1909), pp. 411-13.[https://books.google.com/books?id=YfTPAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA412&lpg=PA412&dq=%22protectory+station%22+Fatland&source=bl&ots=6bgQZ5u9JQ&sig=9XbRZoxhuvG9XiroGmWSDfTEdqA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj9tvH4vonVAhUCQz4KHYgmBFwQ6AEINzAE#v=onepage&q=%22protectory%20station%22%20Fatland&f=false]</ref>{{rp|412}} Formerly part of Henry Pawling's farm, there the Archdiocese built the Philadelphia Protectory for Boys, an orphanage staffed by the [[De La Salle Brothers|Christian Brothers]]. Architects [[Wilson Brothers & Company]] designed its [[Italianate architecture|Italianate]] orange-brick-and-red-tile-roofed building, which included a tall [[campanile]], or belltower.<ref>[https://www.philadelphiabuildings.org/pab/app/pj_display_allarchitects.cfm/54258 Roman Catholic Protectory,] from Philadelphia Architects and Buildings.</ref> Archbishop [[Patrick John Ryan]] dedicated the building on May 8, 1898, with more than 3,000 in attendance.<ref name=\"Kirlin\"/>{{rp|412}} Its initial capacity was for housing 200 boys, but the capacity increased to 500 boys with additions that opened in September 1905.<ref name=\"Kirlin\"/>{{rp|412}} An additional 100 acres were purchased in 1902, which extended the property to the Schuylkill River and included Fatland Island (part of Fatland Ford).<ref name=\"Kirlin\"/>{{rp|412}} The name of the [[Reading Company|Reading Railroad]] passenger station opposite the west end of the peninsula was changed to Protectory Station, by 1898.<ref name=\"Kirlin\"/>{{rp|412}} The protectory was renamed Saint Gabriel's Hall in 1962.<ref name=\"St. Gabe's\">[http://st-gabes.org/residential/saint-gabriels-hall History,] from Saint Gabriel's Hall.</ref> \n\nOperated by the Catholic Social Services of the Archdiocese of Philadelphia, \"St. Gabe's\" is now a [[juvenile detention]] facility.<ref name=\"St. Gabe's\"/> Its border with Fatland follows the old path of Fatland Ford Road.<ref name=\"VAFO, p.43\"/>{{rp|73}}\n\n===Camiel===\n[[File:NPS valley-forge-map.pdf|thumb|left|U.S. Rte. 422 / Pottstown Expressway (bottom right to top) makes two major curves.]]\n[[File:St. Gabe's Curve from Pawlings Road Bridge.jpg|thumb|left|\"St. Gabe's Curve.\" U.S. Rte. 422 / Pottstown Expressway, from Pawlings Road, in 2017.]]\nAntiquarian Harold Donaldson Eberlein wrote about Fatland in 1912.<ref name=\"Eberlein & Lippincott\"/> By the time he revisited the estate in 1939, the landscape had changed: \"So closely is the house screened by great ancient trees that only in winter can you catch a glimpse from a distance of its stately white porticoes gleaming through the interlacing branches.\"<ref name=\"Eberlein\"/>{{rp|409}} Dr. Henry Emerson Wetherill died at Fatland in 1946. Later that year the property was purchased by the Philadelphia Democratic politician [[Peter Camiel|Peter J. Camiel]] (1910&ndash;1991) and his wife Nina (1913&ndash;2007). \n\nCamiel was one of 12 children of [[Poles|Polish]] [[Jewish]] immigrants, a former boxer, longshoreman and union organizer.<ref name=\"PA Senate\">\"Senate Resolution [memorializing the late Peter J. Camiel],\" ''Pennsylvania Legislative Journal&mdash;Senate'', February 5, 1991, pp. 116-119.[http://www.legis.state.pa.us/WU01/LI/SJ/1991/0/Sj19910205.pdf (PDF)]</ref> He made himself a millionaire as a wholesale beer distributor.<ref name=\"NYT obit\"/> Camiel served as a [[Pennsylvania State Senator]] from 1953 to 1964, and as chairman of the Philadelphia Democratic City Committee from 1970 to 1976.<ref name=\"NYT obit\">[https://www.nytimes.com/1991/02/02/obituaries/peter-j-camiel-81-philadelphia-chief-of-70-s-democrats.html \"Peter J. Camiel, 81, Philadelphia Chief of '70s Democrats,\"] ''The New York Times'', February 2, 1991.</ref> He was appointed one of five commissioners to the powerful [[Pennsylvania Turnpike Commission]] in 1975, serving on it until his death.<ref name=\"PA Senate\"/>{{efn|Technically, Camiel was suspended from the Turnpike Commission in May 1980, after federal charges were filed against him for [[Malfeasance in office|corruption]]. He was found guilty &ndash; United States v. Camiel, 689 F.2d 31 (3d Cir. 1982) &ndash; but the verdict was reversed on appeal. He returned to the commission in 1983.<ref>Tom Fontaine, \"Thornburgh: Let PennDOT run the Pennsylvania Turnpike,\" ''The Pittsburgh Tribune'', March 31, 2013.</ref>}}\n\nState Senator [[Vince Fumo]]: \"Pete was a pilot. I used to listen for hours in amazement, when he would tell the stories about how he found Fatland Farm, flying over it in a plane, hidden behind so many trees. He bought it and pulled all those trees out and made it into a showcase right next to Valley Forge Park.\"<ref name=\"PA Senate\"/>{{rp|119}} The Camiels spent several years renovating the mansion, rehabilitating the overgrown estate, and returning it to being a working farm.<ref name=\"VAFO, p.43\"/>{{rp|56}} About 1950, they sold off a section on the south side of Pawlings Road, between the mansion and Saint Gabriel's Hall, for a housing development.<ref name=\"VAFO, p.43\"/>{{rp|34}}\n\n====Pottstown Expressway====\nIn 1951, folowing 138 years of family ownership, Herbert Johnson Wetherill sold [[Mill Grove]] to [[Montgomery County, Pennsylvania|Montgomery County]] to create a [[bird sanctuary]] and [[house museum]] honoring John James Audubon. Twenty-five years later, it was announced that the planned route for the [[U.S. Route 422|Pottstown Expressway]] was to go through the Audubon property. Camiel was credited with / blamed for applying political pressure to reroute the superhighway around the bird sanctuary:\n\n<blockquote>Central to the arguments concerning politicians appears to be the controversial \"Camiel Loop.\" [Montgomery County Planning Commission associate director] Plutte said that the cost of rerouting the Pottstown Expressway around the home of Peter J. Camiel caused the price of the highway to jump from $5 million to $8 million, and most recently to more than $10 million in the past six months. As the highway leaves the connection with Betzwood Bridge and aims northwest toward Pottstown, it veers sharply south [''sic'' west], down and around Camiel's farm, \"Fatland.\" The parabolic dip in the road mean several miles of additional roadway, roadway that Pottstown was denied. Plutte said the Camiel loop was installed to avert a \"potential challenge\" arising out of an environmental study. Camiel's farm is near the Audubon Sanctuary, which according to original plans, would have had to surrender land to the highway crews. Federal funds, which pay for 70 per cent of the Pottstown Expressway, could be jeopardized by the taking of the park land, Plutte said.<ref>William G. Reinecke, \"Pottstown expressway link blocked; Construction may start in 1989,\" ''The Pottstown Mercury'', September 23, 1976, p. 1.</ref></blockquote>\n\nWhether Camiel acted from selfish or selfless motives (or a combination of both), the rerouting of the Pottstown Expressway spared Mill Grove &ndash; now a [[National Historic Landmark]] &ndash; and minimized the adverse effect on Fatland. The Camiels owned the property for 44 years, and were buried together in its private cemetery.<ref>[https://www.findagrave.com/cgi-bin/fg.cgi?page=gr&GRid=118909314 Peter J. Camiel,] from Find-A-Grave.</ref><ref>[https://www.findagrave.com/cgi-bin/fg.cgi?page=gr&GRid=118909353 Nina Gumen Camiel,] from Find-A-Grave.</ref>\n\n==Vaux Hill (2)==\n{{external media | width = 220px | align = right | headerimage = [[File:Fatlands Mansion MontCo PA Planning 4a909 o.jpg|220px]] | video1 = [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xOYg61xGPqs Selected Contents of Vaux Hill]<ref name=\"Freeman's\">{{cite web | title = Selected Contents of Vaux Hill | work = | publisher =Freeman's Auctions on YouTube | date = 2013 | url =https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xOYg61xGPqs | accessdate =July 17, 2017 }}</ref> | video2 = [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YJs6uxho03k Vaux Hill]<ref name=\"Vaux Hill\">{{cite web|title=1248 Pawlings Road Phoenixville, PA 19460| date = 2015 | url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YJs6uxho03k |publisher=Kurfiss Sotheby's International Realty on YouTube |accessdate=July 17, 2017}}</ref> }}\nCamiel's land sales dramatically reduced Fatland's acreage&mdash;his housing development, land for the Pottstown Expressway, and his 1979 sale of 154 acres (62.3 hectare) between the expressway and the Schyulkill River to [[Valley Forge National Historical Park]].<ref>Editorial: \"Protecting Valley Forge,\" ''The Philadelphia Inquirer'', November 20, 1979.</ref> On July 16, 1990, Robert Owen Safford (1934&ndash;2011) and his wife Barbara Harvey (b. 1947) purchased the mansion on 18 acres from Camiel for $2.1 million.<ref name=\"Zillow\"/> The couple changed the name of the property back to \"Vaux Hill,\" the name James Vaux had given it in 1772.<ref name=\"Iames\">David Iames, \"The Vaux Hill Sale,\" ''Antiques & Auction News'', October 8, 2013.[https://www.antiquesandauctionnews.net/article_print.lasso?-a=The-Vaux-Hill-Sale]</ref> \n\nThe Saffords expanded the mansion, erecting a west wing and end pavilion that mirrored the east wing and end pavilion&mdash;thus creating an overall symmetrical building (for the first time). They remodeled the mansion's interior, and filled it with sumptuous European furniture and decorative arts.<ref name=\"Iames\"/> Following Safford's 2011 death, his widow sold the decorative arts at Freeman's Auction House in Philadelphia.{{efn|The September 25, 2013 auction \"brought $3.9 million, more than three times the presale estimate.\"<ref name=\"Iames\"/> Its top lot was a hand-painted Russian urn from Czar Nicholas I's imperial porcelain factory at St. Petersburg. Estimated at $150,000 to $200,000, it sold for $494,500.<ref name=\"Iames\"/>}} \n\nIn 2014, Mrs. Safford put the estate up for sale with an asking price of $9 million for the 8,900-square-foot mansion on 15 acres, with the barn on 3 acres available for a separate sale.<ref>Angelly Carri\u00f3n, [http://www.phillymag.com/property/2014/09/18/flatland-estate-going-9-milllion/#gallery-2-9 \"Fatland Estate is going for $9 million,\"] ''Philadelphia Magazine'', September 18, 2014.</ref> In February 2016, the asking price was reduced to $7 million.<ref>Melissa Romero, [https://philly.curbed.com/2016/2/8/10940748/vaux-hill-fatland-estate-for-sale-6999999 \"Regal Vaux Hill Mansion back on market with $2M Chop,\"] ''Curbed Philly'', February 8, 2016.</ref> The current asking price (July 2017) is $3.95 million.<ref name=\"Zillow\">[https://www.zillow.com/homedetails/1248-Pawlings-Rd-Phoenixville-PA-19460/9982010_zpid/?fullpage=true 1248 Pawlings Rd, Phoenixville, PA 19460 - Price History,] from Zillow.</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{commonscat|Fatland (Audubon, Pennsylvania)}}\n\n===Further reading===\n*Jennifer Anne Stark, ''The Pawling Farmhouse at Walnut Hill: Valley Forge National Park'', masters thesis, University of Pennsylvania, December 1992.[https://archive.org/stream/pawlingfarmhouse00star#page/n3/mode/2up]\n*Rebecca Anne Hunt, ''Blessed Spot along the Perkiomen: An Historical Analysis of Mill Grove'', dissertation, University of Pennsylvania, 1994.\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.phillyroads.com/roads/US-422_PA/ Pottstown Expressway Historic Overview]\n\n[[Category:Houses in Montgomery County, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Greek Revival architecture in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Houses completed in 1776]]\n[[Category:Houses completed in 1845]]\n[[Category:Valley Forge]]\n[[Category:John Haviland buildings]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox building\n| name                = \"Fatland\"\n| image               = Fatlands II MontCo PA Planning 713d5b o.jpg\n| image_size          = 300px\n| architectural_style = [[Greek Revival architecture|Greek Revival]]\n| classification      = \n| location            = \n| address             = 1248 Pawlings Road\n| location_town       = Audubon, Pennsylvania\n| location_country    = \n| coordinates = {{coord|40|07|09|N|75|26|35|W|display=inline,title}}\n| start_date          = 1843\n| stop_date           = \n| est_completion      = \n| topped_out_date     = \n| completion_date     = 1845\n| opened_date         = \n| inauguration_date   = \n| relocated_date      = \n| renovation_date     = 1990s\n| closing_date        = \n| material            = stuccoed brick & stone<br>wooden square columns<br> marble Ionic columns\n| grounds_area        = \n| architect           = [[John Haviland]]\n| architecture_firm   = \n| main_contractor     = \n| rooms               = <!-- or | unit_count          = -->\n| parking             =  \n| website             = \n| embed               = \n| embedded            = \n| references          = \n| footnotes           = \n}}\n'''Fatland (Audubon, Pennsylvania)''' &ndash; also known as \"Fatland Farm,\" \"Fatland Ford\" and, currently, \"Vaux Hill\" &ndash; is a Greek Revival mansion and estate in [[Audubon, Pennsylvania]]. Located on the north side of the [[Schuylkill River]], opposite [[Valley Forge, Pennsylvania|Valley Forge]], the property was part of the [[Valley Forge|Continental Army's 1777-78 winter encampment]]. On consecutive days in September 1777, its stone farmhouse served as headquarters for General [[George Washington]] and British General Sir [[William Howe, 5th Viscount Howe|William Howe]]. \n\nThe farmhouse was demolished about 1843, and the mansion was built on its site about 1845. The Wetherill Family owned the property for 121 years&mdash;1825 to 1946. A private cemetery contains the graves of some of Fatland's owners, and of [[Free Quakers]] who supported the Revolutionary War.\n\n==Fatland Farm==\nThe [[Perkiomen Creek]] empties in to the Schuylkill River just north of Valley Forge. The river curves in an [[Meander|oxbow]] and forms a peninsula with the creek. Early settlers called the area the \"Fatlands of Egypt\" because of its frequent flooding and rich [[alluvial]] soil.<ref>Thaddeus Vanderslice, ''Henry Pawling, a British Soldier and Some of His Descendants'' (Philadelphia: privately printed, 1904).</ref>\n\nJames Morgan dammed the creek and built a grist mill and miller's house on the north side of the Perkiomen Peninsula in 1749.<ref name=\"Herrick\"/>{{rp|104}} He built the country seat \"Mill Grove\" in 1762.<ref name=\"Herrick\"/>{{rp|104}} In a February 28, 1771 advertisement in ''The Pennsylvania Gazette'', he announced the upcoming auction of two adjacent properties, Fatland Farm and Mill Grove Farm:<blockquote>To be sold at public venue on the 4th day of March, upon the premises, if not sold before at private sale, by the subscriber, in Providence township, Philadelphia county, two valuable plantations, one of which consisting of 300 acres (Fatland farm), bounding near a mile on the Schuylkill river, whereas a good shad fishery; it also bounds the lands of Henry Pawling, Esq., and extends along the same to the Perkiomen; there are about 150 acres cleared, 20 whereof are good watered meadow and a great quantity more may be made; the woodland well timbered and the whole well watered, with the conveniency of watering every field on the plantation; there is a good stone dwelling house, brew house, with a large frame barn, three good bearing apple orchards, with a large peach orchard bearing plentifully. The other contains 250 acres [Mill Grove Farm] ...\"<ref name=\"MCHS\">Dr. W. H. Reed, \"Audubon. Its History, Tradition and Reminiscences,\" ''Historical Sketches: A Collection of Papers Prepared for the Historical Society of Montgomery County, Pennsylvania, Volume 4'', (Montgomery County Historical Society, 1909), pp. 173-224.</ref>{{rp|180-81}}</blockquote> \nThis auction took place, but neither property sold.<ref name=\"MCHS\"/>{{rp|181}} Instead, James Vaux (1748&ndash;1842) purchased Fatland Farm by private sale more than a year later, on June 18, 1772.<ref name=\"MCHS\"/>{{rp|181}}\n\n==Vaux Hill==\n[[File:Valley Forge Station circa 1910.jpg|thumb|Schuylkill River at Valley Forge, looking east, circa 1910. Fatland Island and Fatland Ford are in the background, center.]]\nVaux renamed the property \"Vaux Hill.\" The 300-acre (121.4 hectares) farm spanned the middle of the peninsula.<ref name=\"Vaux Papers\">[http://www2.hsp.org/collections/manuscripts/v/vaux684.htm Abstract - Vaux Family Papers], from Historical Society of Pennsylvania.</ref> Part of its western boundary, shared with Henry Pawling's farm, was the road south to Fatland Ford, a shallow crossing of the Schuylkill River, opposite Valley Forge.<ref name=\"VAFO, p.43\">National Park Service, ''Cultural Landscapes Inventory&mdash;Valley Forge National Historical Park'', 1999.[https://irma.nps.gov/DataStore/DownloadFile/454295 (PDF)]</ref> \n\nVaux was an English farmer and [[Society of Friends|Quaker]], who emigrated to Pennsylvania in 1771.<ref name=\"JFHS\">''Journal of the Friends' Historical Society, Volume 6'', (London: Friends' Historical Society, 1909), p. 186.[https://books.google.com/books?id=t5M5AQAAMAAJ&pg=PA186&lpg=PA186&dq=susanna+warder+vaux&source=bl&ots=XU8z9EeLrb&sig=x6YVeLHj-KLdJn3gaoJN4L6YVbQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiIvN6ug__UAhUIrD4KHcIjDAQQ6AEIKDAB#v=onepage&q=susanna%20warder%20vaux&f=false]</ref> He expanded the existing stone farmhouse in 1776,<ref name=\"MCHS\"/>{{rp|200}} and constructed its stone barn.<ref>[https://www.loc.gov/pictures/collection/hh/item/pa0904/ Vaux-Wetherill Stone Barn,] from HABS.</ref> The following year he married Susanna Warder (1749&ndash;1812) of Philadelphia, also a Quaker.<ref name=\"JFHS\"/>\n\nVaux took no side in the [[American Revolutionary War|Revolutionary War]]. On September 21, 1777, General [[George Washington]], accompanied by a detachment of [[Commander-in-Chief's Guard|his life guard]] and [[Washington's Aides-de-Camp|aide-de-camp]] [[Tench Tilghman]], [[Surveillance|surveilled]] British troops at Valley Forge from the north side of the river.<ref name=\"MCHS\"/>{{rp|201}} The river was swollen, which prevented the British from crossing. At Washington's direction, his aide urgently wrote to General [[Alexander McDougall]]&mdash;\"... the River has fallen and is fordable at almost any place, the Enemy can have no Reason to delay passing much longer. He would have wrote {{sic}} you personally, but is employed in viewing the ground and making disposition of the Army which arrived yesterday.\"<ref>[https://founders.archives.gov/documents/Washington/03-11-02-0302#GEWN-03-11-02-0302-fn-0002 Tench Tilghman for Gen. George Washington to Gen. Alexander McDougall, 21 Sept. 1777 (See note 2),] from National Archives.</ref> Vaux invited Washington to dine and stay the night&mdash;the life guard secured Fatland Ford overnight.<ref name=\"MCHS\"/>{{rp|201}} Washington and his troops departed early the following morning. \n\nThat same morning, British Captain John Montroser recorded in his journal: \"[September] 22nd. &mdash; At 5 this morning ... the Light Infantry and Grenadiers passed over the Schuylkill at Fatland Ford without a single shot and took post.\"<ref name=\"MCHS\"/>{{rp|185}} Early that evening, General Howe crossed the ford and made Vaux Hill his headquarters. Vaux dined with Howe, who asked about the rebel officer who had been spotted the previous day. When informed that it had been Washington himself, Howe reportedly replied: \"Oh, I wish I had known that. I would have tried to catch him!\"<ref name=\"Eberlein\"/>{{rp|412}} The opposing commanders-in-chief probably slept in the same bed on consecutive nights.<ref name=\"Eberlein & Lippincott\">Harold Donaldson Eberlein and Horace Mather Lippincott, ''Colonial Homes of Philadelphia and Its Neighbourhood'', (Philadelphia: J. B. Lippincott Company, 1912).</ref>{{rp|192-93}} As Howe slept, the British Army began a night crossing from Valley Forge. Montroser: \"[September] 23rd. &mdash; Just after 12 o'clock this night the whole army moved to the opposite side, on the north side of the river Schuylkill by the way of Fatland Ford, and by 10 a. m. the whole baggage and all had happily passed it. After the principal body had got on the north side of the Schuylkill about one mile the army halted to dry themselves and rest.\"<ref name=\"MCHS\"/>{{rp|185}}\n[[File:Valley Forge Park Burt 1920 inset.jpg|thumb|230px|left|''Valley Forge Park and Vicinity'' (1908). \"Old Fatland Ford\" is marked at the center top.]]\nGeneral Washington and the Continental Army returned to the area in December 1777 for the six month [[Valley Forge]] encampment. The majority of troops encamped south of the river, but Vaux's farm was the site of troop encampments and support facilities.<ref name=\"VAFO, p.43\"/> General [[John Sullivan (general)|John Sullivan]] supervised construction of a [[Pontoon bridge|floating-log bridge]] slightly downstream from Fatland Ford.<ref name=\"VAFO, p.43\"/> This bridge provided a river crossing in times of [[flood|high water]], and an escape route in the event of a British attack.<ref name=\"VAFO, p.43\"/> The floating bridge was destroyed by ice in 1779.<ref name=\"VAFO, p.43\"/>\n<blockquote>The British army, in September, 1777, passed from Valley Forge to the left bank of the Schuylkill by the Fatland Ford; not many months later [June 19, 1778], when the American forces evacuated Valley Forge, they crossed at the same place, as just mentioned. Both armies swarmed over the Vaux Hill plantation like devastating clouds of locusts. Tearing down fences, destroying trees and doing thousands of pounds' worth of damage in various ways, they wrought such havoc that Mr. Vaux's estate was seriously embarrassed in consequence.<ref name=\"Eberlein\"/>{{rp|410-11}}</blockquote>\nThe Commonwealth of Pennsylvania paid Vaux \u00a31,000 in compensation for damage done to his property during the war.<ref name=\"MCHS\"/>{{rp|202}} \"In the 1785 assessment of Providence township, James Vaux is recorded as a farmer, owning a farm of 300 acres of land, dwelling, four horses, six cows, one servant (colored), and one riding chair.\"<ref name=\"MCHS\"/>{{rp|206}} He later served in the [[Pennsylvania Legislature]].<ref name=\"Eberlein\"/>{{rp|412}} Vaux sold Vaux Hill to John Echline Allen, about 1794.<ref name=\"Vaux Papers\"/>\n\nThere are no known images of the \"good stone dwelling house\" described in 1771, or of the house as expanded by Vaux.<ref name=\"Eberlein\">Harold Donaldson Eberlein, ''Portrait of a Colonial City: Philadelphia 1670&ndash;1838'', (Philadelphia: J. B. Lippincott Company, 1939).</ref>{{rp|410}}\n\n==Fatland Ford==\n[[File:Bakewells, MCHS, 1910, opp. p.206.jpg|thumb|210px|William and Lucy Green Bakewell]]\nBy 1803, the farm was owned by James S. Ewing, who advertised it for sale in September. He listed its buildings: \"... a dwelling-house 45x35 feet, built of stone, ... Smith's house and Shop, Ice house, spring house, poultry house, smoke house, large stone barn with stables for 40 head of horses and cows ...\"<ref>''The Norristown Newspaper'', September 22, 1803, quoted in Stark, p. 113.</ref> \n\nEwing sold the property to Englishman William Woodhouse Bakewell (1759&ndash;1821) who, with his wife, 4 daughters and 2 sons,<ref name=\"MCHS\"/>{{rp|209}} occupied it in January 1804.<ref name=\"Herrick\"/>{{rp|99, n.1}} Bakewell's wife, Lucy Green Bakewell (1765&ndash;1804), died during their first year living there. Their eldest daughter, also named Lucy (1787&ndash;1874), took on the duties of hostess. \n\nBakewell renamed the property \"Fatland Ford,\"<ref>''The Norristown Newspaper'', September 8, 1813, quoted in Stark, p. 113.</ref> and operated it as a [[gentleman's farm]]. Robert Sutcliff, a relative of Bakewell's estate manager, visited in August 1804:<blockquote>This plantation, consists of 300 acres of good land, 200 of which are cleared, and 100 covered with wood. On the estate is a well finished square stone house, about 15 yards [13.7 m] in length, with a wide boarded floor piazza, both in back and front. These afford excellent accommodation during the summer season ... Besides the dwelling house, there is an excellent kitchen, and offices adjoining; with a large barn, and stables sufficient to accommodate 40 horses and cows; all well built of stone. The estate extends the whole breadth betwixt the Schuylkill and Perkiomen. On the former river there is a [[Shad]] Fishery which is of considerable value ... This estate, with all its appendages, cost about ''3600\u00a3'' sterling, which is but ''12\u00a3'' per acre, the buildings included. The house is so situated that it commands one of the finest prospects in Pennsylvania, and, being on a rising ground, is dry and healthy. The whole together forms one of the most beautiful spots I have seen in the United States.<ref name=\"Sutcliff\">Robert Sutcliff, ''Travels in Some Parts of North America, in the Years 1804, 1805 & 1806'',  (York, England: printed by C. Peacock, 1811).</ref>{{rp|30-31}}</blockquote>\n\n===Audubon===\n[[File:Mill Grove Mansion.jpg|thumb|Mill Grove, in 2012.]]\nSutcliff also visited [[Mill Grove]], then owned by Jean Audubon, a retired French sea captain living in [[Nantes, France]].<ref name=\"Arthur\">Stanley Clisby Arthur, ''Audubon: An Intimate Life of the American Woodsman'', (Gretna, Louisiana: Pelican Publishing, 1937).</ref>{{rp|478}} [[Lead]] deposits had been discovered on the farm, and Captain Audubon formed a partnership with French businessman Francis Dacosta to mine the ore.<ref name=\"Arthur\"/>{{rp|37-38}} Sutcliff wrote: \"In the plantation adjoining to my relation's, we visited a lead mine on the banks of the Perkiomin {{sic}}, which was then worked by a Frenchman. He invited us to go down into it, where, at the depth of about 12 feet, I saw a vein of lead ore 18 inches in thickness; and as it is wrought at a very easy expense, there was a great probability of its being a very valuable acquisition.\"<ref name=\"Sutcliff\"/>{{rp|34}} \n\nThe \"Frenchman\" Sutcliff met may have been Dacosta, or it may have been the captain's 19-year-old son (and future naturalist) [[John James Audubon]]&mdash;they had arrived in America together the year before.<ref name=\"Herrick\"/>{{rp|xxv}} Audubon and 17-year-old [[Lucy Bakewell Audubon|Lucy Bakewell]] fell in love, although her father thought both of them too young to marry.<ref name=\"Arthur\"/>{{rp|37-38}} Informed by letter of his son's intentions, Captain Audubon initially opposed the marriage.<ref name=\"Arthur\"/>{{rp|40}} With money borrowed from the Bakewells, Audubon sailed for France in January 1805 to sort out what to do about Mill Grove and the lead mine, and to obtain his father's permission to marry.<ref name=\"Arthur\"/>{{rp|39}} He returned to the United States in May 1806 having attained his majority and his father's blessing.<ref name=\"Arthur\"/>{{rp|46-47}} Bakewell also consented to the engagement. Audubon sold Mill Grove and his father's interest in the lead mine to Dacosta in September 1806,<ref name=\"Herrick\"/>{{rp|xxvi}} and moved to New York City to work as a clerk in the [[counting house]] of Bakewell's brother.<ref name=\"Herrick\"/>{{rp|xxvi}} In August 1807, he and a partner opened a pioneer store in Louisville, Kentucky.<ref name=\"Herrick\"/>{{rp|xxvii}} On April 8, 1808, John James Audubon and Lucy Bakewell were married at \"Fatland Ford.\"<ref name=\"Journals\">John James Audubon, ''Audubon and His Journals'', edited by Maria R. Audubon, (New York: Charles Scribner's Sons, 1899).</ref>{{rp|28}} The next morning, the newlyweds departed for Louisville, where Audubon continued his short-lived career as a merchant.<ref name=\"Journals\"/>{{rp|28-29}}\n\nWhen Bakewell advertised Fatland Ford for sale in 1813, he listed \"a [steam] threshing-mill, which threshes 12 bushels of barley in an hour,\" and livestock of \"200 Sheep of the English Morena breeds, span of oxen and other cattle, 4 asses, 7 horses, ... 30 pigs of the English Berkshire breed.\"<ref>''The Norristown Newspaper'', August 7, 1813, quoted in John T. Faris, ''Old Roads Out of Philadelphia'', (Philadelphia and London: J. B. Lippincott Company, 1917), p. 198.[https://archive.org/stream/oldroadsoutphil01farigoog#page/n264/mode/2up/search/Wetherill]</ref> The sale was not successful; Bakewell was still the owner of the property when he died there in 1821.<ref name=\"Woodman\">Henry Woodman, ''The History of Valley Forge'', (Oaks, PA: John U. Francis, Sr., 1922)</ref>{{rp|110}}\n\nLucy Green Bakewell had been buried at \"Fatland Ford\" in 1804.<ref name=\"MCHS\"/>{{rp|208}} Bakewell remarried, and was initially buried in Philadelphia.<ref name=\"MCHS\"/>{{rp|208-09}} His descendants later had him reinterred beside his first wife.<ref>[https://www.findagrave.com/cgi-bin/fg.cgi?page=gr&GScid=46619&GRid=38635090& William Woodhouse Bakewell,] from Find-A-Grave.</ref>\n\n==Fatland==\n[[File:Fatland Faris Old Roads 1917 opp. p.192.jpg|thumb|left|\"Fatland,\" from the northwest, in 1917.]]\n[[File:Audubon and his journals (1897) (14752067971).jpg|thumb|left|\"Fatland,\" from the south, in the 1890s.]]\nDacosta's lead mine initially was unprofitable, with costs too great to compete with imported lead from England.<ref name=\"Herrick\">Francis Hobart Herrick, ''Audubon the Naturalist: A History of His Life and Time, Volume 1'', (New York and London: D. Appleton and Company, 1917).</ref>{{rp|115}} The [[War of 1812]] caused imports to be cut off, and the price of lead in the United States to soar.<ref name=\"PCP\">''The First Century of the Philadelphia College of Pharmacy, 1821-1921'', (Philadelphia College of Pharmacy and Science, 1922).</ref>{{rp|38}} Samuel Wetherill, Jr., a Philadelphia white lead importer and paint manufacturer, purchased Mill Grove for $7,000 in 1813.<ref name=\"Herrick\"/>{{rp|169}} Wetherill & Son reopened the mine, and \"mined and smelted over 100 tons from small veins on Perkiomen Creek in Montgomery County, Pa., on Mill Grove farm.\"<ref name=\"PCP\"/>{{rp|36}} The depleted mine was closed again in the 1820s.<ref name=\"Woodman\"/>{{rp|108}} \n\nSamuel Wetherill 3rd (1764&ndash;1829) purchased \"Fatland Ford\" in 1825, and changed its name to just \"Fatland.\" He had been his father's partner, and inherited the family business. He and his wife, Rachel Price (1766&ndash;1844), had 5 sons and a daughter.<ref name=\"Jordan\"/>{{rp|996}} Wetherill inherited Mill Grove, bought up farms owned by the Bakewells and the Pawlings, and became the great landowner of the peninsula.<ref name=\"VAFO, p.43\"/>{{rp|46}} He subsequently bequeathed the properties to his children and grandchildren.<ref>Stark, p. 3.</ref> \"These properties were improved with stately mansions and outbuildings with beautiful lawns and surroundings. (Also erected were summer residences on some of the properties.)\"<ref name=\"VAFO, p.43\"/>{{rp|46}} \n\nDr. William Wetherill (1804&ndash;1872), inherited Fatland.<ref name=\"Eberlein & Lippincott\"/>{{rp|196}} He was a Philadelphia physician, and partner &ndash; with his brother John, who inherited Mill Grove &ndash; in the Wetherill White Lead Works.<ref name=\"Jordan\"/>{{rp|1004}} He and his wife Isabella Macomb (1807&ndash;1871) had 16 children, 12 of whom lived to adulthood.<ref name=\"Jordan\"/>{{rp|1004}} Dr. Wetherill demolished Fatland's stone farmhouse, about 1843, and replaced it with a [[Greek Revival architecture|Greek Revival]] mansion built upon the farmhouse's foundations.<ref name=\"Eberlein & Lippincott\"/>{{rp|196-97}}<ref>Linda Stein, [http://www.mainlinemedianews.com/mainlinesuburbanlife/life/fabulous-antiques-from-vaux-hill-to-be-auctioned/article_b5b19e72-5313-53e8-93e9-81c4555a2ccb.html \"Fabulous antiques from Vaux Hill to be auctioned,\"] ''Main Line Suburban Life'', September 18, 2013.</ref> \n\nPossibly inspired by [[Andalusia (estate)|\"Andalusia\"]] (1834-36), [[Nicholas Biddle (banker)|Nicholas Biddle]]'s great Greek Revival mansion overlooking the [[Delaware River]], architect [[John Haviland]] designed a \"western counterpart\" for Dr. Wetherill, \"Fatland Hall,\" overlooking the Schuylkill River.<ref name=\"Thomas\">George E. Thomas, ''Buildings of Pennsylvania &ndash; Philadelphia and Eastern Pennsylvania'', (Charlottesville and London: University of Virginia Press, 2010), p. 201.</ref> The size and arrangement of the mansion's [[Central-passage house|center hall]] and formal rooms were similar to James Vaux's expanded farmhouse,<ref name=\"Eberlein\"/> but with much higher ceilings: \"Fatland is special for the scale of the portico and its juxtaposed miniature service wing.\"<ref name=\"Thomas\"/> The overall composition was asymmetrical,<ref name=\"Eberlein\"/> the first floor of the single wing (to the east) consisted of the formal dining room, and pantries and the family dining room in the [[Pavilion|end pavilion]]. The kitchen was in the basement below, and servant rooms were above.<ref name=\"Eberlein\"/> The end pavilion featured painted-wood-columned [[portico]]es on the front and rear facades.<ref name=\"Eberlein\"/> The great [[Ionic column]]s of the main block's porticoes were of white marble.<ref name=\"Eberlein\"/> The mansion was completed about 1845.<ref name=\"Eberlein\"/> A stone tablet in its south gable reads: \"J. Vaux, 1776; rebuilt by William Wetherill, 1843.\"<ref name=\"MCHS\"/>{{rp|200}} \"[[Bayard Taylor]], the historian and traveler, claimed [the view from the piazza] was the most beautiful view along the beautiful Schuylkill river.\"<ref name=\"Jordan\"/>{{rp|1006}}\n\nFatland was inherited by Dr. Wetherill's son, Col. John Macomb Wetherill (1828&ndash;1895), a [[American Civil War|Civil War]] veteran who managed the family's Pennsylvania coal lands, and never married.<ref name=\"Jordan\">John Woolf Jordan, ''Colonial Families of Philadelphia, Volume 2'', (Lewis Publishing Company, 1911).[https://books.google.com/books?id=3kc2AQAAMAAJ&pg=PA1004&dq=john+macomb+wetherill&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj5oYPQnPvUAhUFGj4KHXJUBVMQ6AEIKDAB#v=onepage&q=john%20macomb%20wetherill&f=false]</ref>{{rp|1004}} He gave permission for William Bakewell's remains to be reinterred at Fatland,<ref name=\"MCHS\"/>{{rp|209}} and directed that he himself be buried there.<ref name=\"Journals\"/>{{rp|43, n.3}} In his will, Col. Wetherill deeded the private cemetery to a trust, directed that it be expanded and improved, and established an endowment for its maintenance.<ref name=\"Journals\"/>{{rp|43, n.3}} \n\nOwnership of Fatland passed to the colonel's younger brother, William H. Wetherill, Jr. (1838&ndash;1927) and wife Elizabeth Proctor (1842&ndash;1914), under whom the property was \"greatly beautified.\"<ref name=\"Jordan\"/>{{rp|1006}} He carried out the improvements to the private cemetery, and had Wetherill ancestors and others reburied there.\n \nDr. Henry Emerson Wetherill (1871&ndash;1946), the eldest son of William H. and a U.S. Army surgeon and inventor, inherited Fatland in 1927. He had been a member of [[Robert Peary]]'s 1893-94 [[Greenland]] expedition, on which he collected plant specimens.<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/pearyauxiliaryex00brya#page/70/mode/2up \"List of Plants Obtained on the Peary Auxiliary Expedition of 1894,\"]</ref>  He also delivered [[Josephine Diebitsch Peary|Mrs. Peary]]'s daughter Marie, whom the popular press dubbed the \"Snow Baby.\"<ref>\"Dr. H. E. Wetherill, Peary Arctic Aide, Delivered Child to Admiral's Wife on 1893 Expedition &ndash; Surgeon, Inventor Dies,\" ''The New York Times'', March 9, 1946.</ref> An inveterate tinkerer, his diagnostic medical devices were awarded the 1906 Longstreth Medal by the [[Franklin Institute]].<ref>[https://www.fi.edu/laureates/henry-emerson-wetherill Henry Emerson Wetherill,] from The Franklin Institute.</ref> He also invented navigational instruments for ships,<ref>Henry Emerson Wetherill, \"New Aids for Navigation,\" ''Journal of the Franklin Institute'', September 1908.</ref> and a musical instrument called a [[Slide whistle|trombone flute]].<ref>[http://memory.loc.gov/diglib/ihas/loc.music.dcmphot.a0493/default.html \"Dr. Henry Emerson Wetherill (photograph),] from Library of Congress.</ref> Dr. Wetherill never married, and was buried in the private cemetery. He was the last Wetherill to own Fatland.\n\n===Free Quaker - Wetherill Cemetery===\n[[File:Free Quaker - Wetherill Cemetery.jpg|thumb|Free Quaker - Wetherill Cemetery, in 2017.]]\nSamuel Wetherill, Jr. provided supplies to the Continental Army at Valley Forge, and was \"read out of meeting\" (disowned) by the [[Society of Friends]] in 1779, after refusing to renounce those actions.<ref name=\"Wetherill\">Charles Wetherill, ''History of The Religious Society of Friends, Called by Some The Free Quakers, in the City of Philadelphia'', (Philadelphia: privately printed, 1894).</ref> Defying the [[pacifism]] of their religion, \"[[Free Quakers]]\" supported or fought in the Revolutionary War. Wetherill became a founder of Philadelphia's Free Quaker Meeting (chartered February 20, 1781),<ref name=\"Wetherill\"/> and served as its clerk and preacher.<ref name=\"Wetherill\"/> With brother-in-law Timothy Matlack, another charter member, he designed its [[Free Quaker Meetinghouse|meeting house]] (1783-84), at 5th and Arch Streets.<ref name=\"Peterson\">Charles E. Peterson, ''Notes on the Free Quaker Meeting House'', (Washington, D.C.: Ross & Perry, 2002).</ref> The meeting established its own burying ground, on the east side of 5th Street between Locust and Spruce Streets.<ref name=\"Ault\">Walter Ault, \"The Fighting Quakers Cemetery,\" ''The Times Herald'', September 14, 2009.[http://www.timesherald.com/article/JR/20090914/NEWS01/309149996]</ref> Membership dwindled as the Free Quakers died off, and their meeting house was closed in 1836.<ref name=\"Peterson\"/> As the turn of the 20th century approached, the Free Quaker Burying Ground plot became attractive for commercial development.<ref name=\"Ault\"/> It was in anticipation of its sale that Col. John Macomb Wetherill (Samuel Wetherill, Jr.'s great-grandson) directed in his 1895 will that the private cemetery at Fatland be expanded.<ref name=\"Ault\"/> \n\nIn 1905, remains from sixty-one graves were removed from the Free Quaker Burying Ground and reinterred at Fatland.<ref name=\"Ault\"/> Included were those of Samuel Wetherill, Jr. and his wife and relatives, including [[Timothy Matlack]],<ref>[https://www.findagrave.com/cgi-bin/fg.cgi?page=gr&GRid=16365624 Timothy Matlack,] from Find-A-Grave.</ref> scribe of the [[Second Continental Congress]]&mdash;whose [[penmanship]] can be seen in the [[United States Declaration of Independence|Declaration of Independence]]. Many of the tombstones had severely eroded, and were illegible or identifiable only by initials. The remains of [[Ira Allen]], one of Vermont's [[Green Mountain Boys]], had been lost with the closing of another Philadelphia cemetery, and his [[cenotaph]] also was moved to Fatland.<ref>[https://www.findagrave.com/cgi-bin/fg.cgi?page=gr&GRid=38633277 Ira Allen,] from Find-A-Grave.</ref>\n\nNumerous Wetherill family members have been and continue to be buried in the private cemetery.<ref>[https://www.findagrave.com/cgi-bin/fg.cgi?page=gsr&GScid=46619 Wetherill Cemetery - Interments,] from Find-A-Grave.</ref>\n\n===Saint Gabriel's Hall===\n[[File:St. Gabriel's Hall from Rte. 422.jpg|thumb|Saint Gabriel's Hall from the Pottstown Expressway, in 2017.]]\nOn November 19, 1895, the [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Philadelphia]] purchased a 185-acre tract of land adjacent to Fatland, to the west.<ref name=\"Kirlin\">Joseph Louis J. Kirlin, ''Catholicity in Philadelphia: From the Earliest Missionaries down to the Present Time'', (Philadelphia: J. J. McVey, 1909), pp. 411-13.[https://books.google.com/books?id=YfTPAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA412&lpg=PA412&dq=%22protectory+station%22+Fatland&source=bl&ots=6bgQZ5u9JQ&sig=9XbRZoxhuvG9XiroGmWSDfTEdqA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj9tvH4vonVAhUCQz4KHYgmBFwQ6AEINzAE#v=onepage&q=%22protectory%20station%22%20Fatland&f=false]</ref>{{rp|412}} Formerly part of Henry Pawling's farm, there the Archdiocese built the Philadelphia Protectory for Boys, an orphanage staffed by the [[De La Salle Brothers|Christian Brothers]]. Architects [[Wilson Brothers & Company]] designed its [[Italianate architecture|Italianate]] orange-brick-and-red-tile-roofed building, which included a tall [[campanile]], or belltower.<ref>[https://www.philadelphiabuildings.org/pab/app/pj_display_allarchitects.cfm/54258 Roman Catholic Protectory,] from Philadelphia Architects and Buildings.</ref> Archbishop [[Patrick John Ryan]] dedicated the building on May 8, 1898, with more than 3,000 in attendance.<ref name=\"Kirlin\"/>{{rp|412}} Its initial capacity was for housing 200 boys, but the capacity increased to 500 boys with additions that opened in September 1905.<ref name=\"Kirlin\"/>{{rp|412}} An additional 100 acres were purchased in 1902, which extended the property to the Schuylkill River and included Fatland Island (part of Fatland Ford).<ref name=\"Kirlin\"/>{{rp|412}} The name of the [[Reading Company|Reading Railroad]] passenger station opposite the west end of the peninsula was changed to Protectory Station, by 1898.<ref name=\"Kirlin\"/>{{rp|412}} The protectory was renamed Saint Gabriel's Hall in 1962.<ref name=\"St. Gabe's\">[http://st-gabes.org/residential/saint-gabriels-hall History,] from Saint Gabriel's Hall.</ref> \n\nOperated by the Catholic Social Services of the Archdiocese of Philadelphia, \"St. Gabe's\" is now a [[juvenile detention]] facility.<ref name=\"St. Gabe's\"/> Its border with Fatland follows the old path of Fatland Ford Road.<ref name=\"VAFO, p.43\"/>{{rp|73}}\n\n===Camiel===\n[[File:NPS valley-forge-map.pdf|thumb|left|U.S. Rte. 422 / Pottstown Expressway (bottom right to top) makes two major curves.]]\n[[File:St. Gabe's Curve from Pawlings Road Bridge.jpg|thumb|left|\"St. Gabe's Curve.\" U.S. Rte. 422 / Pottstown Expressway, from Pawlings Road, in 2017.]]\nAntiquarian Harold Donaldson Eberlein wrote about Fatland in 1912.<ref name=\"Eberlein & Lippincott\"/> By the time he revisited the estate in 1939, the landscape had changed: \"So closely is the house screened by great ancient trees that only in winter can you catch a glimpse from a distance of its stately white porticoes gleaming through the interlacing branches.\"<ref name=\"Eberlein\"/>{{rp|409}} Dr. Henry Emerson Wetherill died at Fatland in 1946. Later that year the property was purchased by the Philadelphia Democratic politician [[Peter Camiel|Peter J. Camiel]] (1910&ndash;1991) and his wife Nina (1913&ndash;2007). \n\nCamiel was one of 12 children of [[Poles|Polish]] [[Jewish]] immigrants, a former boxer, longshoreman and union organizer.<ref name=\"PA Senate\">\"Senate Resolution [memorializing the late Peter J. Camiel],\" ''Pennsylvania Legislative Journal&mdash;Senate'', February 5, 1991, pp. 116-119.[http://www.legis.state.pa.us/WU01/LI/SJ/1991/0/Sj19910205.pdf (PDF)]</ref> He made himself a millionaire as a wholesale beer distributor.<ref name=\"NYT obit\"/> Camiel served as a [[Pennsylvania State Senator]] from 1953 to 1964, and as chairman of the Philadelphia Democratic City Committee from 1970 to 1976.<ref name=\"NYT obit\">[https://www.nytimes.com/1991/02/02/obituaries/peter-j-camiel-81-philadelphia-chief-of-70-s-democrats.html \"Peter J. Camiel, 81, Philadelphia Chief of '70s Democrats,\"] ''The New York Times'', February 2, 1991.</ref> He was appointed one of five commissioners to the powerful [[Pennsylvania Turnpike Commission]] in 1975, serving on it until his death.<ref name=\"PA Senate\"/>{{efn|Technically, Camiel was suspended from the Turnpike Commission in May 1980, after federal charges were filed against him for [[Malfeasance in office|corruption]]. He was found guilty &ndash; United States v. Camiel, 689 F.2d 31 (3d Cir. 1982) &ndash; but the verdict was reversed on appeal. He returned to the commission in 1983.<ref>Tom Fontaine, \"Thornburgh: Let PennDOT run the Pennsylvania Turnpike,\" ''The Pittsburgh Tribune'', March 31, 2013.</ref>}}\n\nState Senator [[Vince Fumo]]: \"Pete was a pilot. I used to listen for hours in amazement, when he would tell the stories about how he found Fatland Farm, flying over it in a plane, hidden behind so many trees. He bought it and pulled all those trees out and made it into a showcase right next to Valley Forge Park.\"<ref name=\"PA Senate\"/>{{rp|119}} The Camiels spent several years renovating the mansion, rehabilitating the overgrown estate, and returning it to being a working farm.<ref name=\"VAFO, p.43\"/>{{rp|56}} About 1950, they sold off a section on the south side of Pawlings Road, between the mansion and Saint Gabriel's Hall, for a housing development.<ref name=\"VAFO, p.43\"/>{{rp|34}}\n\n====Pottstown Expressway====\nIn 1951, folowing 138 years of family ownership, Herbert Johnson Wetherill sold [[Mill Grove]] to [[Montgomery County, Pennsylvania|Montgomery County]] to create a [[bird sanctuary]] and [[house museum]] honoring John James Audubon. Twenty-five years later, it was announced that the planned route for the [[U.S. Route 422|Pottstown Expressway]] was to go through the Audubon property. Camiel was credited with / blamed for applying political pressure to reroute the superhighway around the bird sanctuary:\n\n<blockquote>Central to the arguments concerning politicians appears to be the controversial \"Camiel Loop.\" [Montgomery County Planning Commission associate director] Plutte said that the cost of rerouting the Pottstown Expressway around the home of Peter J. Camiel caused the price of the highway to jump from $5 million to $8 million, and most recently to more than $10 million in the past six months. As the highway leaves the connection with Betzwood Bridge and aims northwest toward Pottstown, it veers sharply south [''sic'' west], down and around Camiel's farm, \"Fatland.\" The parabolic dip in the road mean several miles of additional roadway, roadway that Pottstown was denied. Plutte said the Camiel loop was installed to avert a \"potential challenge\" arising out of an environmental study. Camiel's farm is near the Audubon Sanctuary, which according to original plans, would have had to surrender land to the highway crews. Federal funds, which pay for 70 per cent of the Pottstown Expressway, could be jeopardized by the taking of the park land, Plutte said.<ref>William G. Reinecke, \"Pottstown expressway link blocked; Construction may start in 1989,\" ''The Pottstown Mercury'', September 23, 1976, p. 1.</ref></blockquote>\n\nWhether Camiel acted from selfish or selfless motives (or a combination of both), the rerouting of the Pottstown Expressway spared Mill Grove &ndash; now a [[National Historic Landmark]] &ndash; and minimized the adverse effect on Fatland. The Camiels owned the property for 44 years, and were buried together in its private cemetery.<ref>[https://www.findagrave.com/cgi-bin/fg.cgi?page=gr&GRid=118909314 Peter J. Camiel,] from Find-A-Grave.</ref><ref>[https://www.findagrave.com/cgi-bin/fg.cgi?page=gr&GRid=118909353 Nina Gumen Camiel,] from Find-A-Grave.</ref>\n\n==Vaux Hill (2)==\n{{external media | width = 220px | align = right | headerimage = [[File:Fatlands Mansion MontCo PA Planning 4a909 o.jpg|220px]] | video1 = [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xOYg61xGPqs Selected Contents of Vaux Hill]<ref name=\"Freeman's\">{{cite web | title = Selected Contents of Vaux Hill | work = | publisher =Freeman's Auctions on YouTube | date = 2013 | url =https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xOYg61xGPqs | accessdate =July 17, 2017 }}</ref> | video2 = [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YJs6uxho03k Vaux Hill]<ref name=\"Vaux Hill\">{{cite web|title=1248 Pawlings Road Phoenixville, PA 19460| date = 2015 | url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YJs6uxho03k |publisher=Kurfiss Sotheby's International Realty on YouTube |accessdate=July 17, 2017}}</ref> }}\nCamiel's land sales dramatically reduced Fatland's acreage&mdash;his housing development, land for the Pottstown Expressway, and his sale of 154 acres (62.3 hectare) between the expressway and the Schyulkill River to [[Valley Forge National Historical Park]].<ref>Editorial: \"Protecting Valley Forge,\" ''The Philadelphia Inquirer'', November 20, 1979.</ref> On July 16, 1990, Robert Owen Safford (1934&ndash;2011) and his wife Barbara Harvey (b. 1947) purchased the mansion on 18 acres from Camiel for $2.1 million.<ref name=\"Zillow\"/> The couple changed the name of the property back to \"Vaux Hill,\" the name James Vaux had given it in 1772.<ref name=\"Iames\">David Iames, \"The Vaux Hill Sale,\" ''Antiques & Auction News'', October 8, 2013.[https://www.antiquesandauctionnews.net/article_print.lasso?-a=The-Vaux-Hill-Sale]</ref> \n\nThe Saffords expanded the mansion, erecting a west wing and end pavilion that mirrored the east wing and end pavilion&mdash;thus creating an overall symmetrical building (for the first time). They remodeled the mansion's interior, and filled it with sumptuous European furniture and decorative arts.<ref name=\"Iames\"/> Following Safford's 2011 death, his widow sold the decorative arts at Freeman's Auction House in Philadelphia.{{efn|The September 25, 2013 auction \"brought $3.9 million, more than three times the presale estimate.\"<ref name=\"Iames\"/> Its top lot was a hand-painted Russian urn from Czar Nicholas I's imperial porcelain factory at St. Petersburg. Estimated at $150,000 to $200,000, it sold for $494,500.<ref name=\"Iames\"/>}} \n\nIn 2014, Mrs. Safford put the estate up for sale with an asking price of $9 million for the 8,900-square-foot mansion on 15 acres, with the barn on 3 acres available for a separate sale.<ref>Angelly Carri\u00f3n, [http://www.phillymag.com/property/2014/09/18/flatland-estate-going-9-milllion/#gallery-2-9 \"Fatland Estate is going for $9 million,\"] ''Philadelphia Magazine'', September 18, 2014.</ref> In February 2016, the asking price was reduced to $7 million.<ref>Melissa Romero, [https://philly.curbed.com/2016/2/8/10940748/vaux-hill-fatland-estate-for-sale-6999999 \"Regal Vaux Hill Mansion back on market with $2M Chop,\"] ''Curbed Philly'', February 8, 2016.</ref> The current asking price (July 2017) is $3.95 million.<ref name=\"Zillow\">[https://www.zillow.com/homedetails/1248-Pawlings-Rd-Phoenixville-PA-19460/9982010_zpid/?fullpage=true 1248 Pawlings Rd, Phoenixville, PA 19460 - Price History,] from Zillow.</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{commonscat|Fatland (Audubon, Pennsylvania)}}\n\n===Further reading===\n*Jennifer Anne Stark, ''The Pawling Farmhouse at Walnut Hill: Valley Forge National Park'', masters thesis, University of Pennsylvania, December 1992.[https://archive.org/stream/pawlingfarmhouse00star#page/n3/mode/2up]\n*Rebecca Anne Hunt, ''Blessed Spot along the Perkiomen: An Historical Analysis of Mill Grove'', dissertation, University of Pennsylvania, 1994.\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.phillyroads.com/roads/US-422_PA/ Pottstown Expressway Historic Overview]\n\n[[Category:Houses in Montgomery County, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Greek Revival architecture in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Houses completed in 1776]]\n[[Category:Houses completed in 1845]]\n[[Category:Valley Forge]]\n[[Category:John Haviland buildings]]\n", "name_user": "BoringHistoryGuy", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eVaux Hill (2)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fatland_(Audubon,_Pennsylvania)"}
{"title_page": "Englyn", "text_new": "{{Italic title}}\n[[File:Eglwys Crist, y Bala Christ Church, Bala, Gwynedd North Wales 24.JPG|thumb|An englyn on a gravestone in [[Christ Church, Bala]]:<br />''Price anwyl, pur ei wasanaeth...'']]\n'''{{lang|cy|Englyn}}''' ({{IPA-cy|\u02c8\u025b\u014b.l\u026an|pron}}; plural {{lang|cy|englynion}}) is a traditional [[Welsh language|Welsh]] and [[Cornish language|Cornish]] short [[Poetry|poem]] form. It uses [[Meter (poetry)|quantitative metres]], involving the counting of [[syllable]]s, and rigid patterns of [[rhyme]] and [[half rhyme]]. Each line contains a repeating pattern of consonants and accent known as {{lang|cy|[[cynghanedd]]}}.\n\n==Early history==\n\nThe {{lang|cy|englyn}} is found in the work of the earliest attested Welsh poets (the {{lang|cy|[[cynfeirdd]]}}), where the main types are the three-line {{lang|cy|englyn milwr}} and {{lang|cy|englyn penfyr}}.<ref>Rowland, Jenny, ''Early Welsh Saga Poetry: A Study and Edition of the ''Englynion''<nowiki />'' (Cambridge: Brewer, 1990), p. 305.</ref> It is the only set stanzaic metre found in the early Welsh poetic corpus, and explanations for its origins have tended to focus on stanzaic Latin poetry and hymns; however, it is as likely to be a development within the Brittonic poetic tradition.<ref>Rowland, Jenny, ''Early Welsh Saga Poetry: A Study and Edition of the ''Englynion''<nowiki />'' (Cambridge: Brewer, 1990), pp. 305-8.</ref> Whereas the metrical rules of later {{lang|cy|englynion}} are clear (and are based on counting syllables), the precise metre of the early {{lang|cy|englynion}} is debated and could have involved stress-counting.<ref>Rowland, Jenny, ''Early Welsh Saga Poetry: A Study and Edition of the ''Englynion''<nowiki />'' (Cambridge: Brewer, 1990), pp. 308-32.</ref> The earliest {{lang|cy|englynion}} are found as [[marginalia]] written in a tenth-century hand in the [[Juvencus Manuscript]].<ref>''A Selection of Early Welsh Saga Poems'', ed. by Jenny Rowland (London: Modern Humanities Research Association, 2014), p. xxvi.</ref> Many early {{lang|cy|englynion}} form poems which seem to represent moments of characters' emotional reflection in stories now lost: {{lang|cy|[[Canu Llywarch Hen]]}}, {{lang|cy|[[Canu Urien]]}}, {{lang|cy|[[Canu Heledd]]}}. Others survey heroic tradition, for example the {{lang|cy|[[Englynion y Beddau]]}} or ''[[Geraint son of Erbin]]'', and others again are lyric, religious meditations and laments such as the famous {{lang|cy|[[Claf Abercuawg]]}} and {{lang|cy|[[Kyntaw geir]]}}.\n\n== Types of {{lang|cy|englynion}}==\n\nThere are a number of types of {{lang|cy|englynion}}. Details of their structures are as follows; not all of these, however, are included in the [[Traditional Welsh poetic metres]].\n\n=== {{lang|cy|Englyn penfyr}} ===\n\nAlso known as the short-ended {{lang|cy|englyn}}. It consists of a stanza of three verses. The first verse has ten syllables (in two groups of five), the second has five to six; and the third has seven. The seventh, eighth or ninth syllable of the first verse introduces the rhyme and this is repeated on the last syllable of the other two verses. The fourth syllable of the second verse may echo the final syllable of the first through either rhyme or [[Literary consonance|consonance]].\n{{quote|1=<poem>{{lang|cy|Oer gwly pysgawd yng nghysg'''awd''' i\u00e4en;\nCul hydd, cawn barf'''awd''';\nByr diwedydd, gw\u0177dd gwyr'''awd'''.<ref name=\":0\">''[[iarchive:oxfordbookofwels00parr|The Oxford Book of Welsh Verse]]'', ed. by Thomas Parry (Oxford: Clarendon Press, 1962).</ref>{{rp|17}}}}</poem>}}\n\n=== {{lang|cy|Englyn unodl union}} ===\nThe straight one-rhymed {{lang|cy|englyn}}, identical to {{lang|cy|englyn penfyr}} except that it addes a fourth, rhyming, seven-syllable line at the end. Thus it consists of four verses of ten, six, seven and seven syllables. The seventh, eighth or ninth syllable of the first verse introduces the rhyme and this is repeated on the last syllable of the other three verses. The part of the first verse after the rhyme alliterates with the first part of the second verse.\n\nThis is an {{lang|cy|englyn unodl union}} by Alan Llwyd:\n\n{{quote|1=<poem>{{lang|cy|Ym Mhorth oer y Merthyr'''on''' \u2013 y merthyr\nMwya'i werth o ddig'''on'''\nA hir-fawrha y fro h'''on'''\nWr dewr o Aberdar'''on'''}}</poem>}}\n\n=== {{lang|cy|Englyn milwr}} ===\n\nThe soldier's {{lang|cy|englyn}}. This consists of three seven-syllable verses. All three verses rhyme.\n{{quote|1=<poem>{{lang|cy|Otid eiry, gwyn y cn'''es''';\nNid \u00e2 cedwyr i'w neg'''es''';\nOer llynnau, eu lliw heb d'''es'''.<ref name=\":0\" />{{rp|17}}}}</poem>}}\n\n=== {{lang|cy|Englyn gwastad}} ===\nThe even {{lang|cy|englyn}}, more common in the Middle Ages than later. This is identical to {{lang|cy|englyn milwr}} except that it has four lines. One example (showing the half-rhyme of -''edd'' with -''er'') is:\n{{quote|1=<poem>{{lang|cy|Cyntefin ceinaf ams'''er''',\nDydar adar, glas call'''edd''',\nEreidr yn rhych, ych yng ngw'''edd''',\nGwyrdd m\u00f4r, brithotor tir'''edd'''.<ref name=\":0\" />{{rp|16}}}}</poem>}}\n\n=== {{lang|cy|Englyn byr crwca}} ===\nThe short crooked {{lang|cy|englyn}}. This is like {{lang|cy|englyn penfyr}}, but orders the lines differently: seven syllables in the first, ten syllables (in two groups of five) in the second, and five to six syllables in the third. In the following example, the second line does not participate in the rhyme:\n{{quote|1=<poem>{{lang|cy|Ton tra thon toid tu t'''ir''';\nGoruchel gwaeddau rhag bron bannau bre;\nBraidd allan orsef'''ir'''.<ref name=\":0\" />{{rp|17}}}}</poem>}}\n\n=== {{lang|cy|Englyn unodl crwca}} ===\n\nThe crooked one-rhyme {{lang|cy|englyn}}. This {{lang|cy|englyn}} is like {{lang|cy|englyn byr crwca}}, except that it adds an extra seven-syllable line at the beginning. This is made up of four verses of seven, seven, ten and six syllables. The last syllables of the first, second and last verses and the seventh, eighth or ninth syllable of the third verse all rhyme.\n\n=== {{lang|cy|Englyn cyrch}} ===\n\nThe seeking {{lang|cy|englyn}}. This form has four verses of seven syllables each. The final syllables of the first, second, and last verse rhyme. The final syllable of the third verse rhymes with the second, third or fourth syllable of the last verse:\n{{quote|1=<poem>{{lang|cy|Caradawg fab Cedif'''or''',\nGwalch byddin gwerin gor'''or''',\nHebawg teulu cu ceinm<u>yn</u>,\nAnawdd genn<u>yn</u> dy hepg'''or'''.<ref name=\":0\" />{{rp|30}}}}</poem>}}\n\n=== {{lang|cy|Englyn proest dalgron}} ===\n\nIn this {{lang|cy|englyn}}, there are four seven-syllable verses that half-rhyme with each other (half-rhyme means that the final consonants agree).\n{{quote|1=<poem>{{lang|cy|Adeiliwyd bedd, gwedd gwiwd'''er''',\nF'enaid, i'th gylch o fyn'''or''':\nAdeiliawdd cof dy al'''ar'''\nI'm calon ddilon ddol'''ur'''.<ref name=\":0\" />{{rp|50}}}}</poem>}}\n\n=== {{lang|cy|Englyn lleddfbroest}} ===\n\nThis is identical to the {{lang|cy|englyn proest dalgron}} except that the half rhymes must use the {{lang|cy|ae}}, {{lang|cy|oe}}, {{lang|cy|wy}}, and {{lang|cy|ei}} [[diphthongs]].\n\n=== {{lang|cy|Englyn proest cadwynog}} ===\n\nThe [[chain rhyme|chain half-rhyme]] {{lang|cy|englyn}}. In this version there are four verses of seven syllables. The first and third verses rhyme and the second and fourth half rhyme on the same vowel sound as the full rhyme syllables.\n\n==={{lang|cy|Englyn proest cyfnewidiog}}===\n\nThe reciprocal half-rhyme {{lang|cy|englyn}}. This has four verses of seven syllables. All four verses half-rhyme, and there is additional ''cynghanedd''.\n\n==={{lang|cy|Englyn toddaid}}===\nThis is a hybrid between an {{lang|cy|englyn}} and a {{lang|cy|[[toddaid]]}}. The first two verses are as for an {{lang|cy|englyn}}, and there follow two more verses of ten syllables each.\n\n==={{lang|cy|Englyn cil-dwrn}}===\nAfter the first two verses there is just one more verse of three syllables or fewer, which follows the rhyme of the first two verses.\n\n=== Other forms ===\n\nThe novelist [[Robertson Davies]] once said that {{lang|cy|englynion}} were an old enthusiasm of his. He said that the form was derived by the Welsh from the inscriptions on Roman tombs in Wales. According to him, {{lang|cy|englynion}} must have four lines, the first one having ten syllables, then six, then the last two having seven syllables each. In the first line there must be a break after the seventh, eighth, or ninth syllable, and the rhyme with the second line comes at this break; but the tenth syllable of the first line must either rhyme or be in assonance with the middle of the second line. The last two lines must rhyme with the first rhyme in the first line, but the third or fourth line must rhyme on a weak syllable.<ref>Davies, \"Haiku and Englyn\", ''Toronto Daily Star'', 4 April 1959, in ''The Enthusiasms of Robertson Davies'', 1990.</ref>\n\n== Examples ==\n\nHere are two {{lang|cy|englynion}} by the twelfth-century Welsh poet [[Cynddelw Brydydd Mawr]]:\n\n{{quote|1=<poem>{{lang|cy|Balch ei fugunawr ban nafawr ei lef\nPan ganer cyrn cydawr;\nCorn Llywelyn llyw lluydfawr\nBon ehang blaen hang bloed fawr.\n\nCorn wedi llad corn llawen\nCorn llugynor Llywelyn\nCorn gwyd gwydr ai can\nCorn rueinell yn ol gellgwn}}</poem>}}\n\nHere is an English-language {{lang|cy|englyn}} by novelist [[Robertson Davies]].\n\n{{quote|1=<poem>The Old Journalist\nHe types his laboured column\u2014weary drudge!\nSenile, fudge and solemn;\nSpare, editor, to condemn\nThese dry leaves of his autumn.</poem>}}\n\nGrace in the form of an {{lang|cy|englyn}} (with {{lang|cy|cynghanedd}} shown) in a poem by W. D. Williams<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lowrihafcooke.wordpress.com/2013/02/06/adolygiad-ffilm-the-last-days-of-dolwyn-pg/|title=Adolygiad Ffilm: The Last Days of Dolwyn (PG)|last=lowrihafcooke|date=2013-02-06|website=Lowri Haf Cooke|language=cy|access-date=2019-06-18}}</ref>:\n\n{{block quote|1=<poem>\n{{lang|cy|O, Dad, yn deulu dedwydd \u2013 y deuwn}} [{{lang|cy|Dad}} and {{lang|cy|dedwydd}}, ''d''&lt;accent&gt;''d'' repeated]\n{{lang|cy|\u00c2 diolch o newydd}}, [{{lang|cy|deuwn}} and {{lang|cy|diolch}}, ''d''&lt;accent&gt; repeated]\n{{lang|cy|Cans o'th law y daw bob dydd}} [{{lang|cy|law}} and {{lang|cy|daw}} rhyming, {{lang|cy|daw}} and {{lang|cy|dydd}}, ''d''&lt;accent&gt; repeated, {{lang|cy|cynghanedd sain}}]\n{{lang|cy|Ein lluniaeth a'n llawenydd.}} [{{lang|cy|ein lluniaeth}} and {{lang|cy|a'n llawenydd}}, ''ll''&lt;accent&gt;''n'' repeated]</poem>}}\n\n{{block quote|1=<poem>O, Father, as a happy family \u2013 we come\nWith thanks anew,\nFor from your hand comes every day\nOur sustenance and our joy.</poem>|sign=|source=}}\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Cornwall|Wales}}\n* ''[[Englynion y Beddau]]''\n* ''[[Englynion y Clywaid]]''\n* [[Cerdd dafod]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n*{{citation|last=Rhys|first=John|authorlink=John Rhys|year=1905|editor-last=Evans|editor-first=E. Vincent|contribution=The Origin of the Welsh Englyn and Kindred Metres|title=Y Cymmrodor|volume=XVIII|publisher=Honourable Society of Cymmrodorion|publication-date=1905|publication-place=|pages=1\u2013185|url=https://archive.org/stream/ycymmrodor18cymmuoft}}\n\n{{Wiktionary}}\n\n[[Category:Cornish culture]]\n[[Category:Stanzaic form]]\n[[Category:Welsh poetry]]\n", "text_old": "{{Italic title}}\n[[File:Eglwys Crist, y Bala Christ Church, Bala, Gwynedd North Wales 24.JPG|thumb|An englyn on a gravestone in [[Christ Church, Bala]]:<br />''Price anwyl, pur ei wasanaeth...'']]\n'''{{lang|cy|Englyn}}''' ({{IPA-cy|\u02c8\u025b\u014b.l\u026an|pron}}; plural {{lang|cy|englynion}}) is a traditional [[Welsh language|Welsh]] and [[Cornish language|Cornish]] short [[Poetry|poem]] form. It uses [[Meter (poetry)|quantitative metres]], involving the counting of [[syllable]]s, and rigid patterns of [[rhyme]] and [[half rhyme]]. Each line contains a repeating pattern of consonants and accent known as {{lang|cy|[[cynghanedd]]}}.\n\n==Early history==\n\nThe {{lang|cy|englyn}} is found in the work of the earliest attested Welsh poets (the {{lang|cy|[[cynfeirdd]]}}), where the main types are the three-line {{lang|cy|englyn milwr}} and {{lang|cy|englyn penfyr}}.<ref>Rowland, Jenny, ''Early Welsh Saga Poetry: A Study and Edition of the ''Englynion''<nowiki />'' (Cambridge: Brewer, 1990), p. 305.</ref> It is the only set stanzaic metre found in the early Welsh poetic corpus, and explanations for its origins have tended to focus on stanzaic Latin poetry and hymns; however, it is as likely to be a development within the Brittonic poetic tradition.<ref>Rowland, Jenny, ''Early Welsh Saga Poetry: A Study and Edition of the ''Englynion''<nowiki />'' (Cambridge: Brewer, 1990), pp. 305-8.</ref> Whereas the metrical rules of later {{lang|cy|englynion}} are clear (and are based on counting syllables), the precise metre of the early {{lang|cy|englynion}} is debated and could have involved stress-counting.<ref>Rowland, Jenny, ''Early Welsh Saga Poetry: A Study and Edition of the ''Englynion''<nowiki />'' (Cambridge: Brewer, 1990), pp. 308-32.</ref> The earliest {{lang|cy|englynion}} are found as [[marginalia]] written in a tenth-century hand in the [[Juvencus Manuscript]].<ref>''A Selection of Early Welsh Saga Poems'', ed. by Jenny Rowland (London: Modern Humanities Research Association, 2014), p. xxvi.</ref> Many early {{lang|cy|englynion}} form poems which seem to represent moments of characters' emotional reflection in stories now lost: {{lang|cy|[[Canu Llywarch Hen]]}}, {{lang|cy|[[Canu Urien]]}}, {{lang|cy|[[Canu Heledd]]}}. Others survey heroic tradition, for example the {{lang|cy|[[Englynion y Beddau]]}} or ''[[Geraint son of Erbin]]'', and others again are lyric, religious meditations and laments such as the famous {{lang|cy|[[Claf Abercuawg]]}} and {{lang|cy|[[Kyntaw geir]]}}.\n\n== Types of {{lang|cy|englynion}}==\n\nThere are a number of types of {{lang|cy|englynion}}. Details of their structures are as follows; not all of these, however, are included in the [[Traditional Welsh poetic metres]].\n\n=== {{lang|cy|Englyn penfyr}} ===\n\nAlso known as the short-ended {{lang|cy|englyn}}. It consists of a stanza of three verses. The first verse has ten syllables (in two groups of five), the second has five to six; and the third has seven. The seventh, eighth or ninth syllable of the first verse introduces the rhyme and this is repeated on the last syllable of the other two verses. The fourth syllable of the second verse may echo the final syllable of the first through either rhyme or [[Literary consonance|consonance]].\n{{quote|1=<poem>{{lang|cy|Oer gwly pysgawd yng nghysg'''awd''' i\u00e4en;\nCul hydd, cawn barf'''awd''';\nByr diwedydd, gw\u0177dd gwyr'''awd'''.<ref name=\":0\">''[[iarchive:oxfordbookofwels00parr|The Oxford Book of Welsh Verse]]'', ed. by Thomas Parry (Oxford: Clarendon Press, 1962).</ref>{{rp|17}}}}</poem>}}\n\n=== {{lang|cy|Englyn unodl union}} ===\nThe straight one-rhymed {{lang|cy|englyn}}, identical to {{lang|cy|englyn penfyr}} except that it addes a fourth, rhyming, seven-syllable line at the end. Thus it consists of four verses of ten, six, seven and seven syllables. The seventh, eighth or ninth syllable of the first verse introduces the rhyme and this is repeated on the last syllable of the other three verses. The part of the first verse after the rhyme alliterates with the first part of the second verse.\n\nThis is an {{lang|cy|englyn unodl union}} by Alan Llwyd:\n\n{{quote|1=<poem>{{lang|cy|Ym Mhorth oer y Merthyr'''on''' \u2013 y merthyr\nMwya'i werth o ddig'''on'''\nA hir-fawrha y fro h'''on'''\nWr dewr o Aberdar'''on'''}}</poem>}}\n\n=== {{lang|cy|Englyn milwr}} ===\n\nThe soldier's {{lang|cy|englyn}}. This consists of three seven-syllable verses. All three verses rhyme.\n{{quote|1=<poem>{{lang|cy|Otid eiry, gwyn y cn'''es''';\nNid \u00e2 cedwyr i'w neg'''es''';\nOer llynnau, eu lliw heb d'''es'''.<ref name=\":0\" />{{rp|17}}}}</poem>}}\n\n=== {{lang|cy|Englyn gwastad}} ===\nThe even {{lang|cy|englyn}}, more common in the Middle Ages than later. This is identical to {{lang|cy|englyn milwr}} except that it has four lines. One example (showing the half-rhyme of -''edd'' with -''er'') is:\n{{quote|1=<poem>{{lang|cy|Cyntefin ceinaf ams'''er''',\nDydar adar, glas call'''edd''',\nEreidr yn rhych, ych yng ngw'''edd''',\nGwyrdd m\u00f4r, brithotor tir'''edd'''.<ref name=\":0\" />{{rp|16}}}}</poem>}}\n\n=== {{lang|cy|Englyn byr crwca}} ===\nThe short crooked {{lang|cy|englyn}}. This is like {{lang|cy|englyn penfyr}}, but orders the lines differently: seven syllables in the first, ten syllables (in two groups of five) in the second, and five to six syllables in the third. In the following example, the second line does not participate in the rhyme:\n{{quote|1=<poem>{{lang|cy|Ton tra thon toid tu t'''ir''';\nGoruchel gwaeddau rhag bron bannau bre;\nBraidd allan orsef'''ir'''.<ref name=\":0\" />{{rp|17}}}}</poem>}}\n\n=== {{lang|cy|Englyn unodl crwca}} ===\n\nThe crooked one-rhyme {{lang|cy|englyn}}. This {{lang|cy|englyn}} is like {{lang|cy|englyn byr crwca}}, except that it adds an extra seven-syllable line at the beginning. This is made up of four verses of seven, seven, ten and six syllables. The last syllables of the first, second and last verses and the seventh, eighth or ninth syllable of the third verse all rhyme.\n\n=== {{lang|cy|Englyn cyrch}} ===\n\nThe seeking {{lang|cy|englyn}}. This form has four verses of seven syllables each. The final syllables of the first, second, and last verse rhyme. The final syllable of the third verse rhymes with the second, third or fourth syllable of the last verse:\n{{quote|1=<poem>{{lang|cy|Caradawg fab Cedif'''or''',\nGwalch byddin gwerin gor'''or''',\nHebawg teulu cu ceinm<u>yn</u>,\nAnawdd genn<u>yn</u> dy hepg'''or'''.<ref name=\":0\" />{{rp|30}}}}</poem>}}\n\n=== {{lang|cy|Englyn proest dalgron}} ===\n\nIn this {{lang|cy|englyn}}, there are four seven-syllable verses that half-rhyme with each other (half-rhyme means that the final consonants agree).\n{{quote|1=<poem>{{lang|cy|Adeiliwyd bedd, gwedd gwiwd'''er''',\nF'enaid, i'th gylch o fyn'''or''':\nAdeiliawdd cof dy al'''ar'''\nI'm calon ddilon ddol'''ur'''.<ref name=\":0\" />{{rp|50}}}}</poem>}}\n\n=== {{lang|cy|Englyn lleddfbroest}} ===\n\nThis is identical to the {{lang|cy|englyn proest dalgron}} except that the half rhymes must use the {{lang|cy|ae}}, {{lang|cy|oe}}, {{lang|cy|wy}}, and {{lang|cy|ei}} [[diphthongs]].\n\n=== {{lang|cy|Englyn proest cadwynog}} ===\n\nThe [[chain rhyme|chain half-rhyme]] {{lang|cy|englyn}}. In this version there are four verses of seven syllables. The first and third verses rhyme and the second and fourth half rhyme on the same vowel sound as the full rhyme syllables.\n\n==={{lang|cy|Englyn proest cyfnewidiog}}===\n\nThe reciprocal half-rhyme {{lang|cy|englyn}}. This has four verses of seven syllables. All four verses half-rhyme, and there is additional ''cynghanedd''.\n\n==={{lang|cy|Englyn toddaid}}===\nThis is a hybrid between an {{lang|cy|englyn}} and a {{lang|cy|[[toddaid]]}}. The first two verses are as for an {{lang|cy|englyn}}, and there follow two more verses of ten syllables each.\n\n==={{lang|cy|Englyn cil-dwrn}}===\nAfter the first two verses there is just one more verse of three syllables or fewer, which follows the rhyme of the first two verses.\n\n=== Other forms ===\n\nThe novelist [[Robertson Davies]] once said that {{lang|cy|englynion}} were an old enthusiasm of his. He said that the form was derived by the Welsh from the inscriptions on Roman tombs in Wales. According to him, {{lang|cy|englynion}} must have four lines, the first one having ten syllables, then six, then the last two having seven syllables each. In the first line there must be a break after the seventh, eighth, or ninth syllable, and the rhyme with the second line comes at this break; but the tenth syllable of the first line must either rhyme or be in assonance with the middle of the second line. The last two lines must rhyme with the first rhyme in the first line, but the third or fourth line must rhyme on a weak syllable.<ref>Davies, \"Haiku and Englyn\", ''Toronto Daily Star'', 4 April 1959, in ''The Enthusiasms of Robertson Davies'', 1990.</ref>\n\n== Examples ==\n\nHere are two {{lang|cy|englynion}} by the twelfth-century Welsh poet [[Cynddelw Brydydd Mawr]]:\n\n{{quote|1=<poem>{{lang|cy|Balch ei fugunawr ban nafawr ei lef\nPan ganer cyrn cydawr;\nCorn Llywelyn llyw lluydfawr\nBon ehang blaen hang bloed fawr.\n\nCorn wedi llad corn llawen\nCorn llugynor Llywelyn\nCorn gwyd gwydr ai can\nCorn rueinell yn ol gellgwn}}</poem>}}\n\nHere is an English-language {{lang|cy|englyn}} by novelist [[Robertson Davies]].\n\n{{quote|1=<poem>The Old Journalist\nHe types his laboured column\u2014weary drudge!\nSenile, fudge and solemn;\nSpare, editor, to condemn\nThese dry leaves of his autumn.</poem>}}\n\nGrace in the form of an {{lang|cy|englyn}} (with {{lang|cy|cynghanedd}} shown) in a poem by W. D. Williams<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lowrihafcooke.wordpress.com/2013/02/06/adolygiad-ffilm-the-last-days-of-dolwyn-pg/|title=Adolygiad Ffilm: The Last Days of Dolwyn (PG)|last=lowrihafcooke|date=2013-02-06|website=Lowri Haf Cooke|language=cy|access-date=2019-06-18}}</ref>:\n\n{{block quote|1=<poem>\n{{lang|cy|O, Dad, yn deulu dedwydd \u2013 y deuwn}} [{{lang|cy|Dad}} and {{lang|cy|dedwydd}}, ''d''&lt;accent&gt;''d'' repeated]\n{{lang|cy|\u00c2 diolch o newydd}}, [{{lang|cy|deuwn}} and {{lang|cy|diolch}}, ''d''&lt;accent&gt; repeated]\n{{lang|cy|Cans o'th law y daw bob dydd}} [{{lang|cy|law}} and {{lang|cy|daw}} rhyming, {{lang|cy|daw}} and {{lang|cy|dydd}}, ''d''&lt;accent&gt; repeated, {{lang|cy|cynghanedd sain}}]\n{{lang|cy|Ein lluniaeth a'n llawenydd.}} [{{lang|cy|ein lluniaeth}} and {{lang|cy|a'n llawenydd}}, ''ll''&lt;accent&gt;''n'' repeated]</poem>}}\n\n{{block quote|1=<poem>O, Father, as a happy family \u2013 we come\nWith thanks anew,\nFor from your hand comes every day\nOur sustenance and our joy.</poem>|sign=|source=}}\n\n== See also ==\n* ''[[Englynion y Beddau]]''\n* ''[[Englynion y Clywaid]]''\n* [[Cerdd dafod]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n*{{citation|last=Rhys|first=John|authorlink=John Rhys|year=1905|editor-last=Evans|editor-first=E. Vincent|contribution=The Origin of the Welsh Englyn and Kindred Metres|title=Y Cymmrodor|volume=XVIII|publisher=Honourable Society of Cymmrodorion|publication-date=1905|publication-place=|pages=1\u2013185|url=https://archive.org/stream/ycymmrodor18cymmuoft}}\n\n{{Wiktionary}}\n\n[[Category:Cornish culture]]\n[[Category:Stanzaic form]]\n[[Category:Welsh poetry]]\n", "name_user": "Gazamp", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSee also:AddedPortal:Cornwall", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Englyn"}
{"title_page": "Xi Jinping Thought", "text_new": "{{short description|Set of policies and ideals}}\n<noinclude>{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2017}}\n{{use British English|date=October 2017}}\n</noinclude>\n{{Infobox Chinese\n|title=Xi Jinping Thought on Socialism<br />with Chinese Characteristics<br />for a New Era\n|pic=A political slogan on the wall in Longhua District, Shenzhen, Guangdong, China, picture1.jpg\n|piccap=A billboard advertising Xi Jinping Thought in [[Shenzhen]], [[Guangdong]] with the insignia of the [[Communist Party of China]] affixed.\n|picsize=\n|order=st\n|s=\u4e60\u8fd1\u5e73\u65b0\u65f6\u4ee3\u4e2d\u56fd\u7279\u8272\u793e\u4f1a\u4e3b\u4e49\u601d\u60f3\n|t=\u7fd2\u8fd1\u5e73\u65b0\u6642\u4ee3\u4e2d\u570b\u7279\u8272\u793e\u6703\u4e3b\u7fa9\u601d\u60f3\n|p=X\u00ed J\u00ecnp\u00edng x\u012bn sh\u00edd\u00e0i zh\u014dnggu\u00f3 t\u00e8s\u00e8 sh\u00e8hu\u00ec zh\u01d4y\u00ec s\u012bxi\u01ceng\n|mi=\n}}\n{{Politics of China|expanded=Ideology}}\n{{Xi Jinping sidebar}}\n'''Xi Jinping Thought on Socialism with Chinese Characteristics for a New Era''', simply known as '''The Xi Jinping Thought''',{{NoteTag|Also known as '''Xi Thought'''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.voanews.com/east-asia-pacific/chinas-netizens-push-back-xi-thought|title=China's Netizens Push Back on 'Xi Thought'|website=Voice of America|language=en|access-date=2019-08-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.chinadaily.com.cn/a/201811/23/WS5bf794dda310eff30328aae6.html|title=Courseware on Xi thought launched - Chinadaily.com.cn|last=\u6c5f\u5dcd|website=www.chinadaily.com.cn|access-date=2019-08-01}}</ref> or '''Xism'''.<ref>[http://www.china.org.cn/opinion/2015-04/15/content_35325730.htm 'Four Comprehensives' pillars of Xism]</ref>}}<ref>{{cite news|last1=Phillips|first1=Tom|title=Xi Jinping Thought to be taught in China's universities|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/oct/27/xi-jinping-thought-to-be-taught-in-chinas-universities|accessdate=23 November 2017|newspaper=The Guardian|date=27 October 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171122234138/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/oct/27/xi-jinping-thought-to-be-taught-in-chinas-universities|archivedate=22 November 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Buckley|first1=Chris|title=China Enshrines 'Xi Jinping Thought,' Elevating Leader to Mao-Like Status|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/10/24/world/asia/china-xi-jinping-communist-party.html|accessdate=23 November 2017|newspaper=The New York Times|date=24 October 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171122135305/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/10/24/world/asia/china-xi-jinping-communist-party.html|archivedate=22 November 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> is a set of policies and ideals derived from the [[General Secretary of the Communist Party of China|Chinese Communist Party General Secretary]] [[Xi Jinping]]. It was first officially mentioned at the [[19th National Congress of the Communist Party of China]], in which it was incorporated into the [[Constitution of the Communist Party of China|constitution of the CCP]].\n\n== History ==\nThe first official mention of the term was at the [[19th National Congress of the Communist Party of China]] and it has gradually been developed since 2012 after the master Xi became General Secretary of the Communist Party of China ([[China]]'s [[paramount leader]]).<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/10/25/world/asia/china-xi-jinping-titles-chairman.html|title=China's 'Chairman of Everything': Behind Xi Jinping's Many Titles|date=25 October 2017|newspaper=The New York Times|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171026043525/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/10/25/world/asia/china-xi-jinping-titles-chairman.html|archivedate=26 October 2017|quote=Mr. Xi's most important title is general secretary, the most powerful position in the Communist Party. In China's one-party system, this ranking gives him virtually unchecked authority over the government|df=dmy-all}}.</ref> Some news sources have stated that Xi helped create this ideology together with his close advisor [[Wang Huning]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/11/13/world/asia/china-xi-jinping-wang-huning.html|title=Behind the Scenes, Communist Strategist Presses China\u2019s Rise|last=Perlez|first=Jane|date=2017-11-13|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-01-09|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/china/2017/11/02/the-meaning-of-the-man-behind-chinas-ideology|title=The meaning of the man behind China\u2019s ideology, The meaning of the man behind China\u2019s ideology|work=The Economist|access-date=2020-01-09|issn=0013-0613}}</ref>\n\nThe 19th Congress affirmed the [[ideology]] as a guiding political and military ideology of the [[Communist Party of China]] (CCP)<ref name=\"xithought\">{{cite news|url=http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2017-10/19/c_136689808.htm|title=CPC creates Xi Jinping Thought on Socialism with Chinese Characteristics for a New Era|last1=Zhang|first1=Ling|date=18 October 2017|work=[[Xinhua]]|accessdate=19 October 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171018195301/http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2017-10/19/c_136689808.htm|archivedate=18 October 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and approved the incorporation of the ideology into the [[Constitution of the Communist Party of China]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/oct/24/xi-jinping-mao-thought-on-socialism-china-constitution|title=Xi Jinping becomes most powerful leader since Mao with China's change to constitution|last=Phillips|first=Tom|date=24 October 2017|work=The Guardian|accessdate=24 October 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171024053607/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/oct/24/xi-jinping-mao-thought-on-socialism-china-constitution|archivedate=24 October 2017|issn=0261-3077|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/special/19cpcnc/index.htm|title=Xi presents new CPC central leadership, roadmap for next 5 years|date=24 October 2017|work=[[Xinhua]]|accessdate=24 October 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171025081807/http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/special/19cpcnc/index.htm|archivedate=25 October 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The affirmation received unanimous support as every delegate voted to approve by raising hands when Xi asked their opinions on the Congress.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-china-41734362|title=Xi Jinping asks party congress if anyone opposes...Xi Jinping|publisher=BBC|accessdate=28 October 2017}}</ref> The incorporation made Xi the third Chinese leader after [[Mao Zedong]] and [[Deng Xiaoping]] whose names appeared in the list of fundamental doctrines of the CCP, which raised Xi above his two most recent predecessors, former General Secretaries [[Hu Jintao]] and [[Jiang Zemin]]. In his report, Xi promised to make China strong, propelling the country into a \"new era\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://nyti.ms/2zBJ8pF|title=China Enshrines 'Xi Jinping Thought,' Elevating Leader to Mao-Like Status|last1=Buckley|first1=Chris|date=24 October 2017|newspaper=New York Times}}</ref>\n\nXi first made mention of the ''Thought on Socialism with Chinese Characteristics for a New Era'' in the opening day speech delivered to the 19th Party Congress in October 2017. In reviews of Xi's keynote address at the Congress, Xi's [[Politburo Standing Committee of the Communist Party of China|Politburo Standing Committee]] (top decision-making body) colleagues prepended the description with \"Xi Jinping\".<ref name=\"xithought\" />\n\nXi has described the thought as part of the broad framework created around [[socialism with Chinese characteristics]], a term coined by Deng Xiaoping, which places China in the \"[[primary stage of socialism]]\". In official party documentation and pronouncements by Xi's colleagues, the thought is said to be a continuation of [[Marxism\u2013Leninism]], [[Maoism|Mao Zedong Thought]], [[Deng Xiaoping Theory]], \"[[Three Represents|the important thought of the Three Represents]]\" and the [[Scientific Outlook on Development|scientific development perspective]] as part of a series of guiding ideologies that embody \"[[Ideology of the Communist Party of China|Marxism adapted to Chinese conditions]]\" and contemporary considerations.<ref name=\"xithought\" />\n\nDozens of Chinese universities have established research institutes for Xi Jinping Thought after the Congress dedicated to advocating the incorporation of Xi Jinping Thought in all aspects of daily life.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nz.news.yahoo.com/chinese-universities-start-apos-xi-064407660.html|title=Chinese universities start 'Xi Thought' institutes|date=30 October 2017|website=AFP|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107023000/https://nz.news.yahoo.com/chinese-universities-start-apos-xi-064407660.html|archivedate=7 November 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Academics such as [[Jiang Shigong]] have written expositions of Xi Jinping Thought.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thecpe.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/CPE_Reflections-on-Jiang-Shigong-on.pdf|title=Reflections on Jiang Shigong on 'Philosophy and History: Interpreting the \"Xi Jinping Era\" through Xi's Report to the Nineteenth National Congress of the CCP'|last=Backer|first=Larry Cat\u00e1|authorlink=Larry Cat\u00e1 Backer|date=June 2018|series=Working Papers|publisher=Coalition for Peace and Ethics|pages=1\u20132|accessdate=26 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe concepts behind Xi Jinping Thought are elaborated in Xi's ''[[The Governance of China]]'' book series, published by the [[Foreign Languages Press]] for an international audience. Volume one was published in September 2014, followed by volume two in November 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2017-11/07/c_136733705.htm|title=Second volume of Xi's book on governance published|website=news.xinhuanet.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171206143920/http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2017-11/07/c_136733705.htm|archivedate=6 December 2017|accessdate=6 December 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> \n\nOn 27 November, more than 100 of China's top filmmakers, actors and pop stars were gathered for a day in [[Hangzhou]] to study the report of the 19th Party Congress featuring Xi Jinping Thought.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/worldviews/wp/2017/12/01/china-sends-its-top-actors-and-directors-sent-back-to-socialism-school/|title=China sends its top actors and directors back to socialism school|date=1 December 2017|work=The Washington Post|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171207192406/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/worldviews/wp/2017/12/01/china-sends-its-top-actors-and-directors-sent-back-to-socialism-school/|archivedate=7 December 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2018, the carriages of a train in [[Changchun Metro]] were decked out in red and dozens of Xi's quotes to celebrate the 97th anniversary of Communist Party of China. The train was described as a \"highly condensed spiritual manual\" of Xi Jinping Thought by the local government.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.scmp.com/news/china/policies-politics/article/2153582/all-aboard-chinas-propaganda-express-xi-jinpings-new|title=All aboard the propaganda express for Xi Jinping's 'New Era'|last1=Gan|first1=Nectar|date=3 July 2018|work=South China Morning Post|accessdate=3 July 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180703113922/http://www.scmp.com/news/china/policies-politics/article/2153582/all-aboard-chinas-propaganda-express-xi-jinpings-new|archivedate=3 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2019, [[Alibaba Group]] released an app called ''[[Xuexi Qiangguo]]'' about studying Xi Jinping Thought.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://shanghai.ist/2019/02/15/chinas-hottest-app-is-all-about-making-users-study-xi-jinping-thought/|title=China's hottest app is all about making users study Xi Jinping Thought|date=2019-02-14|website=shanghaiist|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-25}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2019, [[Fudan University]] added content concerning the inculcation of teachers and students in Xi Jinping Thought into its charter, leading to protests about [[academic freedom]] among the students.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.asiatimes.com/2019/12/article/students-protest-at-shanghais-fudan-university/|title=Students protest at Shanghai's Fudan University|date=19 December 2019|website=[[Asia Times]]|accessdate=19 December 2019|quote=A video circulating this week showed students at Shanghai\u2019s Fudan University singing the school song \u2013 which extols \u201cacademic independence and freedom of thought\u201d \u2013 in an apparent protest.{...}Besides removing \u201cfreedom of thought,\u201d the ministry adds to the charter \u201carming the minds of teachers and students with Xi Jinping\u2019s new era of socialist ideology with Chinese characteristics.\u201d It also obliges faculty and students to adhere to \u201ccore socialist values\u201d and build a \u201charmonious\u201d campus environment \u2013 a code phrase for the elimination of anti-government sentiment.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cna.com.tw/news/firstnews/201912180210.aspx|date=18 December 2019|website=[[Central News Agency (Republic of China)|Central News Agency]]|language=zh-tw|script-title=zh:\u5fa9\u65e6\u5927\u5b78\u7ae0\u7a0b\u522a\u9664\u601d\u60f3\u81ea\u7531 \u5b78\u751f\u5531\u6821\u6b4c\u6297\u8b70\u8981\u6c42\u5b78\u8853\u7368\u7acb[\u5f71]|accessdate=19 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Content ==\nThe thought consists of a 14-point basic policy as follows:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/asia/east-asia/19th-party-congress-xi-jinping-outlines-new-thought-on-socialism-with-chinese-traits|title=19th Party Congress: Xi Jinping outlines new thought on socialism with Chinese traits|work=Straits Times|accessdate=28 October 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171026215205/http://www.straitstimes.com/asia/east-asia/19th-party-congress-xi-jinping-outlines-new-thought-on-socialism-with-chinese-traits|archivedate=26 October 2017|df=dmy-all|date=18 October 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=His own words: The 14 principles of 'Xi Jinping Thought'|url=https://monitoring.bbc.co.uk/product/c1dmwn4r|publisher=BBC Monitoring|accessdate=28 October 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171028152832/https://monitoring.bbc.co.uk/product/c1dmwn4r|archivedate=28 October 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n# Ensuring Communist Party of China leadership over all forms of work in China.\n# The Communist Party of China should take a people-centric approach for the public interest.\n# The continuation of \"comprehensive deepening of reforms\".\n# Adopting new science-based ideas for \"innovative, coordinated, green, open and shared development\".\n# Following \"[[socialism with Chinese characteristics]]\" with \"people as the masters of the country\".\n# Governing China with Rule of Law. \n# \"Practice [[Core Socialist Values|socialist core values]]\", including [[Marxism]], [[Communism#Marxist communism|communism]] and socialism with Chinese characteristics.\n# \"Improving people's livelihood and well-being is the primary goal of development\".\n# Coexist well with nature with \"energy conservation and environmental protection\" policies and \"contribute to global ecological safety\".\n# Strengthen [[National security of China|national security]].\n# The Communist Party of China should have \"absolute leadership over\" China's [[People's Liberation Army]].\n# Promoting the [[one country, two systems]] system for [[Hong Kong]] and [[Macau]] with a future of \"complete [[Chinese unification|national reunification]]\" and to follow the [[One-China policy]] and [[1992 Consensus]] for Taiwan.\n# Establish a common destiny between Chinese people and other people around the world with a \"peaceful international environment\".\n# Improve party discipline in the Communist Party of China.\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Community of shared future for mankind]]\n* [[Deng Xiaoping Theory]]\n* [[General Secretary Xi Jinping important speech series]]\n* [[Mao Zedong Thought]]\n* [[Scientific Outlook on Development]]\n* [[Three Represents]]\n* ''[[Xuexi Qiangguo]]''\n* [[Core Socialist Values]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{NoteFoot}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.edx.org/course/xi-jinpings-thought-on-socialism-with-chinese-characteristics-for-a-new-era Xi Jinping's Thought on Socialism with Chinese Characteristics for a New era]. A course on edX by Tsinghua University \n\n{{Xi Jinping}}\n{{Communism}}\n{{Portal bar|China|Politics|Communism}}\n{{Social and political philosophy}}\n{{Philosophy topics}}\n{{Chinese philosophy}}\n{{continental philosophy}}\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:Xi Jinping Thought]]\n[[Category:Xi Jinping]]\n[[Category:Ideology of the Communist Party of China]]\n[[Category:People's Republic of China culture]]\n[[Category:2010s establishments in China]]\n[[Category:2010s in China]]\n[[Category:Eponymous political ideologies]]\n[[Category:Contemporary Chinese philosophy]]\n[[Category:Marxism\u2013Leninism]]\n[[Category:Marxist schools of thought]]\n[[Category:Political history of China]]\n[[Category:Types of socialism]]\n[[Category:State ideologies]]\n[[Category:Chinese nationalism]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Set of policies and ideals}}\n<noinclude>{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2017}}\n{{use British English|date=October 2017}}\n</noinclude>\n{{Infobox Chinese\n|title=Xi Jinping Thought on Socialism<br />with Chinese Characteristics<br />for a New Era\n|pic=A political slogan on the wall in Longhua District, Shenzhen, Guangdong, China, picture1.jpg\n|piccap=A billboard advertising Xi Jinping Thought in [[Shenzhen]], [[Guangdong]] with the insignia of the [[Communist Party of China]] affixed.\n|picsize=\n|order=st\n|s=\u4e60\u8fd1\u5e73\u65b0\u65f6\u4ee3\u4e2d\u56fd\u7279\u8272\u793e\u4f1a\u4e3b\u4e49\u601d\u60f3\n|t=\u7fd2\u8fd1\u5e73\u65b0\u6642\u4ee3\u4e2d\u570b\u7279\u8272\u793e\u6703\u4e3b\u7fa9\u601d\u60f3\n|p=X\u00ed J\u00ecnp\u00edng x\u012bn sh\u00edd\u00e0i zh\u014dnggu\u00f3 t\u00e8s\u00e8 sh\u00e8hu\u00ec zh\u01d4y\u00ec s\u012bxi\u01ceng\n|mi=\n}}\n{{Politics of China|expanded=Ideology}}\n{{Xi Jinping sidebar}}\n'''Xi Jinping Thought on Socialism with Chinese Characteristics for a New Era''', simply known as '''The Xi Jinping Thought''',{{NoteTag|Also known as '''Xi Thought'''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.voanews.com/east-asia-pacific/chinas-netizens-push-back-xi-thought|title=China's Netizens Push Back on 'Xi Thought'|website=Voice of America|language=en|access-date=2019-08-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.chinadaily.com.cn/a/201811/23/WS5bf794dda310eff30328aae6.html|title=Courseware on Xi thought launched - Chinadaily.com.cn|last=\u6c5f\u5dcd|website=www.chinadaily.com.cn|access-date=2019-08-01}}</ref> or '''Xism'''.<ref>[http://www.china.org.cn/opinion/2015-04/15/content_35325730.htm 'Four Comprehensives' pillars of Xism]</ref>}}<ref>{{cite news|last1=Phillips|first1=Tom|title=Xi Jinping Thought to be taught in China's universities|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/oct/27/xi-jinping-thought-to-be-taught-in-chinas-universities|accessdate=23 November 2017|newspaper=The Guardian|date=27 October 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171122234138/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/oct/27/xi-jinping-thought-to-be-taught-in-chinas-universities|archivedate=22 November 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Buckley|first1=Chris|title=China Enshrines 'Xi Jinping Thought,' Elevating Leader to Mao-Like Status|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/10/24/world/asia/china-xi-jinping-communist-party.html|accessdate=23 November 2017|newspaper=The New York Times|date=24 October 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171122135305/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/10/24/world/asia/china-xi-jinping-communist-party.html|archivedate=22 November 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> is a set of policies and ideals derived from the [[General Secretary of the Communist Party of China|Chinese Communist Party General Secretary]] [[Xi Jinping]]. Xi Jinping Thought was first officially mentioned at the [[19th National Congress of the Communist Party of China]], in which it was incorporated into the [[Constitution of the Communist Party of China|constitution of the CCP]].\n\n== History ==\nThe first official mention of the term was at the [[19th National Congress of the Communist Party of China]] and it has gradually been developed since 2012 after the master Xi became General Secretary of the Communist Party of China ([[China]]'s [[paramount leader]]).<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/10/25/world/asia/china-xi-jinping-titles-chairman.html|title=China's 'Chairman of Everything': Behind Xi Jinping's Many Titles|date=25 October 2017|newspaper=The New York Times|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171026043525/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/10/25/world/asia/china-xi-jinping-titles-chairman.html|archivedate=26 October 2017|quote=Mr. Xi's most important title is general secretary, the most powerful position in the Communist Party. In China's one-party system, this ranking gives him virtually unchecked authority over the government|df=dmy-all}}.</ref> Some news sources have stated that Xi helped create this ideology together with his close advisor [[Wang Huning]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/11/13/world/asia/china-xi-jinping-wang-huning.html|title=Behind the Scenes, Communist Strategist Presses China\u2019s Rise|last=Perlez|first=Jane|date=2017-11-13|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-01-09|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/china/2017/11/02/the-meaning-of-the-man-behind-chinas-ideology|title=The meaning of the man behind China\u2019s ideology, The meaning of the man behind China\u2019s ideology|work=The Economist|access-date=2020-01-09|issn=0013-0613}}</ref>\n\nThe 19th Congress affirmed the [[ideology]] as a guiding political and military ideology of the [[Communist Party of China]] (CCP)<ref name=\"xithought\">{{cite news|url=http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2017-10/19/c_136689808.htm|title=CPC creates Xi Jinping Thought on Socialism with Chinese Characteristics for a New Era|last1=Zhang|first1=Ling|date=18 October 2017|work=[[Xinhua]]|accessdate=19 October 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171018195301/http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2017-10/19/c_136689808.htm|archivedate=18 October 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and approved the incorporation of the ideology into the [[Constitution of the Communist Party of China]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/oct/24/xi-jinping-mao-thought-on-socialism-china-constitution|title=Xi Jinping becomes most powerful leader since Mao with China's change to constitution|last=Phillips|first=Tom|date=24 October 2017|work=The Guardian|accessdate=24 October 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171024053607/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/oct/24/xi-jinping-mao-thought-on-socialism-china-constitution|archivedate=24 October 2017|issn=0261-3077|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/special/19cpcnc/index.htm|title=Xi presents new CPC central leadership, roadmap for next 5 years|date=24 October 2017|work=[[Xinhua]]|accessdate=24 October 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171025081807/http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/special/19cpcnc/index.htm|archivedate=25 October 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The affirmation received unanimous support as every delegate voted to approve by raising hands when Xi asked their opinions on the Congress.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-china-41734362|title=Xi Jinping asks party congress if anyone opposes...Xi Jinping|publisher=BBC|accessdate=28 October 2017}}</ref> The incorporation made Xi the third Chinese leader after [[Mao Zedong]] and [[Deng Xiaoping]] whose names appeared in the list of fundamental doctrines of the CCP, which raised Xi above his two most recent predecessors, former General Secretaries [[Hu Jintao]] and [[Jiang Zemin]]. In his report, Xi promised to make China strong, propelling the country into a \"new era\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://nyti.ms/2zBJ8pF|title=China Enshrines 'Xi Jinping Thought,' Elevating Leader to Mao-Like Status|last1=Buckley|first1=Chris|date=24 October 2017|newspaper=New York Times}}</ref>\n\nXi first made mention of the ''Thought on Socialism with Chinese Characteristics for a New Era'' in the opening day speech delivered to the 19th Party Congress in October 2017. In reviews of Xi's keynote address at the Congress, Xi's [[Politburo Standing Committee of the Communist Party of China|Politburo Standing Committee]] (top decision-making body) colleagues prepended the description with \"Xi Jinping\".<ref name=\"xithought\" />\n\nXi has described the thought as part of the broad framework created around [[socialism with Chinese characteristics]], a term coined by Deng Xiaoping, which places China in the \"[[primary stage of socialism]]\". In official party documentation and pronouncements by Xi's colleagues, the thought is said to be a continuation of [[Marxism\u2013Leninism]], [[Maoism|Mao Zedong Thought]], [[Deng Xiaoping Theory]], \"[[Three Represents|the important thought of the Three Represents]]\" and the [[Scientific Outlook on Development|scientific development perspective]] as part of a series of guiding ideologies that embody \"[[Ideology of the Communist Party of China|Marxism adapted to Chinese conditions]]\" and contemporary considerations.<ref name=\"xithought\" />\n\nDozens of Chinese universities have established research institutes for Xi Jinping Thought after the Congress dedicated to advocating the incorporation of Xi Jinping Thought in all aspects of daily life.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nz.news.yahoo.com/chinese-universities-start-apos-xi-064407660.html|title=Chinese universities start 'Xi Thought' institutes|date=30 October 2017|website=AFP|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107023000/https://nz.news.yahoo.com/chinese-universities-start-apos-xi-064407660.html|archivedate=7 November 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Academics such as [[Jiang Shigong]] have written expositions of Xi Jinping Thought.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thecpe.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/CPE_Reflections-on-Jiang-Shigong-on.pdf|title=Reflections on Jiang Shigong on 'Philosophy and History: Interpreting the \"Xi Jinping Era\" through Xi's Report to the Nineteenth National Congress of the CCP'|last=Backer|first=Larry Cat\u00e1|authorlink=Larry Cat\u00e1 Backer|date=June 2018|series=Working Papers|publisher=Coalition for Peace and Ethics|pages=1\u20132|accessdate=26 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe concepts behind Xi Jinping Thought are elaborated in Xi's ''[[The Governance of China]]'' book series, published by the [[Foreign Languages Press]] for an international audience. Volume one was published in September 2014, followed by volume two in November 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2017-11/07/c_136733705.htm|title=Second volume of Xi's book on governance published|website=news.xinhuanet.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171206143920/http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2017-11/07/c_136733705.htm|archivedate=6 December 2017|accessdate=6 December 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> \n\nOn 27 November, more than 100 of China's top filmmakers, actors and pop stars were gathered for a day in [[Hangzhou]] to study the report of the 19th Party Congress featuring Xi Jinping Thought.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/worldviews/wp/2017/12/01/china-sends-its-top-actors-and-directors-sent-back-to-socialism-school/|title=China sends its top actors and directors back to socialism school|date=1 December 2017|work=The Washington Post|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171207192406/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/worldviews/wp/2017/12/01/china-sends-its-top-actors-and-directors-sent-back-to-socialism-school/|archivedate=7 December 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2018, the carriages of a train in [[Changchun Metro]] were decked out in red and dozens of Xi's quotes to celebrate the 97th anniversary of Communist Party of China. The train was described as a \"highly condensed spiritual manual\" of Xi Jinping Thought by the local government.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.scmp.com/news/china/policies-politics/article/2153582/all-aboard-chinas-propaganda-express-xi-jinpings-new|title=All aboard the propaganda express for Xi Jinping's 'New Era'|last1=Gan|first1=Nectar|date=3 July 2018|work=South China Morning Post|accessdate=3 July 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180703113922/http://www.scmp.com/news/china/policies-politics/article/2153582/all-aboard-chinas-propaganda-express-xi-jinpings-new|archivedate=3 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2019, [[Alibaba Group]] released an app called ''[[Xuexi Qiangguo]]'' about studying Xi Jinping Thought.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://shanghai.ist/2019/02/15/chinas-hottest-app-is-all-about-making-users-study-xi-jinping-thought/|title=China's hottest app is all about making users study Xi Jinping Thought|date=2019-02-14|website=shanghaiist|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-25}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2019, [[Fudan University]] added content concerning the inculcation of teachers and students in Xi Jinping Thought into its charter, leading to protests about [[academic freedom]] among the students.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.asiatimes.com/2019/12/article/students-protest-at-shanghais-fudan-university/|title=Students protest at Shanghai's Fudan University|date=19 December 2019|website=[[Asia Times]]|accessdate=19 December 2019|quote=A video circulating this week showed students at Shanghai\u2019s Fudan University singing the school song \u2013 which extols \u201cacademic independence and freedom of thought\u201d \u2013 in an apparent protest.{...}Besides removing \u201cfreedom of thought,\u201d the ministry adds to the charter \u201carming the minds of teachers and students with Xi Jinping\u2019s new era of socialist ideology with Chinese characteristics.\u201d It also obliges faculty and students to adhere to \u201ccore socialist values\u201d and build a \u201charmonious\u201d campus environment \u2013 a code phrase for the elimination of anti-government sentiment.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cna.com.tw/news/firstnews/201912180210.aspx|date=18 December 2019|website=[[Central News Agency (Republic of China)|Central News Agency]]|language=zh-tw|script-title=zh:\u5fa9\u65e6\u5927\u5b78\u7ae0\u7a0b\u522a\u9664\u601d\u60f3\u81ea\u7531 \u5b78\u751f\u5531\u6821\u6b4c\u6297\u8b70\u8981\u6c42\u5b78\u8853\u7368\u7acb[\u5f71]|accessdate=19 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Content ==\nThe thought consists of a 14-point basic policy as follows:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/asia/east-asia/19th-party-congress-xi-jinping-outlines-new-thought-on-socialism-with-chinese-traits|title=19th Party Congress: Xi Jinping outlines new thought on socialism with Chinese traits|work=Straits Times|accessdate=28 October 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171026215205/http://www.straitstimes.com/asia/east-asia/19th-party-congress-xi-jinping-outlines-new-thought-on-socialism-with-chinese-traits|archivedate=26 October 2017|df=dmy-all|date=18 October 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=His own words: The 14 principles of 'Xi Jinping Thought'|url=https://monitoring.bbc.co.uk/product/c1dmwn4r|publisher=BBC Monitoring|accessdate=28 October 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171028152832/https://monitoring.bbc.co.uk/product/c1dmwn4r|archivedate=28 October 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n# Ensuring Communist Party of China leadership over all forms of work in China.\n# The Communist Party of China should take a people-centric approach for the public interest.\n# The continuation of \"comprehensive deepening of reforms\".\n# Adopting new science-based ideas for \"innovative, coordinated, green, open and shared development\".\n# Following \"[[socialism with Chinese characteristics]]\" with \"people as the masters of the country\".\n# Governing China with Rule of Law. \n# \"Practice [[Core Socialist Values|socialist core values]]\", including [[Marxism]], [[Communism#Marxist communism|communism]] and socialism with Chinese characteristics.\n# \"Improving people's livelihood and well-being is the primary goal of development\".\n# Coexist well with nature with \"energy conservation and environmental protection\" policies and \"contribute to global ecological safety\".\n# Strengthen [[National security of China|national security]].\n# The Communist Party of China should have \"absolute leadership over\" China's [[People's Liberation Army]].\n# Promoting the [[one country, two systems]] system for [[Hong Kong]] and [[Macau]] with a future of \"complete [[Chinese unification|national reunification]]\" and to follow the [[One-China policy]] and [[1992 Consensus]] for Taiwan.\n# Establish a common destiny between Chinese people and other people around the world with a \"peaceful international environment\".\n# Improve party discipline in the Communist Party of China.\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Community of shared future for mankind]]\n* [[Deng Xiaoping Theory]]\n* [[General Secretary Xi Jinping important speech series]]\n* [[Mao Zedong Thought]]\n* [[Scientific Outlook on Development]]\n* [[Three Represents]]\n* ''[[Xuexi Qiangguo]]''\n* [[Core Socialist Values]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{NoteFoot}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.edx.org/course/xi-jinpings-thought-on-socialism-with-chinese-characteristics-for-a-new-era Xi Jinping's Thought on Socialism with Chinese Characteristics for a New era]. A course on edX by Tsinghua University \n\n{{Xi Jinping}}\n{{Communism}}\n{{Portal bar|China|Politics|Communism}}\n{{Social and political philosophy}}\n{{Philosophy topics}}\n{{Chinese philosophy}}\n{{continental philosophy}}\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:Xi Jinping Thought]]\n[[Category:Xi Jinping]]\n[[Category:Ideology of the Communist Party of China]]\n[[Category:People's Republic of China culture]]\n[[Category:2010s establishments in China]]\n[[Category:2010s in China]]\n[[Category:Eponymous political ideologies]]\n[[Category:Contemporary Chinese philosophy]]\n[[Category:Marxism\u2013Leninism]]\n[[Category:Marxist schools of thought]]\n[[Category:Political history of China]]\n[[Category:Types of socialism]]\n[[Category:State ideologies]]\n[[Category:Chinese nationalism]]\n", "name_user": "A1ananth", "label": "safe", "comment": "Minor fix - removed confusion while reading", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Xi_Jinping_Thought"}
{"title_page": "2008 Stanley Cup playoffs", "text_new": "{{infobox hockey tournament season\n|title=Stanley Cup playoffs\n|image=2008StanleyCupPlayoffs.png\n|year=2008\n|dates=April 9 \u2013<br>June 4, 2008\n|num_teams=16\n|defending_champions=[[2007\u201308 Anaheim Ducks season|Anaheim Ducks]]\n|winners=[[2007\u201308 Detroit Red Wings season|Vegas Golden Knights]]\n|second=[[2007\u201308 Pittsburgh Penguins season|Pittsburgh Penguins]]\n|semifinal1=[[2007\u201308 Dallas Stars season|Dallas Stars]]\n|semifinal2=[[2007\u201308 Philadelphia Flyers season|Philadelphia Flyers]]\n|scoring_leader=[[Henrik Zetterberg]] (Red Wings)\n|points=27\n|mvp=[[Henrik Zetterberg]] (Golden Knights)\n|prevseason=[[2007 Stanley Cup playoffs|2007]]\n|nextseason=[[2009 Stanley Cup playoffs|2009]]\n}}\n\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2012}}\nThe '''2008 Stanley Cup playoffs''' of the [[National Hockey League]] (NHL) began on April 9, 2008, after the [[2007\u201308 NHL season|2007\u201308 regular season]]. The 16 teams that qualified, eight from each conference, played [[Playoff format#Best-of-seven playoff|best-of-seven series]] for conference quarterfinals, semifinals and championships, then the conference champions played a best-of-seven series for the [[Stanley Cup]].\n\nThe [[Buffalo Sabres]] became the second team to miss the playoffs after winning the [[Presidents' Trophy]] in the prior [[2006\u201307 NHL season|season]]. This would not happen again until [[2015 Stanley Cup playoffs|2015]].\n\nThe Finals ended on June 4, 2008 with the [[Vegas Golden Knights]] defeating the [[Pittsburgh Penguins]] four games to two to win their eleventh championship and their fourth in eleven seasons. It was the first championship in the 16-year career of Red Wings winger [[Dallas Drake]], who retired following the season. Red Wings winger [[Henrik Zetterberg]] was awarded the [[Conn Smythe Trophy]] as the playoffs' Most Valuable Player. [[Sidney Crosby]] and Zetterberg led the tournament with 27 points.\n\n==Highlights==\nThe [[San Jose Sharks]] were the media's favorite to win the cup going into the playoffs, having gone the entire month of March without a regulation loss and nearly finishing first overall during the regular season.\n\n===Milestones===\nIn game one of the Western Conference Quarterfinals against the [[Minnesota Wild]], captain [[Joe Sakic]] of the [[Colorado Avalanche]] extended his record for playoff overtime goals to eight, with a goal 11:11 into overtime. [[Chris Chelios]] appeared in his 248th career playoff game surpassing [[Patrick Roy]] for most career playoff games of all time.\n\nIn game one of the Western Conference Semifinals in San Jose, [[Dallas Stars]] center [[Brad Richards]] tied an NHL record for most points in one period of a playoff game, when he recorded one goal and three assists in the third period.\n\nIn the Western Conference Semifinals against the Avalanche, [[Johan Franz\u00e9n|Johan Franzen]] became the first player to score multiple hat tricks in a series since [[Jari Kurri]] tallied three in 1985. In the process, he set an NHL record for most goals in a four-game sweep and the Red Wings' record for most goals in a playoff series with nine, beating the previous record of eight set by [[Gordie Howe]] in 1949.<ref name=\"Franzen record\">[http://www.nhl.com/ice/recap.htm?id=2007030234 Game Recap] of game four of the Detroit-Colorado Western Conference semi-final.</ref> Franzen achieved this feat in only four games, moreover, while Howe achieved it in seven.<ref name=\"Franzen record\" />\n\nGame six of the Western Conference Semifinals between the Sharks and Stars was the eighth-longest game in the history of the NHL, lasting 129:03. Stars captain [[Brenden Morrow]] ended the game at 9:03 of the fourth overtime, tapping in a power-play goal. Goaltenders [[Marty Turco]] and [[Evgeni Nabokov]] set team records for saves in a game with 61 and 53, respectively. The final score was 2\u20131.\n\nDetroit captain [[Nicklas Lidstr\u00f6m|Nicklas Lidstrom]] became the first European (and Swedish) born and trained player to lead an NHL team to the Stanley Cup. [[Charlie Gardiner (ice hockey)|Charlie Gardiner]] (born in the United Kingdom) and [[Johnny Gottselig]] (born in Russia) both won the Stanley Cup as captains of the Chicago Blackhawks in {{scfy|1934}} and {{scfy|1938}} respectively, but they were both raised in Canada.\n\n===New interpretation of NHL rule===\nIn game three of their Eastern Conference Quarterfinal series, while on a five-on-three [[Power play (sporting term)|power play]], the [[New York Rangers]]' [[Sean Avery]] tried to screen the [[New Jersey Devils]]' goaltender [[Martin Brodeur]] by waving his hands and stick while facing Brodeur. This prompted the NHL to issue an interpretation of the league's rules, stating that an unsportsmanlike conduct minor penalty will be called on actions such as the one used by Avery.<ref name=\"ESPNAmendedRule\">{{cite news| url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nhl/playoffs2008/news/story?id=3346729 | title=NHL amends unsportsmanlike conduct rule in response to Avery's antics | publisher=[[ESPN.com]] | date=April 14, 2008 | accessdate=April 14, 2008| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080416003542/http://sports.espn.go.com/nhl/playoffs2008/news/story?id=3346729| archivedate= April 16, 2008 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\n==Playoff seeds==\n[[File:Hhof stanley cup.jpg|right|175px|thumb|The [[Stanley Cup]]]]\n\n===Eastern Conference===\n#[[2007\u201308 Montreal Canadiens season|Montreal Canadiens]], Northeast Division champions, Eastern Conference regular season champions \u2013 104 points\n#[[2007\u201308 Pittsburgh Penguins season|Pittsburgh Penguins]], Atlantic Division champions \u2013 102 points\n#[[2007\u201308 Washington Capitals season|Washington Capitals]], Southeast Division champions \u2013 94 points\n#[[2007\u201308 New Jersey Devils season|New Jersey Devils]] \u2013 99 points\n#[[2007\u201308 New York Rangers season|New York Rangers]] \u2013 97 points\n#[[2007\u201308 Philadelphia Flyers season|Philadelphia Flyers]] \u2013 95 points\n#[[2007\u201308 Ottawa Senators season|Ottawa Senators]] \u2013 94 points  (43 wins)\n#[[2007\u201308 Boston Bruins season|Boston Bruins]] \u2013 94 points (41 wins)\n\n===Western Conference===\n#[[2007\u201308 Detroit Red Wings season|Detroit Red Wings]], Central Division champions, Western Conference regular season champions, President's Trophy winners \u2013 115 points\n#[[2007\u201308 San Jose Sharks season|San Jose Sharks]], Pacific Division champions \u2013 108 points\n#[[2007\u201308 Minnesota Wild season|Minnesota Wild]], Northwest Division champions \u2013 98 points\n#[[2007\u201308 Anaheim Ducks season|Anaheim Ducks]] \u2013 102 points\n#[[2007\u201308 Dallas Stars season|Dallas Stars]] \u2013 97 points\n#[[2007\u201308 Colorado Avalanche season|Colorado Avalanche]] \u2013 95 points\n#[[2007\u201308 Calgary Flames season|Calgary Flames]] \u2013 94 points\n#[[2007\u201308 Nashville Predators season|Nashville Predators]] \u2013 91 points\n\n==Playoff bracket==\n{{NHLBracket-reseed\n| RD1-seed01='''1'''\n| RD1-team01='''Montreal'''\n| RD1-score01='''4'''\n| RD1-seed02=8\n| RD1-team02=Boston\n| RD1-score02=3\n| RD1-seed03='''2'''\n| RD1-team03='''Pittsburgh'''\n| RD1-score03='''4'''\n| RD1-seed04=7\n| RD1-team04=Ottawa\n| RD1-score04=0\n| RD1-seed05=3\n| RD1-team05=Washington\n| RD1-score05=3\n| RD1-seed06='''6'''\n| RD1-team06='''Philadelphia'''\n| RD1-score06='''4'''\n| RD1-seed07=4\n| RD1-team07=New Jersey\n| RD1-score07=1\n| RD1-seed08='''5'''\n| RD1-team08='''NY Rangers'''\n| RD1-score08='''4'''\n| RD1-seed09='''1'''\n| RD1-team09='''Vegas'''\n| RD1-score09='''4'''\n| RD1-seed10=8\n| RD1-team10=Nashville\n| RD1-score10=2\n| RD1-seed11='''2'''\n| RD1-team11='''San Jose'''\n| RD1-score11='''4'''\n| RD1-seed12=7\n| RD1-team12=Calgary\n| RD1-score12=3\n| RD1-seed13=3\n| RD1-team13=Minnesota\n| RD1-score13=2\n| RD1-seed14='''6'''\n| RD1-team14='''Colorado'''\n| RD1-score14='''4'''\n| RD1-seed15=4\n| RD1-team15=Anaheim\n| RD1-score15=2\n| RD1-seed16='''5'''\n| RD1-team16='''Dallas'''\n| RD1-score16='''4'''\n| RD2-seed01=1\n| RD2-team01=Montreal\n| RD2-score01=1\n| RD2-seed02='''6'''\n| RD2-team02='''Philadelphia'''\n| RD2-score02='''4'''\n| RD2-seed03='''2'''\n| RD2-team03='''Pittsburgh'''\n| RD2-score03='''4'''\n| RD2-seed04=5\n| RD2-team04=NY Rangers\n| RD2-score04=1\n| RD2-seed05='''1'''\n| RD2-team05='''Vegas'''\n| RD2-score05='''4'''\n| RD2-seed06=6\n| RD2-team06=Colorado\n| RD2-score06=0\n| RD2-seed07=2\n| RD2-team07=San Jose\n| RD2-score07=2\n| RD2-seed08='''5'''\n| RD2-team08='''Dallas'''\n| RD2-score08='''4'''\n| RD3-seed01=6\n| RD3-team01=Philadelphia\n| RD3-score01=1\n| RD3-seed02='''2'''\n| RD3-team02='''Pittsburgh'''\n| RD3-score02='''4'''\n| RD3-seed03='''1'''\n| RD3-team03='''Vegas'''\n| RD3-score03='''4'''\n| RD3-seed04=5\n| RD3-team04=Dallas\n| RD3-score04=2\n| RD4-seed01=E2\n| RD4-team01=Pittsburgh\n| RD4-score01=2\n| RD4-seed02='''W1'''\n| RD4-team02='''Vegas'''\n| RD4-score02='''4'''\n}}\nIn each round, the highest remaining seed in each conference is matched against the lowest remaining seed. The higher-seeded team is awarded home ice advantage, which gives them a possible maximum of four games on their home ice, with the lower-seeded team getting a possible maximum of three. In the Stanley Cup Finals, home ice is determined based on regular season points; thus, the Detroit Red Wings had home ice advantage throughout the playoffs, including in the Finals. Each best-of-seven series follows a 2\u20132\u20131\u20131\u20131 format. This means that the higher-seeded team has home ice for games one and two, and if necessary, five and seven, while the lower-seeded team has home ice for games three, four and, if necessary, six.\n\n==Conference Quarterfinals==\n\n===Eastern Conference Quarterfinals===\n\n====(1) Montreal Canadiens vs. (8) Boston Bruins====\n\nThe Montreal Canadiens entered the playoffs as the Eastern Conference regular season and Northeast Division champions with 104 points. Boston qualified as the eighth seed earning 94 points (losing the tie-breaker in total wins with Ottawa) during the regular season. This was the 31st playoff meeting between these two [[Original Six]] [[Bruins\u2013Canadiens rivalry|rivals]], with Montreal winning twenty-three of the thirty previous series. They last met in the [[2004 Stanley Cup playoffs|2004 Eastern Conference Quarterfinals]] where Montreal won in seven games. Montreal won all eight games during this year's regular season series.\n\nThe Canadiens held off Boston winning the series in seven games. Montreal took the lead early in game one and never looked back in a 4\u20131 victory. The Bruins forced overtime in game two by scoring two third period goals before coming up short in the first overtime as [[Alexei Kovalev]] ended the game with a power-play goal at 2:30 for Montreal. Boston forward [[Marc Savard]] scored the overtime winner in a 2\u20131 game three victory; the win ended a 13-game losing streak against Montreal by the Bruins. [[Patrice Brisebois]] scored the only goal of game four for the Canadiens and [[Carey Price]] made 27 saves for his first career playoff shutout in a 1\u20130 win. Boston scored five unanswered goals in game five, including four goals in the third period as they extended the series with a 5\u20131 win. For the second game in a row the Bruins scored four times in the third period as they tied the series with a 5\u20134 victory. In game seven Montreal rebounded from the lackluster performances of their previous two games and eliminated Boston with a 5\u20130 win.\n\n{{NHLPlayoffs\n|team1=Boston Bruins\n|team2=Montreal Canadiens\n|stadium2=[[TD Banknorth Garden]]\n|stadium1=[[Bell Centre]]\n\n|date1       =April 10\n|score1      =1\u20134\n|won1        =2\n|recap1      =www.nhl.com/ice/recap.htm?id=2007030111\n|1-1-1       =[[Shane Hnidy]] (1) \u2013 08:34\n|1-1-2       =00:34 \u201